led ''Smile Jenny, You're Dead''.<ref name=TVGuide>{{cite web|url=https://www.tvguide.com/celebrities/andrea-marcovicci/credits/139575/|title=Andrea Marcovicci|website=TVGuide.com|publisher=[[TV Guide]]|access-date=25 April 2020}}</ref She was nominated for a [[Golden Globe Award for New Star Of The Year - Actress|Golden Globe award for the New Star of the Year]] in 1977 for the film, ''[[The Front]]'' (1976).\n\nMarcovicci had a recurring role on ''[[Hill Street Blues]]''.<ref name=TVGuide></ref> She has appeared on ''[[Scarecrow and Mrs. King]],'' ''[[Kojak]],''<ref name=TVGuide></ref> ''[[The Incredible Hulk (1978 TV series)|The Incredible Hulk]],''<ref name=TVGuide></ref> ''[[Magnum, P.I.]],'' ''[[Cybill]],'' ''[[Arli$$]],'' ''[[Taxi (TV series)|Taxi]],'' ''[[Voyagers!]]'' (as [[Cleopatra]]), ''[[Baretta]],'' ''[[Mannix]]'', and ''[[Paul Sand in Friends and Lovers]]''. She starred on both ''[[Trapper John, M.D.]]'' and ''[[Berrenger's]].''<ref name=TVGuide></ref>\n\nMarcovicci appeared onstage on [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] in ''[[Ambassador (musical)|Ambassador]]''. Her film roles include ''[[The Concorde ... Airport '79]]'' (1979), ''[[Spacehunter: Adventures in the Forbidden Zone]]'' (1983) and ''[[Jack the Bear]]'' (1993).\n\nIn 2008 Marcovicci celebrated her 22nd season at the legendary [[Oak Room (Algonquin Hotel)|Oak Room]] of the [[Algonquin Hotel]] with ''Marcovicci Sings Movies II.'' A very special 60th Birthday concert followed in May 2009 at Town Hall in NYC, celebrating Andrea\u2019s contribution to the American Songbook. To commemorate this event her personal record label, Andreasong Recordings, Inc., released a compilation CD titled ''As Time Goes By: The Best of Andrea Marcovicci,'' her 17th album and/or CD.\n\nAt the end of 2011, Marcovicci celebrated her 25th season at the Oak Room with \"No Strings\", a collection of songs about travel. Her closing performance of \"No Strings\" was the final cabaret event at the Oak Room, as the Algonquin's new owner decided to turn the space into a lounge for \"preferred\" customers.<ref name=npr>{{cite web|last=Lunden|first=Jeff|title=Requiem For A Cabaret: The Oak Room Closes|url=https://www.npr.org/2012/05/31/153720369/requiem-for-a-cabaret-the-oak-room-closes|work=npr.org|publisher=npr|accessdate=7 September 2013}}</ref>\n\nMarcovicci celebrated her 65th birthday, November 18, 2013, by playing two shows at Joe's Pub, part of the Public Theater.\n\n== Awards ==\nShe is the recipient of several awards and honors including the Mabel Mercer Foundation\u2019s 2007 Mabel Award and three Lifetime Achievement Awards\u2014honored by the Manhattan Association of Cabarets and Clubs, the Licia Albanese-Puccini Foundation, and by a Bob Harrington Backstage Bistro Award. In recognition of her accomplishments in the arts, Andrea has received honorary degrees from [[Trinity College (Connecticut)|Trinity College]] in Hartford, CT and the [[Memphis College of Art]]. In addition, \"The Andrea Marcovicci Suite\" at the Algonquin Hotel, dedicated in 2006 on her twentieth anniversary at the Oak Room, contains memorabilia of her work in theatre, film, television, and on the concert stage.\n\n== Personal life ==\nShe married actor Daniel Reichert in 1993. The couple separated in 2004, and are now divorced. They have a daughter, Alice Wolfe Reichert.<ref name=Tribune>{{cite news|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1999-12-26/features/9912260082_1_bora-bora-greta-garbo-orchestra-hall |author=Cheryl Lavin |title=Andrea Marcovicci|newspaper=The [[Chicago Tribune]]|date=26 December 1999|accessdate=15 May 2010}}</ref>\n\n== Partial filmography ==\n* ''Cry Rape'' (1973) (TV) - Betty Jenner\n* ''[[Thriller (British TV series)|Thriller]]'' (1975) (TV) - Ruth Harrow\n* ''[[The Front]]'' (1976) - Florence Barrett\n* ''[[A Vacation In Hell]]''  (1979) - Barbara\n* ''[[The Concorde ... Airport '79]]'' (1979) - Alicia Rogov\n* ''[[The Hand (1981 film)|The Hand]]'' (1981) - Anne Lansdale\n* ''[[Magnum, P.I.]]'' (1981) (TV) - Kendall Chase / Amy Crane / Carol Foster\n* ''[[Kings and Desperate Men]]'' (1981) - Terrorist\n* ''[[Spacehunter: Adventures in the Forbidden Zone]]'' (1983) - Chalmers\n* ''[[The Stuff]]'' (1985) -  Nicole\n* ''[[The Canterville Ghost (1986 film)|The Canterville Ghost]]'' (1986) - Lucy Canterville\n* ''[[Someone to Love (1987 film)|Someone to Love]]'' (1987) - Helen Eugene\n* ''[[The Water Engine]]'' (1992) (TV) - Singer in dance hall\n* ''[[Jack the Bear]]'' (1993) - Elizabeth Leary\n* ''[[Irene in Time]]'' (2009) - Helen Dean\n* ''Driving by Braille'' (2011) - Clare Robles\n* ''[[Baskets (TV series)|Baskets]]'' (2019) (TV) - Tammy\n\n== Discography ==\n* ''Marcovicci Sings Movies'' (1987)\n* ''I'll Be Seeing You: Love Songs of World War II'' (1991)\n*  [[December Songs ]](1992)\n* ''[[What Is Love? (Andrea Marcovicci album)|What Is Love?]]'' (1992)\n* ''Just Kern'' (1992)\n* ''Always Irving Berlin'' (1995)\n* ''New Words'' (1996)\n* ''I Am Anne Frank'' (1997)\n* ''Live from London'' (1998)\n* ''Some Other Time: Sings Mabel Marcer'' (1998)\n* ''Here There & Everywhere'' (2000)\n* ''How's Your Romance?'' (2004)\n* ''If I Were a Bell'' (2005)\n* ''My Christmas Song for You'' (2007)\n* ''Andrea Sings Astaire'' (2007)\n* ''Sings Rodgers & Hart'' (2007)\n* ''Smile'' (2012)\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website|www.andreamarcovicci.com}}\n* {{IMDb name|0546004}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Marcovicci, Andrea}}\n[[Category:1948 births]]\n[[Category:American female singers]]\n[[Category:American film actresses]]\n[[Category:American television actresses]]\n[[Category:American people of Romanian descent]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Manhattan]]\n[[Category:Traditional pop music singers]]\n[[Category:Singers from New York City]]\n[[Category:Actresses from New York City]]\n", "name_user": "PumpkinButter", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eBiography:typo", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Andrea_Marcovicci"}
{"title_page": "Development of stadiums in English football", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2018}}\nA large number of English football clubs have ongoing schemes to redevelop existing grounds, or to move to newly constructed stadiums. A trend towards all-seater stadiums was initially prescribed by the [[Taylor Report]], and was originally a condition only of [[Premier League]] admission. It has now become a requirement that within three years of a club's first promotion to [[Football League Championship|the Championship]] all paying spectators are seated, even if the club is subsequently relegated. This page provides an (incomplete) list and description of those clubs who have planned new stadiums or refurbishments, or who have already moved/refurbished since around the time of the Taylor Report.\n\nThe following list includes clubs that are based in [[Wales]] but play in the [[English football league system]].\n\n==History==\nWhen [[Scunthorpe United F.C.|Scunthorpe United]] moved to [[Glanford Park]] in 1988, it was the first time a [[The Football League|Football League]] club had moved to a new purpose-built home since 1956.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/chesters-grounds-for-hope-built-in-just-30-weeks-the-deva-stadium-has-allowed-frustrated-fans-to-welcome-their-team-home-from-exile-1542436.html|title=Chester's grounds for hope|newspaper=The Independent|date=25 August 1992|accessdate=19 May 2010|location=London|first=Phil|last=Shaw}}</ref> Up to this point, most sides were playing in grounds that had been largely structurally unchanged for most of the 20th century. One of the few clubs to play in a completely rebuilt post [[World War II]] stadium was [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]], whose stadium had been rebuilt due to bomb damage during the war, and significantly altered in the 1960s and again in the early 1980s.\n\nGround improvements were seldom, most clubs rarely reached their capacity on a regular basis, and poor facilities were commonplace \u2013 this particularly being the case between 1979 and 1986, when attendances fell, with this fall in spectators being blamed largely on increased [[Football hooliganism|hooliganism]], as well as the [[Early 1980s recession|economic downturn]] and sharp rise in unemployment that occurred in the early 1980s. The main source of income came from gate receipts, and most additional money was spent on transfers. It was not until the growing concern in the 1980s about the safety of existing stadiums, that clubs began to examine the possibilities offered by redeveloping their grounds. This was first highlighted in May 1985, when 56 fans were burnt to death [[Bradford City stadium fire|in a fire]] at the [[Bradford City F.C.|Bradford City]] stadium, and even more so in the aftermath of the [[Hillsborough disaster]] of April 1989, which led to the death of 96 [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] fans at an [[FA Cup]] semi-final. Poor maintenance was seen as the main reason for the fire at Bradford, while the presence of perimeter fencing and standing areas (as well as loss of police control) were seen as the main factors in the Hillsborough tragedy.\n\nIn January 1990, the [[Taylor Report]] recommended the conversion of all [[Football League]] stadiums to all-seater arenas<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.footballnetwork.org/dev/communityfootball/violence_taylor_report.asp |title=The Taylor Report |publisher=Footballnetwork.org |date=15 April 1989 |accessdate=13 October 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080415180944/http://www.footballnetwork.org/dev/communityfootball/violence_taylor_report.asp |archivedate=15 April 2008 }}</ref> although this was subsequently applied just to the top two levels with effect from the [[1994-95 in English football|1994\u201395 season]]. The report had ordered third and fourth tier teams to follow suit by 1999, but clubs at this level were allowed to continue with standing accommodation.\n\nThis was given governmental financial assistance, and while unpopular with many fans, attendances began to rise again in the 1990s.\n\nThe new all-seater arrangement tended to be more popular with both the clubs and football authorities, as they had the combined benefits of being safer and more profitable.\n\nThe boom in television rights following the creation of the [[Premier League]] in 1992 allowed a number of clubs to further expand their stadiums, or even move to new ones. Realising the commercial possibilities of new stadiums, many ambitious outfits constructed purpose-built stadiums often on the outskirts of cities or in urban regeneration areas. It has become common for clubs to tie these new stadiums in with residential or leisure complexes.\n\nA number of lower-league clubs had plans for ground improvements halted following the collapse of [[ITV Digital]] and the lucrative broadcasting contract they had agreed.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/business/1896732.stm |title=BUSINESS &#124; ITV Digital goes broke |work=BBC News |date=27 March 2002 |accessdate=14 April 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/business/1961343.stm |title=BUSINESS &#124; The fallout from ITV Digital's collapse |work=BBC News |date=1 May 2002 |accessdate=14 April 2010}}</ref> Following the re-sale of rights, a number of these programmes have been re-activated in recent years, and some of the heaviest stadium redevelopment has been in the lower divisions. Most teams with ambitions of eventual promotion to the Premier League have plans for continued work on their grounds to bring them up to an appropriate standard. Even the biggest clubs have been affected, [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] have heavily rebuilt and expanded [[Old Trafford]] since 1992, while [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] moved to the [[Emirates Stadium]] in 2006.\n\nIn 2015, every stadium in England have to adhere to Accessible Stadia guideline, which each clubs are required to have a certain minimum number of amenity and easy access spaces with accessible toilets. Since then most of England stadium have more accessibility for disabled.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://disabilityhorizons.com/2019/05/accessible-football-stadiums-reviewed-part-1/|title=Accessible football stadiums reviewed by wheelchair user and football fan|date=2019-05-01|website=Disability Horizons|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-01-14}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://sgsa.org.uk/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/Accessible-Stadia-Supplementary-Guidance.pdf|title=Accessible Stadia Supplementary guidance|last=|first=|publisher=Sports Ground Safety Authority|year=2015|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref>\n\nUnder the bullet ''Current stadium status'' below, \"New\" means built after 1988 and replacing a former venue, while \"Reconstructed\" means the club has merely made improvements to their stadium.\n\n{{Expand list|date=August 2008}}\n\n==Premier League==\n===AFC Bournemouth===\n\n* Stadium: [[Dean Court|Vitality Stadium]] \n* Capacity: 11,364<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|url=https://premierleague-static-files.s3.amazonaws.com/premierleague/document/2019/08/02/add6ee50-25c6-4474-8854-edf8a56c23c1/2019-20-PL-Handbook-020819.pdf|title=Premier League Handbook Season 2019/20|last=|first=|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref>\n*''Current stadium status'': Reconstructed.\n[[A.F.C. Bournemouth|Bournemouth's]] [[Dean Court]] ground was completely rebuilt in 2001, with the pitch rotated ninety degrees from its original position. The stadium was also moved away from adjacent housing. Although it was rebuilt as a three sided stadium, seats were placed on the undeveloped South End in the autumn of 2005. These seats were removed when the club was relegated to the bottom tier in 2008 but installed once more following promotion back to League One in 2010. Following promotion to the [[Sky Bet Championship]] in 2013 the club installed a larger, roofed temporary stand, bringing the total ground capacity just shy of 12,000. This was named after club legend, the [[Ted MacDougall]] Stand. After a successful debut [[Premier League]] campaign, the club submitted a planning application to Bournemouth Borough Council to redevelop the temporary Ted MacDougall Stand with a much larger one which would take the capacity of the ground to 14,529.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.afcb.co.uk/news/article/south-stand-afc-bournemouth-stadium-expansion-plans-3012635.aspx|title=South Stand: See the full plans for AFC Bournemouth's potential South Stand development|last=afcb.co.uk|access-date=19 January 2017}}</ref> However these plans have been put on hold and just nine months later the club announced that they were seeking a new site on which to build a new stadium, with a view to being ready for the 2020/21 season.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.afcb.co.uk/news/article/2016-17/club-statement-afc-bournemouth-vitality-stadium-3459607.aspx|title=Club statement: AFC Bournemouth chief executive Neill Blake makes statement on Vitality Stadium|last=afcb.co.uk|access-date=19 January 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Arsenal===\n\n* Stadium: [[Emirates Stadium]]\n* Capacity: 60,704<ref name=\":0\" />\n*''Current stadium status'': New.\n[[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] moved to the [[Emirates Stadium]] in 2006, which has massively boosted club income.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/a/arsenal/7009944.stm |title=BBC SPORT &#124; Football &#124; My Club &#124; Arsenal &#124; Arsenal bullish over \u00a3200m income |work=BBC News |date=24 September 2007 |accessdate=14 April 2010}}</ref> At present, the capacity is 60,355 (seated), with currently no public plans to expand it despite strong average attendances of 60,025 in the Premier League. Emirates Stadium is the third largest club ground in England, after Old Trafford and Tottenham\u2018s new White Hart Lane. The Emirates replaced [[Arsenal Stadium|Highbury]], where the club had been based since 1913, which itself had been substantially updated in the early 1990s and reduced capacity from 59,000 to an all-seater 38,500 by 1993. However, this was deemed inadequate by 1998 and led to the club's directors deciding that relocation was necessary, prompting the club to build a new stadium, with the site at Ashburton Grove being selected in November 1999 (after a bid to buy [[Wembley Stadium]] failed) and work beginning in the spring of 2004. It finally opened for the [[2006-07 in English football|2006\u201307 season]].\n\n===Aston Villa===\n\n* Stadium: [[Villa Park]]\n* Capacity: 42,095<ref name=\":0\" />\n*''Current stadium status'': Reconstructed.\n[[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]] have planning permission to increase [[Villa Park]] from 42,000 to 50,000 seats by expanding the North Stand. Villa Park has been all-seater since 1994, when the Holte End was rebuilt, but did not reach its current capacity until the Trinity Road Stand was rebuilt in the [[2000-01 in English football|2000\u201301 season]]. No major developments have taken place since, although plans have been in the pipeline since the late 1990s to take the stadium's capacity to more than 50,000\n\n===Brighton and Hove Albion===\n\n* Stadium: [[Falmer Stadium|The American Express Community Stadium]]\n* Capacity: 30,750<ref name=\":0\" />\n*''Current stadium status'': New.\n\nBrighton's 14-year wait for a permanent home came to an end when Brighton moved to [[Falmer Stadium]], in 2011, with a capacity of 22,000 seats. The stadium had built into its design the ability to have capacity increased to 30,750, which has been completed as of the end of the 2012\u201313 season. This has been done by filling in all four corners of the stadium and adding an extra tier to the top of the East Stand. Extra corporate boxes and hospitality suites have also been added to the existing South Stand mezzanine, and the 1901 Club West Stand middle tier has been extended around each corner.\n\nBrighton had been without a permanent home since May 1997, when they left the [[Goldstone Ground]] after 95 years after it was sold to a developer in an effort to ease the club's financial crisis. Two seasons were spent ground-sharing with [[Gillingham F.C.|Gillingham]] before the club returned to Brighton to a temporary home at [[Withdean Athletics Stadium]], although the aim from the outset was to build a new stadium in the Falmer area.\n\n===Burnley===\n\n* Stadium: [[Turf Moor]]\n* Capacity: 21,944<ref name=\":0\" />\n*''Current stadium status'': Reconstructed.\n\nSince consolidating their place in the [[Premier League]], [[Burnley F.C.|Burnley]] have made several structural and cosmetic improvements to [[Turf Moor]].\nWork has been completed outside the stadium including new a new club shop and corporate facilities, and work has begun building two purpose-built corner stands between the James Hargreaves, [[Jimmy McIlroy]] and [[Bob Lord (football chairman)|Bob Lord]] stands that will house disabled supporters. This work is due to be completed in time for the 2018\u201319 season.\n\n===Chelsea===\n\n* Stadium: [[Stamford Bridge (stadium)|Stamford Bridge]]\n* Capacity: 40,834<ref name=\":0\" />\n*''Current stadium status'': Reconstructed. Reconstruction on hold indefinitely.\n\nFollowing [[Roman Abramovich]]'s takeover, [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]] have examined expanding their current home at [[Stamford Bridge (stadium)|Stamford Bridge]] to a capacity of over 50,000.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/c/chelsea/4630618.stm |title=BBC SPORT &#124; Football &#124; My Club &#124; Chelsea &#124; Chelsea plan Bridge redevelopment |work=BBC News |date=20 January 2006 |accessdate=14 April 2010}}</ref> Numerous problems over health and safety issues have stalled this, because due to the stadium's location fans can only exit onto the [[Fulham Road]].<ref>{{cite book | author=Glanvill | year=2006 | title=Chelsea FC: The Official Biography | page=76}}</ref> The club have thus been linked with moves to a number of potential sites in west [[London]], including a site at [[Earl's Court]], although the club have indicated no such plans exist.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.mirrorfootball.co.uk/news/Chelsea-have-reiterated-their-desire-to-stay-at-Stamford-Bridge-claiming-history-and-tradition-outweigh-the-desire-for-bigger-crowds-article596067.html |title=Chelsea rule out move from the Bridge |newspaper=Daily Mirror |date=7 October 2010 |accessdate=15 March 2011}}</ref> A further stumbling block is that the club's [[naming rights]] are owned by the [[Chelsea Pitch Owners]], which also owns the Stamford Bridge [[Freehold (law)|freehold]]. As a condition for using the Chelsea FC name, the club has to play its first team matches at Stamford Bridge. A move to a new stadium could mean the club having to change their name.<ref>{{cite book | author=Glanvill | year=2006 | title=Chelsea FC: The Official Biography | pages=91\u201392}}</ref> Stamford Bridge was extensively rebuilt between 1993 and 1998, with three stands being replaced and the circular track between the pitch and stands being removed, and the only pre-1993 stand at the stadium being the 1974 East Stand structure. This achieved a 34,000 all-seater capacity which had been given the go-ahead in July 1990. The current capacity of just under 42,000 was reached in 2001.\n\nIn November 2015, Chelsea Football Club announced that they have submitted plans to the Local Authority to build a new 60,000 seater stadium on the Stamford Bridge site, which would match the current capacity of Arsenal's Emirates Stadium and only be surpassed by Old Trafford, and Tottenham's new stadium in the Premier League.\n\n===Crystal Palace===\n\n* Stadium: [[Selhurst Park|Selhurt Park]]\n* Capacity: 25,486<ref name=\":0\" />\n*''Current stadium status'': Reconstructed.\n\nIn January 2011, [[Crystal Palace F.C.|Crystal Palace]] announced plans to move from their run-down [[Selhurst Park]] home to return to the [[Crystal Palace National Sports Centre]] (on the site of the original ground the club left in 1915, a stadium that also hosted the [[FA Cup final]] from 1895 to 1914). The plans involve demolishing the existing structure and redeveloping it into a 40,000-seater [[Crystal Palace Park (stadium)|purpose-built football stadium]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cpfc.co.uk/page/News/0,,10323~2271669,00.html |title=Eagles Fly Home |publisher=Crystal Palace F.C. |work=cpfc.co.uk |date=28 June 2011 |accessdate=4 November 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110907152719/http://www.cpfc.co.uk/page/News/0%2C%2C10323~2271669%2C00.html |archivedate=7 September 2011 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.]] also released plans to redevelop the NSC into a 25,000-seater stadium, maintaining it as an athletics stadium, as part of their plans to redevelop the [[Olympic Stadium (London)|Olympic Stadium]] after the [[2012 Summer Olympics]] and [[2012 Summer Paralympics|Paralympics]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goal.com/en-gb/news/2896/premier-league/2011/01/28/2327743/tottenham-release-images-of-proposed-crystal-palace |title=Tottenham release images of proposed Crystal Palace Athletics Stadium |publisher=Goal.com |date=28 January 2011 |accessdate=4 November 2011}}</ref> However, Spurs' failure to secure the site, which instead went to [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]] has left the road clear for Palace to pursue the site.\n\nTheir current [[Selhurst Park]] home has been all-seater since the mid 1990s, holding more than 26,000 spectators. In December 2017, the club announced plans to undertake a redevelopment of the Main Stand at Selhurst Park, raising the capacity to approximately 34,000, with the new structure ready by 2021.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/sport/football/crystal-palace-reveal-plan-to-build-new-100m-main-stand-at-selhurst-park-a3709841.html |title=Crystal Palace reveal plan to build new \u00a3100m main stand at Selhurst Park |last=Muro |first=Giuseppe |date=4 December 2017 |website=standard.co.uk |publisher=Evening Standard |access-date=29 January 2018 |quote=}}</ref>\n\n===Everton===\n\n* Stadium: [[Goodison Park]]\n* Capacity: 39,414<ref name=\":0\" />\n*''Current stadium status:'' Reconstructed.\n\n[[Everton F.C.|Everton]] were planning to relocate to a [[Everton Kirkby Project|new stadium]] in [[Kirkby]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/merseyside/7168024.stm |title=England &#124; Merseyside &#124; Everton submit new stadium plans |work=BBC News |date=2 January 2008 |accessdate=14 April 2010}}</ref> This generated a large amount of controversy,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nsno.co.uk/news.php?item.2426.1 |title=Nil Satis Nisi Optimum: Keep Everton in Our City |publisher=Nsno.co.uk |date=31 March 1906 |accessdate=13 October 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080305073134/http://www.nsno.co.uk/news.php?item.2426.1 |archivedate=5 March 2008 }}</ref> as it was beyond the city limits of [[Liverpool]]. In June 2008 Kirkby council approved the new stadium, however, following a public inquiry that was held in December 2008, the stadium was rejected by the Secretary of State in November 2009.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/news/liverpool-news/everton-fcs-plans-50000-seater-3457040|title=Everton FC's plans for a 50,000-seater stadium could by delayed by a year|date=14 March 2009|newspaper=Liverpool Echo|accessdate=13 October 2013}}</ref>\n\nIt is planned to have 50,401 seats initially, with potential to increase to 60,000 at a later date. The club's current stadium has been all-seater (with a capacity of just over 40,000) since 1994, when a new stand was built at one end of the ground. The Main Stand was built in 1970, while the two remaining stands are refurbished interwar structures.\n\nThe first plans for relocation were announced in 1996. A site at [[King's Dock, Port of Liverpool|King's Dock]] was identified and bid for in 2000, with a view to building a new stadium with 55,000 to 60,000 seats.<ref>{{cite news|title=Goodison exit moves ever closer|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/e/everton/959934.stm|work=BBC Sport|date=6 October 2000|accessdate=15 November 2012}}</ref> These plans were then shelved in 2003 when chairman [[Bill Kenwright]] said that the club could not raise adequate funds.<ref>{{cite news|title=Everton move off|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/2399479/Everton-move-off.html|work=The Telegraph|date=11 April 2003|accessdate=15 November 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Leicester City===\n\n* Stadium: [[King Power Stadium]]\n* Capacity: 32,261<ref name=\":0\" />\n*''Current stadium status'': New.\n\nLeicester have announced plans to extend the King Power Stadium to 42,000 seats.<ref name=\"foxes\">{{cite web|title=Leicester City could increase capacity at the King Power Stadium to 42,000|url=http://www.leicestermercury.co.uk/Leicester-City-increase-capacity-King-Power/story-26656839-detail/story.html|website=Leicester Mercury|accessdate=5 April 2016|date=8 June 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160102235844/http://www.leicestermercury.co.uk/Leicester-City-increase-capacity-King-Power/story-26656839-detail/story.html|archive-date=2 January 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> The owners announced in June 2015 that they had begun the application for permission to build. This expansion plan will most likely extend the east stand, and possibly the south stand (Kop) into 2-tier stands.\n\nThe club have played at their 32,500-seat stadium since relocating from nearby [[Filbert Street]] in 2002. They had spent 111 years at Filbert Street and converted it into an all-seater format in 1993 with the construction of one new stand and the refurbishment of the three others, but a run of success in the top flight prompted demand for tickets vastly outstripping supply, and the stadium's confined location made expansion difficult, so by 1998 the decision was made to build a new stadium. However, the relocation to a new stadium took place in the same year as relegation from the Premier League, putting a huge strain on the club's finances and leading to a spell in [[Receivership|administration]] as debts reached more than \u00a330million.\n\n===Liverpool===\n\n* Stadium: [[Anfield]]\n* Capacity: 53,394<ref name=\":0\" />\n*''Current stadium status'': Reconstructed. 7,000 Anfield Road expansion plan.\n\nIn May 2002, [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] announced plans to build a new 55,000-seat [[Stanley Park Stadium|stadium]] in [[Stanley Park, Liverpool|Stanley Park]], near their current [[Anfield]] home.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/liverpool/content/articles/2007/11/07/liverpoolfc.shtml |title=Liverpool's new stadium in Stanley Park moves a step closer |publisher=BBC |date=7 November 2007 |accessdate=14 April 2010 |first=Simon |last=Moffatt}}</ref> The stadium's planned capacity was then increased to more than 66,000, with preliminary construction beginning in 2007.\n\nAnfield has been all-seater since the mid-1990s, when the Spion Kop was rebuilt two years after the completion of the Centenary Stand on the southern side of the stadium. The Main Stand dates back to the early 1970s, while the Anfield Road Stand was already all-seater when it was rebuilt in 1997.\n\nConstruction of the new stadium, however, was halted in 2008 due to lack of funds combined with the [[Late 2000s recession|onset of the recession]].\n\nThe relocation was first proposed in 2000, when the club had been hoping to have a 70,000-seat stadium ready for the 2004\u201305 season. In May 2002 it was decided that relocation was a more viable option than expansion, when the plans were amended for a less expensive 55,000-seat stadium to be built.\n\n<span>In April 2014 Liverpool F.C. signed a legal agreement with Liverpool City Council and Your Housing Group to redevelop the surrounding Anfield area. This is seen as a significant step towards the renovation of the stadium. The redevelopment was worth around \u00a3260 million.</span><ref>{{cite news| title=Liverpool sign heads of terms on road to Anfield stadium redevelopment | first=Andy|last=Hunter|work=The Guardian|date=17 April 2014|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2014/apr/17/liverpool-heads-of-terms-anfield-stadium-redevelopment |accessdate=18 April 2014 }}</ref><span> On 9 September 2016, the first phase of expansion was completed, bringing the total capacity 54,047. On 10 September, the newly renovated Anfield was opened for its first use in a [[Premier League]] game against [[Leicester City F.C.|Leicester City]]. Plans to expand the Anfield Road stand have been announced to increase the capacity to over 60,000. However, as of yet these plans have not been officially published.</span>\n\nAnfield Road expansion plan were allowed to be expired on September 2019<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thisisanfield.com/2019/11/photos-how-anfield-will-change-as-liverpool-release-images-of-anfield-road-end-plans/|title=PHOTOS: How Liverpool's Anfield Road end expansion will look|date=2019-11-29|website=This Is Anfield|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-12-18}}</ref> and Liverpool resubmitted a new \u00a360M plan which will push Anfield capacity into 61,000. The expansion plan includes granting permission of permanent hosting concert and other major events such as American Football<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.liverpoolfc.com/news/announcements/375238-liverpool-fc-launches-public-consultation-anfield-road-expansion|title=LFC launches first-stage public consultation on proposed Anfield Road Stand expansion|website=Liverpool FC|access-date=2019-12-18}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newcivilengineer.com/latest/liverpool-fc-submits-plans-60m-stadium-expansion-03-12-2019/|title=Liverpool FC submits plans for \u00a360M stadium expansion|last=Stein|first=Joshua|date=2019-12-03|website=New Civil Engineer|language=en|access-date=2019-12-18}}</ref>\n\n===Manchester City===\n\n* Stadium: [[City of Manchester Stadium|Etihad Stadium]]\n* Capacity: 55,017<ref name=\":0\" />\n*''Current stadium status'': New \u2013 expansion to 54,000 completed August 2015.\n\nCity have played at the [[City of Manchester Stadium]] since 2003 (it was completed for the [[2002 Commonwealth Games|previous year's]] [[Commonwealth Games]]) and for the previous 80 years had played at [[Maine Road]], which had been converted into an all-seater format during the 1990s with the construction of two new stands, giving it a capacity of just over 35,000, although in its early days it had held crowds of more than 80,000.\n\nThe decision to relocate to the City of Manchester Stadium was made in 1997, in place of previous plans for Maine Road to be expanded to 45,000 seats, which had initially been postponed a year earlier due to City's relegation.\n\nManchester City were taken over by the [[Abu Dhabi United Group]] in September 2008, and quickly earmarked land around Eastlands for redevelopment. A memorandum of understanding has since been formed with Manchester City Council, and City jointly own 200 acres of land in the vicinity of Eastlands.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Club statement: East Manchester|url=http://www.mcfc.co.uk/news/club-news/2011/march/club-announcement-east-mcr |work=mcfc.co.uk|publisher=Manchester City F.C.|date=3 March 2011}}</ref> In July 2011, the City of Manchester Stadium was renamed the Etihad Stadium which would help fund the redevelopment.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Revealed: Sporting mecca at the heart of Etihad's record sponsorship of Manchester City|url=http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/greater-manchester-news/revealed-sporting-mecca-at-the-heart-of-etihads-865129|work=Manchester Evening News|publisher=Trinity Mirror|date=9 July 2011|first=Deborah|last=Linton}}</ref> The first developments include a new state-of-the-art training complex for Manchester City and the local community is to be built nearby the Etihad Stadium with a centrepiece bridge linking the complex to the stadium.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Our Proposal |url=http://www.cityfootballacademy.co.uk/the-vision/our-plans/ |work=cityfootballacademy.co.uk |accessdate=13 October 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20131013164502/http://www.cityfootballacademy.co.uk/the-vision/our-plans/ |archivedate=13 October 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nAfter two seasons with virtually every league match selling out, City announced that they were in the process of applying for planning permission for an expansion of approximately 13,500 seats, which would make the ground the second largest club ground in the [[United Kingdom]], and the seventh largest stadium of any type in the same, at approximately 61,000 total seats.<ref>{{Cite news |title=MCFC invites fans to join stadium expansion waiting list |url=http://www.mcfc.co.uk/News/Club-news/2013/October/Stadium-waiting-list |work=mcfc.co.uk |date=10 October 2013}}</ref>\n\nAfter receiving planning permission for stadium expansion on 14 February 2014, City announced their intention to begin construction of a third tier of seating on the South Stand only.<ref name=\"expansionstatement\">{{cite web |url=http://www.mcfc.co.uk/News/Club-news/2014/February/Club-statement-14-February? |title=Club Statement 14 February |date=14 February 2014 |accessdate=14 February 2014}}</ref> Although they noted that permission has been received for expansion to the North Stand along with further pitch-side seating, the club is at present holding off on these projects.<ref name=\"expansionstatement\" /> With the South Stand expansion adding approximately 6,250 seats, the new capacity of the stadium after construction will be just above 54,000.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-manchester-26168685 |title=Manchester City's Etihad Stadium expansion approved |date=13 February 2014 |accessdate=14 February 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2015, the 7,000 seat third tier on the South Stand was completed, in time for the start of the 2015\u201316 football season. The expansion was designed to be in keeping with the existing roof design. A North Stand third tier has planning approval and work on it is expected to begin by 2017, increasing capacity to around 61,000.\n\n===Manchester United===\n\n* Stadium: [[Old Trafford]]\n* Capacity: 74,879<ref>{{Cite book|title=Premier League Handbook 2018/19|last=|first=|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref>\n*''Current stadium status'': Reconstructed.\n\nSince 1992, [[Old Trafford]] has undergone a massive facelift converting the stadium into a 76,000 all-seater, the largest club stadium in the [[United Kingdom]].\n\nOld Trafford has been United's home since 1910, and after decades of gradual development (and a complete rebuild following bomb damage in [[World War II]]) became largely all-seater in the [[1992-93 in English football|1992\u20131993 season]] when the Stretford End was rebuilt, and completely all-seater the following season once the Scoreboard Paddock had been converted, giving it the country's largest capacity at club level with more than 45,000 seats, although demand for tickets vastly outstripped supply. Further redevelopment took place in [[1995-96 in English football|1995\u201396]] when the 30-year-old North Stand was bulldozed to make way for a new three-tier structure. The other two stands at Old Trafford were expanded in the [[1999-2000 in English football|1999\u20132000 season]] and the latest expansion took place in [[2006-07 in English football|2006\u201307]] with the enlargement of seating in the quadrants. There have been proposals for the South Stand to become triple-tiered; also this would increase the capacity to 92,300 (a higher capacity than even Wembley Stadium); however, the railway station and tracks have hindered such ideas and seem to be on ice for the foreseeable future. If this expansion did take place, it would even allow for attendances that were not seen in the days when Old Trafford had standing areas.\n\n===Newcastle United===\n\n* Stadium: [[St James' Park]]\n* Capacity: 52,305<ref name=\":0\" />\n*''Current stadium status'': Reconstructed.\n\nIn 2007 under the chairmanship of [[Freddy Shepherd]], [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]] announced plans to increase the capacity of [[St James' Park]] by 8,000 to 60,000 by rebuilding the Gallowgate End as part of a \u00a3300m scheme to redevelop the stadium and its surrounding area.<ref>\n{{cite news\n | title =Newcastle announce ground plans\n | work =[[BBC News]]\n | publisher =[[bbc.co.uk]]\n | date =2 April 2007\n | url =http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/n/newcastle_united/6517989.stm\n | accessdate =2 April 2007}}</ref> This would cure [[St James' Park]] of its current lopsided appearance.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.footballgroundguide.com/newcastle_united.htm |title=The Internet Football Grounds Guide \u2013 St James Park, Newcastle United |publisher=Footballgroundguide.com |accessdate=14 April 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110519180422/http://www.footballgroundguide.com/newcastle_united.htm |archivedate=19 May 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> The plans appeared to have been shelved upon the 2007 takeover and review of the club by [[Mike Ashley (businessman)|Mike Ashley]], who subsequently announced in 2008 he would be selling the club. The club had trouble selling out games in the 2008\u201309 season as Newcastle headed towards relegation after 16 years in the Premier League, and also in the promotion winning campaign of 2009\u201310, as they played at a lower level.\n\nSt James's Park was initially revamped between 1992 and 1995 to give it a 36,000-seat capacity, but the most recent expansion did not take place until 1999\u20132000, in time for the 2000\u201301 season. In 1995, with demand for tickets exceeding the initial all-seater capacity, there had been plans relocate to a new 50,000-seat stadium at [[Castle Leazes]], but these were abandoned in favour of expanding the existing stadium.\n\n===Norwich City===\n\n* Stadium: [[Carrow Road]]\n* Capacity: 27,359<ref name=\":0\" />\n*''Current stadium status'': Reconstructed.\n\n[[Norwich City F.C.|Norwich City]] increased the capacity of [[Carrow Road]] to 27,000 over the Summer of 2010; nearly 20 years after the conversion to an all-seater stadium had given it a capacity of more than 21,000. There are plans to further expand Carrow Road by around 8,000 either by the redevelopment of the Geoffrey Watling City Stand or by adding a second tier to the Jarrold Stand, taking the capacity to around 35,000 seats. The initial conversion to an all-seater capacity in the early 1990s saw the stadium have more than 21,000 seats.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/n/norwich/9366650.stm|title=Norwich City consider full-on push for promotion|date=19 January 2011|publisher=BBC|accessdate=8 March 2012}}</ref> The club confirmed in September 2012 that the feasibility of a 7,000-seat development has been backed by the [[University of East Anglia]], based on factors such as \"population growth, and real numbers, such as socio-economic data, and not instinct or intuition.\"<ref name=\"EDP\">{{cite news|url=http://www.edp24.co.uk/sport/norwich-city-fc/norwich_city_playing_squad_comes_first_then_carrow_road_expansion_says_david_mcnally_1_152427|title=Norwich City playing squad comes first \u2013 then Carrow Road expansion, says David McNally|last=Cuffley|first=David|date=20 September 2012|work=Eastern Daily Press|accessdate=21 September 2012|publisher=Archant}}</ref> The likely cost has been estimated at \u00a320m, but that \"Currently, every spare penny is reinvested in the first team squad and this is something that the board wishes to continue in the short term.\"<ref name=\"EDP\" />\n\nThe building of a [[Holiday Inn]] franchise in one corner of the ground, has somewhat diminished possibilities for the future enlargement of Carrow Road. However, the club is looking at options to build a small stand in front of the hotel in the short-term.<ref name=\"EDP\" />\n\n===Sheffield United===\n\n* Stadium: [[Bramall Lane]]\n* Capacity: 32,125<ref name=\":0\" />\n*''Current stadium status'': Reconstructed.\n\n[[Sheffield United F.C.|Sheffield United]] announced in 2009 plans to redevelop the Kop Stand, extending it backwards to create an additional 3,215 seats, alongside adding an additional tier to the South Stand. Planned for when the club were promoted back to the [[Premier League]], these would also include significant upgrades to the concourse. While these are yet to be completed, the permission to build was secured in 2009, and the plans were most recently resubmitted for approval in 2017.<ref name=\"sufc.co.uk\">{{cite news|url= https://www.sufc.co.uk/news/2017/december/south-stand-plans/|title=South Stand Plans|publisher=Sheffield United F.C.|accessdate=7 December 2017}}</ref> The developments were planned to be built through two phases, with the Kop first, taking capacity up to 37,000, followed by the South Stand.<ref name=\"insidermedia.com\">{{cite news|url= https://www.insidermedia.com/news/yorkshire/blades-to-kickstart-bramall-lane-redevelopment|title=Blades To Kickstart Bramall Lane Redevelopment|publisher=Insider Media|accessdate=11 November 2015}}</ref> The additional tier for the South Stand would potentially provide 5,400 seats.\n\n[[Bramall Lane]] became all-seater in the mid-1990s after completion of two new stands and the refurbishment of two existing stands. The most recent addition to the stadium is the Westfield Corner, filling in the gap between the South and Bramall Lane stands, which was completed in summer 2006.\n\n===Southampton===\n\n* Stadium: [[St Mary's Stadium]]\n* Capacity: 32,384<ref name=\":0\" />\n*''Current stadium status'': New.\n\n[[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]] left [[The Dell (Southampton)|The Dell]] for a new ground, [[St Mary's Stadium]], in 2001. The stadium has a capacity of 32,505 and is currently the largest football stadium in the South of England (excluding London). Relocation had been in the pipeline since the 1980s, although Southampton had converted The Dell into an all-seater stadium in the early 1990s as a temporary measure, leaving it with a capacity of less than 16,000.\n\n===Tottenham Hotspur===\n\n* Stadium: [[Tottenham Hotspur Stadium]]\n* Capacity: 62,303<ref name=\"capacity\">{{cite news|url=https://www.tottenhamhotspur.com/the-stadium/local/|title=Local: Information for local residents and businesses|publisher=Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|accessdate=18 December 2019}}</ref>\n*''Current stadium status'': New.\n\n[[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham]] have been planning a larger stadium since the late 1990s, however, it was undecided whether this strategy would involve expanding [[White Hart Lane]] (which has held some 36,000 all-seated fans since the early 1990s) or moving to a new site.  Spurs announced in the [[Northumberland Development Project]] (NDP) on 30 October 2008 that the club planned to build a new stadium on the existing White Hart Lane site combined with land purchased or optioned to the north, creating a [[New Tottenham Hotspur stadium|56,250-seater stadium]].<ref name=\"Sheringham\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/t/tottenham_hotspur/8326735.stm|title=Spurs aim for new stadium by 2012|last=Sheringham|first=Sam|date=26 October 2009|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=31 March 2015}}</ref> The new development would include leisure facilities, shops, housing, a club museum, public space and also a new base for the Tottenham Hotspur Foundation. Initial public consultations took place in December 2008 and a further consultations on the NDP's more detailed plans were held at the start of April 2009.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.tottenhamhotspur.com/news/club-reveal-next-stage-plans-for-northumberland-development-project-010109/|title=Club reveal next stage plans for the NDP |publisher=THFC |date=3 April 2009|accessdate=13 October 2013}}</ref> A planning application was submitted to [[Haringey Council]] in October 2009. However, following criticism by [[English Heritage]] and other conservation groups about the proposed demolition of listed buildings, the club withdrew the plans in May 2010 in favour of a revised plan which retained the listed buildings and improved the public areas around the stadium.<ref>[http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/sport/football/premier_league/tottenham/article7131149.ece Tottenham's plans to redevelop White Hart Lane shown red card ''Times online''] Accessed 22 May 2010</ref>\n\nOn 30 September 2010 the Planning Committee of Haringey Council unanimously approved the revised planning application and the [[Mayor of London]] gave his approval on 25 November 2010.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/t/tottenham_hotspur/9228658.stm Tottenham's White Hart Lane stadium plans approved BBC Sport online], Accessed 25 November 2010</ref>\n\nAfter an extended period of negotiations with Haringey Council and the Mayor of London, leading to a [[Town and Country Planning Act 1990#Section 106|Section 106 agreement]], planning permissions were issued on 20 September 2011.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/14996725.stm|title=Tottenham sign planning agreement to build new stadium|publisher=BBC|date=20 September 2011}}</ref> Following the [[2011 England riots|riots in Tottenham, other parts of London and elsewhere in England]] in August 2011, the [[Greater London Authority]] and Haringey Council announced on 28 September that it would relieve the club of all community infrastructure payments that planners would normally require, estimated at \u00a38.5m, and to provide a further \u00a38.5m for regeneration and infrastructure projects.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-london-15095674|title=Club reveal next stage plans for Northumberland Development Tottenham stadium: Club offered White Hart Lane deal|publisher=BBC |date=28 September 2011|accessdate=18 November 2011}}</ref> On 11 July 2014 the Secretary of State for the [[Department for Communities and Local Government]] announced that a [[compulsory purchase order]] had been granted for the outstanding parcel of land required for the development of the new stadium site.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/new-tottenham-hotspur-stadium-scheme-gets-the-green-light|title=New Tottenham Hotspur stadium scheme gets the green light|date=11 July 2014|publisher=Department for Communities and Local Government|accessdate=13 July 2014}}</ref> In February 2015 this compulsory purchase order was subject to an unsuccessful legal challenge by the business that owned the land.<ref name=\"highcourt\">[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/tottenham-hotspur/11424828/Tottenham-plans-for-new-stadium-given-massive-boost-as-business-looking-to-block-move-loses-High-Court-appeal.htmlTottenham plans for new stadium given massive boost as business looking to block move loses High Court appeal.] ''[[Daily Telegraph]]''<span wfd-id=\"5307\"> 20 February 2015</span>, Accessed 20 February 2015</ref> The anticipated stadium opening date was revised several times.<ref name=\"stadiumopening\">[http://m.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-london-30831515 Tottenham Hotspur stadium dispute firm in court challenge BBC News online 15 January 2015], Accessed 25 May 2015</ref>\n\nThe new stadium, [[Tottenham Hotspur Stadium]], opened with a ceremony on 3 April 2019 before its first competitive Premier League game, which was against [[Crystal Palace F.C.|Crystal Palace]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/sport/football/tottenham/tottenham-hotspur-stadium-opening-ceremony-spurs-pay-homage-to-regeneration-of-local-area-after-2011-a4108686.html |title=Tottenham Hotspur stadium opening ceremony: Spurs pay homage to regeneration of local area after 2011 riots |date=3 April 2019 |work=Evening Standard |accessdate=4 April 2019 |first= Jack |last=Rosser }}</ref> It opened with a stadium capacity of 62,062 which has since been increased to 62,303.<ref name=capacity /> The new stadium features two pitches\u2014an advanced artificial pitch to be used primarily for [[American football]], and a slide-in grass pitch to be used for association football. This is similar to the setup of the [[Sapporo Dome]] in Japan, a venue used for both baseball and association football. On 7 July 2015, Tottenham and the [[National Football League]] (NFL) announced that the new stadium would host at least [[NFL International Series|two NFL games each season]] from 2018 through to 2027.<ref>{{cite press release|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000500560/article/nfl-tottenham-hotspur-ink-10year-stadium-partnership |title=NFL, Tottenham Hotspur ink 10-year stadium partnership |publisher=National Football League |date=7 July 2015 |accessdate=11 July 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe capacity was further increased on 5 August 2019 with additional 148 seat, increased the overall capacity into 62,214.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://talksport.com/football/582476/tottenham-stadium-update-spurs-capacity/|title=Spurs given permission to increase capacity of Tottenham Hotspur Stadium|last=161385360554578|date=2019-08-05|website=talkSPORT|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-18}}</ref> Further 89 seats were added on 17 December 2019 and the capacity increased into 62,303 after being granted permission from Haringey Council.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tottenhamhotspur.com/news/2019/december/application-to-increase-stadium-capacity-approved/|title=Application to increase stadium capacity approved|website=Tottenham Hotspur|language=en|access-date=2019-12-18}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.90min.com/posts/6520023-tottenham-granted-permission-to-increase-stadium-capacity-for-the-second-time-since-opening|title=Tottenham Granted Permission to Increase Stadium Capacity for the Second Time Since Opening|date=2019-12-18|website=90min.com|language=en|access-date=2019-12-18}}</ref>\n\n===Watford===\n\n* Stadium: [[Vicarage Road]]\n* Capacity: 22,200<ref name=\":0\" />\n*''Current stadium status'': Reconstructed.\n\n[[Watford F.C.|Watford]] play their home games at the 20,877 seater [[Vicarage Road|Vicarage Road Stadium]] after the new 3,400 East Stand, known as the Sir Elton John stand, was completed.\n\nIn June 2015, the club announced that the staircases of the Sir Elton John stand would be removed and replaced with 700 seats.<ref>{{cite web|title=Extra Sir Elton John Stand Capacity|url=http://www.watfordfc.com/news/article/stadium-2483443.aspx|publisher=Watford FC|accessdate=11 June 2015}}</ref> The club announced that the North East corner would be transformed and 400 seats added to it,<ref>{{cite web |title=North-East Corner Transformation To Begin |url=http://www.watfordfc.com/news/article/150608-vicarage-road-stadium-north-east-corner-2486084.aspx |publisher=Watford FC |accessdate=11 June 2015}}</ref> thus taking the total capacity to 22,000.\n\n===West Ham United===\n\n* Stadium: [[London Stadium]]\n* Capacity: 60,000<ref name=\":0\" />\n*''Current stadium status'': New.\n\n[[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]] shelved plans for a new stadium in east London at a Parcelforce depot adjacent to [[West Ham tube station]] following their chairman's bankruptcy in the Icelandic financial crisis. In October 2010 the club formally registered an interest in conjunction with [[Newham Borough Council]] in taking over the nearby [[Olympic Stadium (London)|2012 Olympic Stadium]]. The plan involved a 60,000-capacity stadium and the retention of the running track. A converted Olympic stadium would be part of the 2018 World Cup bid. On 12 November 2010 the [[Olympic Park Legacy Company]] (OPLC) announced that West Ham and Tottenham Hotspur were the two preferred bidders to take over the Olympic stadium after the 2012 Olympics.<ref name=\"bbc.co.uk\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-london-11746496|title=Tottenham and West Ham lead London 2012 stadium bid|accessdate=12 November 2010|date=12 November 2010|work=BBC News}}</ref>\n\nThe OPLC announced on 11 February 2011 that [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham]] had been selected as the preferred bidder for the Olympic Stadium. The decision was subsequently ratified by Government departments and the Mayor of London.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-london-12424549|title=West Ham chosen as preferred Olympic Stadium tenant|work=BBC News|accessdate=12 February 2011}}</ref> However, following a legal challenge by Tottenham Hotspur and Leyton Orient over the operation of the bidding process the Olympic Park Legacy Company decided in October 2011 to nullify the first bid process, change the legacy handover arrangements, and launch a new bidding process to look for consortiums to lease the stadium.<ref name=\"olympicstadiumbid\">{{cite news| url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-london-14646806 | work=BBC News | title=Spurs win right to challenge 2012 stadium decision | date=24 August 2011}}</ref> In March 2012 West Ham and Newham Council submitted a bid under the revamped process.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/olympics/17489659|work=BBC Sport|title=London 2012: West Ham bid to be Olympic Stadium tenants|date=23 March 2012}}</ref>\n\nUpton Park had been all-seater since the mid 1990s, the most recent development being the construction of the Dr Martens Stand in the [[2000-01 in English football|2000\u201301 season]] which gave the club a 35,000 capacity, up from the 26,000 capacity reached in the mid 1990s when Upton Park first became all-seater.\n\nAt the start of the 2016\u201317 season, West Ham left Upton Park and moved into the Olympic Stadium (Renamed The London Stadium), which now has a revised capacity of 60,000, and is designed with retractable seating so the athletics track can still be used.\n\n===Wolverhampton Wanderers===\n\n* Stadium: [[Molineux Stadium]]\n* Capacity: 32,050<ref name=\":0\" />\n*''Current stadium status'': Reconstructed.\n\nPlans were announced in May 2010 to expand the capacity of [[Molineux Stadium|Molineux]] by the 2014\u201315 season from 29,303 to 36,000, with work beginning at the end of the 2010\u201311 season on the replacement of the Stan Cullis Stand. The new Stan Cullis Stand was completed at the end of the 2011\u201312 season, raising the stadium's capacity to approximately 31,700.<ref name=\"Wolves.co.uk\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wolves.co.uk/page/News/0,,10307~2581694,00.html |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120620051640/http://www.wolves.co.uk/page/News/0%2C%2C10307~2581694%2C00.html |archivedate=20 June 2012 |title=Wolves To Postpone Steve Bull Stand Redevelopment |publisher=Wolverhampton Wanderers FC |date=20 January 2012 |accessdate=13 October 2013 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> In January 2012 the club announced that the redevelopment of the Steve Bull Stand, which had been set to begin in 2012, had been postponed.<ref name=\"Wolves.co.uk\" /> The Jack Harris Stand and Billy Wright Stand will also remain unchanged until the club indicates otherwise.\n\nTwo of the stadium's four current stands were built in the early 1990s. The original Stan Cullis Stand was also built at this juncture (replacing the old North Bank Stand terraces), but was replaced itself in 2011\u201312 after just two decades use.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.shropshirestar.com/video/2012/08/10/wolves-unveil-new-stan-cullis-stand/|title=Wolves unveil new Stan Cullis stand|newspaper=[[Shropshire Star]]|date=10 August 2012 |accessdate=21 January 2019}}</ref> The Steve Bull Stand, currently the oldest part of the stadium, was built in 1979. With the completion of three new stands in 1993, in addition to the one opened just fourteen years earlier, Molineux was at the time one of the largest club stadiums in England, but has since been eclipsed by many other clubs who have relocated to new stadiums or expanded their existing ones.\n\n== Premier League Stadium Expanded Capacity ==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! width=\"20\" | Rank\n! width=\"150\" | Stadium\n! width=\"65\" | Capacity\n! width=\"125\" | Club\n! width=\"65\" | Committed Expanded Capacity\n! width=\"20\" | Rank with Expansion\n! Notes\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 1 ||[[Old Trafford]]|| style=\"text-align:center;\" |74,879\n|[[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]]|| || style=\"text-align:center;\" | 1 ||\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 2 ||[[Tottenham Hotspur Stadium]]|| style=\"text-align:center;\" |62,303||[[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]]|| || style=\"text-align:center;\" | 4 || New Stadium\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |3||[[London Stadium]]|| style=\"text-align:center;\" |{{nts|60,000}}||[[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]]||66,000|| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 2 ||\n|-\n\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |4||[[Emirates Stadium]]|| style=\"text-align:center;\" |60,704\n|[[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]]||  || style=\"text-align:center;\" | 6 ||\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 5 ||[[City of Manchester Stadium|Etihad Stadium]]|| style=\"text-align:center;\" |55,017\n|[[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]]||{{nts|63000}}{{citation needed|date=December 2019}}|| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 3 || North Stand Expansion\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 6 ||[[Anfield]]|| style=\"text-align:center;\" |53,394\n|[[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]]||61,000|| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 5 ||Anfield Road Expansion\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 7 ||[[St James' Park]]|| style=\"text-align:center;\" |52,305\n|[[Newcastle United]]||  || style=\"text-align:center;\" | 9 ||\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 8 ||[[Villa Park]]|| style=\"text-align:center;\" |42,095\n|[[Aston Villa]]||  || style=\"text-align:center;\" | 10 ||\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 9 ||[[Stamford Bridge (stadium)|Stamford Bridge]]|| style=\"text-align:center;\" |40,834\n|[[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]]||{{nts|60000}}<ref>{{cite web |title=Chelsea Expansion |url=http://www.getwestlondon.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/stamford-bridge-expansion-chelseas-proposed-10976207|date=June 2016 |accessdate=29 June 2016}}</ref>|| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 7 || Stadium Reconstruction\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 10 ||[[Goodison Park]]|| style=\"text-align:center;\" |39,414\n|[[Everton F.C.|Everton]]||60,000|| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 7 || New Stadium plan\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 11 ||[[King Power Stadium]]|| style=\"text-align:center;\" |32,261\n|[[Leicester City F.C.|Leicester City]]||{{nts|42000}}<ref>{{cite web |title=Leicester Expansion |url=http://www.leicestermercury.co.uk/Leicester-City-look-ground-expansion-build-new/story-29238169-detail/story.html|date=June 2016 |accessdate=29 June 2016}}</ref>|| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 11 || East Stand Expansion\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 12 ||[[St Mary's Stadium]]|| style=\"text-align:center;\" |32,384\n|[[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]]|| || style=\"text-align:center;\" | 12 ||\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 13 ||[[Bramall Lane]]|| style=\"text-align:center;\" |32,125\n|[[Sheffield United F.C.|Sheffield United]]||  || style=\"text-align:center;\" | 13 ||\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 14 ||[[Molineux Stadium]]|| style=\"text-align:center;\" |{{nts|32050}}||[[Wolverhampton Wanderers]]||  || style=\"text-align:center;\" | 14 ||\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 15 ||[[Falmer Stadium|The American Express Community Stadium]]|| style=\"text-align:center;\" |{{nts|30750}}||[[Brighton & Hove Albion]]||  || style=\"text-align:center;\" | 15 ||\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 16 ||[[Carrow Road]]|| style=\"text-align:center;\" |27,359||[[Norwich City F.C.|Norwich City]]||  || style=\"text-align:center;\" | 16 ||\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 17 ||[[Selhurst Park]]|| style=\"text-align:center;\" |25,486 \n|[[Crystal Palace F.C.|Crystal Palace]]||  || style=\"text-align:center;\" | 17 ||\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 18 ||[[Vicarage Road]]|| style=\"text-align:center;\" |22,200 \n|[[Watford F.C.|Watford]]|| || style=\"text-align:center;\" | 18 ||\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 19 ||[[Turf Moor]]|| style=\"text-align:center;\" |21,944 \n|[[Burnley F.C.|Burnley]]|| || style=\"text-align:center;\" | 19 ||\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 20 ||[[Vitality Stadium]]|| style=\"text-align:center;\" |11,364 \n|[[A.F.C. Bournemouth|AFC Bournemouth]]|| || style=\"text-align:center;\" | 20 ||\n|-\n|}\n\n==Championship==\n===Barnsley===\n\n* Stadium: [[Oakwell]]\n* Capacity: 23,287<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.efl.com/clubs-and-competitions/sky-bet-championship/clubs/barnsley/|title=EFL Official Website - Barnsley|website=www.efl.com|access-date=2019-12-18}}</ref>\n*''Current stadium status'': Reconstructed.\n\n[[Barnsley F.C.|Barnsley]] have announced that they are to demolish the old West Stand at [[Oakwell]] and replace it with a new 9,000-seater stand similar to the current East Stand .<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.footballgroundguide.com/barnsley/|title=Internet Football Ground Guide \u2013 Oakwell, Barnsley FC|publisher=Football Ground Guide|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130820143516/http://www.footballgroundguide.com/barnsley/|archivedate=20 August 2013|accessdate=13 October 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref> [[Oakwell Stadium]] currently holds 23,000 all-seated spectators and has done so since the mid-1990s. The plans for the reconstruction of the West Stand were first announced in the late 1990s. The stadium has a lot of clear land surrounding it making possible expansion to 40,000 or more; however, as Oakwell is rarely full to capacity, the club will continue to maintain the old West Stand for the foreseeable future.\n\n=== Birmingham City ===\n\n* Stadium: [[St Andrew's (stadium)|St Andrew's Trillion Trophy Stadium]]\n* Capacity: 30,016<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.efl.com/clubs-and-competitions/sky-bet-championship/clubs/birmingham-city/|title=EFL Official Website - Birmingham City|website=www.efl.com|access-date=2019-12-18}}</ref>\n* ''Current stadium status'': Reconstructed.\n\n===Blackburn Rovers===\n\n* Stadium: [[Ewood Park]]\n* Capacity: 31,367<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.efl.com/clubs-and-competitions/sky-bet-championship/clubs/blackburn-rovers/|title=EFL Official Website - Blackburn Rovers|website=www.efl.com|access-date=2019-12-18}}</ref>\n*''Current stadium status'': Reconstructed.\nThere are long-term plans to redevelop the 1988-built Riverside Stand which would raise [[Ewood Park|Ewood Park's]] capacity by around 9,000 to 41,000.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.footballgroundguide.com/blackburn_rovers/ewood_park.htm |title=Ewood Park, Blackburn Rovers FC, Ground Description |publisher=Football Ground Guide |date=21 January 2009 |accessdate=14 April 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120218104723/http://www.footballgroundguide.com/blackburn_rovers/ewood_park.htm |archivedate=18 February 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> The stadium became all-seater for the [[1994-95 in English football|1994\u201395 season]] after a two-year reconstruction programme which saw three of the stadium's stands rebuilt. The reconstruction of the Darwen End saw the demolition of the Fernhurst Mill and the new Jack Walker Stand's construction saw the demolition of houses along Nuttall Street, so by the time Blackburn were league champions in 1995, the stadium held nearly 32,000 fans all-seated.\n\nAny further development in the foreseeable future depends on an increase of attendance, as attendances have regularly been below Ewood Park's full capacity since relegation from the Premier League at the end of 2011\u201312 season.\n\n===Brentford===\n\n* Stadium: [[Griffin Park]]\n* Capacity: 12,763<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.efl.com/clubs-and-competitions/sky-bet-championship/clubs/brentford/|title=EFL Official Website - Brentford|website=www.efl.com|access-date=2019-12-18}}</ref>\n*''Current stadium status'': Reconstructed; preparing to build new ground ([[Brentford Community Stadium|Brentford Community Stadium]]).\n\n[[Brentford F.C.]], who have been considering relocating from [[Griffin Park]] since the 1990s, are hoping to move to a [[Lionel Road Stadium|new 20,000-capacity stadium]] a mile from Griffin Park, and still in [[Brentford]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/b/brentford/2401265.stm|title=Bees unveil stadium plans|work=BBC News|date=6 November 2002|accessdate=14 April 2010}}</ref> After several years of effort, the club announced in December 2007 that they had been given an option on the site at Lionel Road,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/b/brentford/7132539.stm|title=Brentford given new stadium boost|work=BBC News|date=7 December 2007|accessdate=14 April 2010}}</ref> and announced two months later a link-up with property developer Barratt Homes to develop the site.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://world.brentfordfc.co.uk/page/LatestNews/0,,10421~1246803,00.html |title=Brentford Football Club And Barratt Homes Team Up To Acquire Land For New Community Stadium |date=22 February 2008 |work=brentfordfc.premiumtv.co.uk |access-date=14 April 2010 |publisher=Brentford F.C. |df=dmy-all}}</ref> The proposed move is strongly backed by fans, particularly as it will keep them in [[Brentford]]. The new stadium may be shared with a professional rugby club.\n\nAt one point, it was reported that the club would increase the capacity of Griffin Park (their home since 1904) from 12,500 to 17,000, but those plans now appear to be on hold in relation to the new stadium.\n\nIn 2014 the club announced that planning permission had been granted for the new stadium. After a number of delays, a compulsory purchase order was finally granted by the London Borough of Hounslow in late 2016, allowing the club to take full possession of the site. In February 2017 Brentford football club announced that they expected to start work on the new stadium in March. They plan to move into the new stadium for the start of the 2019/20 season.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/b/brentford/3476135.stm|title=Bees plan to expand stadium|work=BBC News|date=10 February 2004|accessdate=14 April 2010}}</ref>\n\nConstruction of [[Brentford Community Stadium]] began on 24 March 2017<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.brentfordcommunitystadium.com/news/work-underway|title=Work underway {{!}} Brentford Community Stadium|website=www.brentfordcommunitystadium.com|access-date=2019-12-18}}</ref> and expected to finish by summer 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.brentfordfc.com/news/2018/august/stadium-update-28.08.18/|title=Brentford FC to move home in summer 2020 as work continues on new stadium|website=www.brentfordfc.com|language=en-gb|access-date=2019-12-18}}</ref> The capacity of the new stadium will be at 17,250.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://newstadium.brentfordfc.com/?_ga=2.245961412.1359159317.1576690043-1780454102.1576690043|title=Brentford FC New Stadium {{!}}|website=newstadium.brentfordfc.com|access-date=2019-12-18}}</ref>\n\n===Bristol City===\n\n* Stadium: [[Ashton Gate Stadium]]\n* Capacity: 27,000<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.efl.com/clubs-and-competitions/sky-bet-championship/clubs/bristol-city/|title=EFL Official Website - Bristol City|website=www.efl.com|access-date=2019-12-18}}</ref>\n*''Current stadium status'': Reconstructed.\n\nOn 29 November 2007 it was announced that after over 100 years at [[Ashton Gate Stadium|Ashton Gate]], [[Bristol City F.C.|Bristol City]] would be moving to a new stadium in South [[Bristol]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.bcfc.co.uk/page/NewsDetail/0,,10327~1178896,00.html |title=CITY ANNOUNCE NEW STADIUM PLANS |date=30 November 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120208062010/http://www.bcfc.co.uk/page/NewsDetail/0%2C%2C10327~1178896%2C00.html |archivedate=8 February 2012 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> This [[Bristol City Stadium|proposed new stadium]] would have had a capacity of 30,000 seats. At the time Ashton Gate held around 21,000 all-seated spectators and had done so since the mid-1990s, as the initial plan was to upgrade the existing stadium rather than relocate to a new site. In February 2012 the project was delayed by legal rows in the High Court.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-bristol-17112097 |title=Legal bid over Ashton Vale town green may take a month |publisher=BBC |date=21 February 2012 |accessdate=8 March 2012}}</ref>\nAs an alternative, it was announced that plans for the reconstruction of Ashton Gate were being developed. Following the successful submission of a planning application to [[Bristol City Council]], the decision was taken to rebuild the stadium. The rebuild, completed in 2016, brought the all-seater capacity of Ashton Gate to 27,000. It involved the renovation of the Atyeo Stand interior, a total renovation of the Dolman Stand, rebuilding the former Wedlock stand to the same height as the Dolman Stand, and rebuilding the former Williams stand (now the Lansdown stand) to make it double tiered with executive boxes.\n\n===Cardiff City===\n\n* Stadium: [[Cardiff City Stadium]]\n* Capacity: 33,280<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.efl.com/clubs-and-competitions/sky-bet-championship/clubs/cardiff-city/|title=EFL Official Website - Cardiff City|website=www.efl.com|access-date=2019-12-18}}</ref>\n* ''Current stadium status'': New.\n\nA new all-seater stadium, planned since the late 1990s, for [[Cardiff City F.C.|Cardiff City]] opened in 2009 after the club had spent 99 years at nearby [[Ninian Park]], and for three seasons the new stadium was shared with the [[Cardiff Blues]] rugby union club. The [[Cardiff City Stadium]] has been expanded to hold up to 33,000 fans, and can be extended further to hold up to 60,000.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/c/cardiff_city/6451593.stm|title=Cardiff reduce stadium capacity|date=15 March 2007|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=14 April 2010}}</ref> It is to be the second largest stadium in [[Wales]], after the [[Millennium Stadium]], also in the [[Wales|Welsh]] capital.\n\n===Charlton Athletic===\n\n* Stadium: [[The Valley (London)|The Valley]]\n* Capacity: 27,111<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.efl.com/clubs-and-competitions/sky-bet-championship/clubs/charlton-athletic/|title=EFL Official Website - Charlton Athletic|website=www.efl.com|access-date=2019-12-18}}</ref>\n*''Current stadium status'': Reconstructed.\n\n[[Charlton Athletic F.C.|Charlton]] have planning permission from [[Greenwich London Borough Council|Greenwich Council]] to add a second tier to the East Stand at [[The Valley (London)|The Valley]], increasing capacity to 31,000, up from a capacity of more than 26,000 which was reached in December 2001. Potential future developments to the Jimmy Seed Stand could see this raised to 40,000, but this is unlikely to happen unless the club is promoted back to the [[Premier League]] or comes under new ownership.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.footballgroundguide.com/charlton_athletic/index.htm|title=The Internet Football Grounds Guide \u2013 The Valley, Charlton Athletic FC|publisher=Football Ground Guide|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130928153748/http://www.footballgroundguide.com/charlton_athletic/index.htm|archivedate=28 September 2013|accessdate=13 October 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Derby County===\n\n* Stadium: [[Pride Park Stadium|Pride Park]]\n* Capacity: 33,597<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.efl.com/clubs-and-competitions/sky-bet-championship/clubs/derby-county/|title=EFL Official Website - Derby County|website=www.efl.com|access-date=2019-12-18}}</ref>\n*''Current stadium status'': New.\n\nIn April 2007, [[Derby County F.C.|Derby County]] released details of a proposed \u00a320m development around their [[Pride Park Stadium]] which would create about 250 jobs.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/derby/content/articles/2007/04/26/pride_park_hotel_development_feature.shtml|title=Rams announce \u00a320m Pride Park development|publisher=BBC|date=26 April 2007|accessdate=14 April 2010|first=John|last=Atkin}}</ref> The Pride Plaza project would include a 165-bed hotel, bars, restaurants and office space. On 9 November 2007 [[Derby City Council]] agreed to let the plans go ahead.\n\nAdditionally the club has announced plans to expand the capacity up from 33,500 to 44,000, with the work due to take place during the 2007\u201308 close season,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.therams.co.uk/details.asp?back=true&key=1D29%7C0%7C2185366269754%7CR%7C536%7C11372241262007310839232&parentkey=1D29%7C0%7C2185366269754%7Cp%7C536%7C0 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927201803/http://www.therams.co.uk/details.asp?back=true&key=1D29%7C0%7C2185366269754%7CR%7C536%7C11372241262007310839232&parentkey=1D29%7C0%7C2185366269754%7Cp%7C536%7C0 |archivedate=27 September 2007 |title=Rams as big as Chelsea? |work=therams.co.uk |publisher=Northcliffe Media |url-status=dead |df=dmy |accessdate=25 March 2017 }}</ref> provided the club avoided relegation. The plans include adding rows of seats to the north, south and east stands.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.footballgroundguide.com/derby.htm |title=Internet Football Grounds Guide \u2013 Pride Park, Derby County Football Club |publisher=Footballgroundguide.com |accessdate=14 April 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110519180411/http://www.footballgroundguide.com/derby.htm |archivedate=19 May 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> If completed, this would allow the club to break its current club record home attendance, Pride Park was opened in 1997 when Derby left the [[Baseball Ground]], as one of the first clubs to relocate to a new stadium to comply with the [[Taylor Report]]. The new stadium was opened just 18 months after the decision to relocate was made public; the previous plan had been for the Baseball Ground to be rebuilt with a 26,000-seat capacity. However, the club failed to maintain its top-flight status and when, in January 2008, was sold into new American ownership, in the form of General Sports and Entertainment<ref name=\"newowners\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/d/derby_county/7210230.stm|work=BBC Sport|title=New owners reveal Derby ambition|date=28 January 2008}}</ref> both the Plaza plan and the Ground expansion initiatives were scrapped.\n\nOn 3 October 2011, Derby County announced that they had submitted plans to Derby City Council for a \u00a37 million development of land outside the stadium, which the club named \"The Plaza @ Pride Park\".<ref name=\"Plaza 2 statement\">{{cite news|url=http://www.dcfc.co.uk/news/article/press-release-the-plaza-pride-park-256822.aspx?pageView=full#anchored|publisher=Derby County F.C.|work=dcfc.co.uk|title=Press Release: The Plaza @ Pride Park|date=11 October 2011|accessdate=19 December 2012}}</ref>\n\nThese plans include five [[Coffeehouse|cafes]]/[[restaurant]]s, two [[convenience store]]s and 2,000 square metres of [[Office|office space]]. These plans have been scaled down from the planned \u00a320 million development proposed in 2007.<ref name=\"Plaza 2\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-lincolnshire-15147480|work=BBC News|title=Derby County submits plans for new Pride Park plaza|date=3 October 2011}}</ref> Derby County CEO Tom Glick, said that these plans would help the club deal with the new Financial Fair Play regulations which will be introduced in the [[The Football League|Football League]] from 2012, as revenue from the Plaza will be reinvested back into the club.<ref name=\"Plaza 2 statement\" />\n\nThis planned development also coincides with a plan from the City Council to build a multi-use sports arena on the same site as the proposed Plaza.<ref name=\"Plaza 2\" />\n\nOn 12 January 2012, Derby City Council's Planning Control Committee gave planning permission for the development,<ref name=\"2012 planning permission\">{{cite news|url=http://www.dcfc.co.uk/news/article/press-release-planning-consent-approved-256826.aspx?pageView=full#anchored|publisher=Derby County F.C.|work=dcfc.co.uk|title=Press Release: Planning Consent Approved|date=12 January 2012|accessdate=19 December 2012}}</ref> Derby County Chief Executive Tom Glick stated the club had moved the next stage of the development, finding a development company to build the plaza.<ref name=\"2012 planning permission\" />\n\n===Fulham===\n\n* Stadium: [[Craven Cottage]]\n* Capacity: 25,700<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.efl.com/clubs-and-competitions/sky-bet-championship/clubs/fulham/|title=EFL Official Website - Fulham|website=www.efl.com|access-date=2019-12-18}}</ref>\n*''Current stadium status'': Reconstructed. 2019 Riverside Stand project.\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:2004 proposal for craven cottage rebuild.jpg|thumb|right|2003\u201304 proposal for a complete reconstruction of the ground to a modern 40,000-seater stadium]] -->\n\nSince [[Fulham F.C.|Fulham's]] promotion to the Premier League, and the conversion of [[Craven Cottage]] to an all-seater stadium, the club have been slowly adding to the capacity of the ground every summer. There are periodic reports of a new stadium in [[White City Stadium|White City]] to be shared with [[Queens Park Rangers F.C.|Queens Park Rangers]], but such plans are not currently being pursued by either club, with both concentrating on developing their existing grounds. Craven Cottage was the final top division stadium to feature standing accommodation when Fulham were promoted in 2001, but [[Taylor Report]] regulations meant it closed a year later. During this period there was intermittent rumours of the Cottage being sold and Fulham possibly purchasing land at [[Battersea Power Station]] or elsewhere in West London. Thus Fulham ground-shared with rivals Queens Park Rangers for two years at [[Loftus Road]] until they returned to an all-seater Craven Cottage. The plan at the time had been for Craven Cottage to reach over 30,000 capacity, but these were delayed due to opposition from local residents and at first the club had to settle for a 22,000-seat stadium.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://qprreport.blogspot.co.uk/2008/03/qprs-major-new-sponsorship-dealnaomi.html|title=QPR's Major New Sponsorship Deal: Lotto Kit&nbsp;... Kingfisher Sponsors&nbsp;... Naomi Campbell Modelling&nbsp;... and New Stadium Search|date=24 March 2008|work=QPR Report|accessdate=13 October 2013}}</ref>\n\nThere have been gradual increases in capacity since Fulham's return, with the capacity now being 25,700. In 2012, the local council approved raising Craven Cottage's capacity to 30,000.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11681/7939236/Cottage-expansion-granted|title=Cottage expansion granted|work=Sky Sports|access-date=2018-10-09}}</ref> The latest plans include changes made by their new owner Shahid Khan after he purchased the club in 2013, with construction to begin in Summer of 2019.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/sport/football/fulham-plans-for-craven-cottage-expansion-approved-by-council-with-work-due-to-begin-in-summer-of-a3794981.html|title=Fulham plans for Craven Cottage expansion approved|work=Evening Standard|access-date=2018-10-09}}</ref> The new plan includes a riverwalk which extends up to 11m into the River Thames, which some opponents feel will set a dangerous precedent for future development along the river.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/sport/football/fulham-stadium-expansion-plan-includes-new-river-walk-and-4000-more-seats-a3743621.html|title=Fulham stadium expansion includes new river walk and 4,000 more seats|work=Evening Standard|access-date=2018-10-09}}</ref> On 22 May 2019, Fulham appointed [[Buckingham Group|Buckingham Group Contracting Ltd]] as the lead contractor for Riverside Stand project.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.fulhamfc.com/stadium-development|title=Riverside Development|website=www.fulhamfc.com|language=en|access-date=2019-12-18}}</ref>\n\nThe development begun on summer 2019 and scheduled to be completed in 2021.<ref name=\":1\" /> The capacity at Riverside Stand will be increased from 4,689 to 8,650; increasing the overall capacity into 29,600.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fulhamfc.com/stadium-development/the-application|title=The Application|website=www.fulhamfc.com|language=en|access-date=2019-12-18}}</ref>\n\n===Huddersfield Town===\n\n* Stadium: [[Kirklees Stadium|The John Smith's Stadium]]\n* Capacity: 24,500<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.efl.com/clubs-and-competitions/sky-bet-championship/clubs/huddersfield-town/|title=EFL Official Website - Huddersfield Town|website=www.efl.com|access-date=2019-12-18}}</ref>\n*''Current Stadium status'': New.\n\n[[Huddersfield Town F.C.|Huddersfield Town's]] [[John Smith's Stadium]], was opened as the McAlpine Stadium in August 1994. Initially two stands were open, with a third stand opening later in 1994, but eventually the 2 tiered North Stand was completed to leave an all seater stadium with a capacity of 24,500 in 1998. The Stadium complex includes fitness and leisure facilities built behind the North Stand with gymnasium, swimming pool and hotel facilities and offices. The venture was a tri-partide one with Huddersfield Town, [[Huddersfield Giants]] Rugby league club and Kirklees Metropolitan Council being shareholders in a 40:20:40 ratio with a company called KSDL. After Huddersfield Town went into administration the 40% shares were bought for \u00a32 by Rugby League Chairman and owner [[Ken Davy]], and transferred into his own private company Huddersfield Sporting Pride which holds 60% ownership of the Stadium complex at present.\n\nThere are current plans for significant construction work around the Stadium which would provide Hotels, Shops, a Riverside leisure facility, bars and restaurants opposite the Stadium and on the Golf driving range site and either side of the river. The project, HDOne, would provide ongoing and significant income streams to KSDL, the company which runs and owns the stadium. There is potential for further expansion of the capacity by adding a 2nd tier to the East Stand but no plans are being considered as yet. The North Stand Lower Tier remains as a temporary seating area to facilitate any rock concerts that could be held at the Stadium. However, there have not been any in recent years and there is hope that a permanent stand will be constructed here as a standing terrace for home fans.\n\n===Hull City===\n\n* Stadium: [[KCOM Stadium]] \n* Capacity: 25,586<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.efl.com/clubs-and-competitions/sky-bet-championship/clubs/hull-city/|title=EFL Official Website - Hull City|website=www.efl.com|access-date=2019-12-18}}</ref>\n*''Current stadium status'': New.\n\n[[Hull City A.F.C.|Hull's]] [[KC Stadium]], which opened in December 2002 with a capacity of more than 25,000 seats to replace [[Boothferry Park]], is designed to provide for future expansion to a capacity of approximately 45,000 by the addition of a second tier on the Arco East Stand.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://kcstadium.co.uk/kc-stadium/stadium-facts |title=The Kingston Communications Stadium |publisher=Kcstadium.co.uk |date= |accessdate=13 October 2013}}</ref> In March 2008 the Hull chairman said an expansion could potentially take place within two years if there was a clear need for further capacity.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thisishullandeastriding.co.uk/Hull-City-promotion-mean-KC-expansion/story-11945621-detail/story.html|archive-url=https://archive.today/20131013211139/http://www.thisishullandeastriding.co.uk/Hull-City-promotion-mean-KC-expansion/story-11945621-detail/story.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=2013-10-13|title=Hull City promotion could mean KC expansion|publisher=}}</ref> In January 2011 it was announced that Hull, under new owner [[Assem Allam]], were interested in buying the KC Stadium from [[Hull City Council]] in order to redevelop the stadium and the vicinity of it.<ref>{{cite news|title=Allams plan to buy KC Stadium from Hull City Council|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/h/hull_city/9355077.stm|work=BBC Sport|date=11 January 2011|accessdate=19 December 2012}}</ref> Consultation with the council commenced in May.<ref>{{cite news|title=Hull City owner Allam in stadium talks with council|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/h/hull_city/9495830.stm|date=24 May 2011|accessdate=19 December 2012|work=BBC Sport}}</ref> These talks broke down in September 2011,<ref>{{cite news|title=KC Stadium not to be sold by city council to Hull City|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/15077080|work=BBC Sport|date=27 September 2011|accessdate=19 December 2012}}</ref> leading the club to announce in December 2012 their intention to move into a new stadium should the club achieve promotion back to the Premier League.<ref>{{cite news|title=Hull City owner plans stadium move if they win promotion|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/20773372|work=BBC Sport|date=18 December 2012|accessdate=19 December 2012}}</ref>\n\nWhen Hull moved to the stadium in December 2002, they were still playing in [[Football League Division Three|Division Three]] (they reached the Premier League in 2008). For the 56 years prior to that, they had played at [[Boothferry Park]] but the decision was made to build a new stadium when a takeover by [[Adam Pearson (sports executive)|Adam Pearson]] in 2001 the club's new owner declared his ambition to build a stadium suited to top flight football, as Boothferry Park was too confined to develop a stadium fit for top division football. The stadium had also fallen into disrepair during the 1990s, as Hull's precarious financial position at the time meant that maintenance costs could often not be met.\n\n===Leeds United===\n\n* Stadium: [[Elland Road]]\n* Capacity: 37,890<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.efl.com/clubs-and-competitions/sky-bet-championship/clubs/leeds-united/|title=EFL Official Website - Leeds United|website=www.efl.com|access-date=2019-12-18}}</ref>\n*''Current stadium status'': Reconstructed.\n\nAt one point, while flying high in Europe in 2001, [[Leeds United A.F.C.|Leeds]] were examining a potential move to a new 50,000-seat stadium in nearby [[Stourton, West Yorkshire|Stourton]], while there were also ambitious plans to redevelop [[Elland Road]] as a 90,000-seat \"Wembley of the North\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_prem/1528777.stm|title=Leeds opt for new stadium|work=BBC News|date=7 September 2001|accessdate=14 April 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://old.fsf.org.uk/ground-guide/stadiums/leeds-united/elland-road/ |title=The Football Supporters' Federation \u2013 Leeds United |publisher=Fsf.org.uk |accessdate=13 October 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20131013193343/http://old.fsf.org.uk/ground-guide/stadiums/leeds-united/elland-road/ |archivedate=13 October 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Following the club's collapse into administration and dropping down two divisions, the sum of Leeds stadium ambitions at the present is simply to regain ownership of [[Elland Road]], which had to be sold to offset debts between 2002 and 2004.\n\nThe stadium became all-seater in 1994, following the refurbishment of \"Kop\" (now the [[Don Revie]] Stand), and also following the reconstruction of the East Stand two years earlier as a 15,100-seat stand, which gave Elland Road a capacity of more than 40,000 seats.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/l/leeds_united/3995041.stm |title=Leeds sell ground after bid fails |work=BBC News |date=12 November 2004 |accessdate=14 April 2010}}</ref>\n\n===Luton Town===\n\n* Stadium: [[Kenilworth Road]]\n* Capacity: 10,356<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.efl.com/clubs-and-competitions/sky-bet-championship/clubs/luton-town/|title=EFL Official Website - Luton Town|website=www.efl.com|access-date=2019-12-18}}</ref>\n*''Current stadium status'': Reconstructed.\n\nThe club were planning to move to a 20,000-seat stadium near the M1, outside of [[Luton]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.footballgroundguide.com/conference/luton_town.htm#Future%20Developments|title=Internet Football Ground Guide \u2013 Kenilworth Road, Luton Town FC|date=|publisher=Footballgroundguide.com|accessdate=13 October 2013}}</ref> but these plans have been delayed because of the club's financial difficulties. The club has been intending to move since the 1950s, when it was proposed to build a 50,000-seater stadium in the Lewsey Park area of the town. More recently, relocation has been in the pipeline since the early 1990s. Firstly, it was intended to move to the Kohlerdome, named after [[David Kohler]], an indoor stadium seating 20,000. This was blocked at planning permission due to issues surrounding improvements at the nearby junction 10 of the [[M1 motorway]]. An appeal against the decision was unsuccessful.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football-noades-barrier-to-sale-of-park-1072745.html|title=Noades barrier to sale of Park|date=23 February 1999|work=The Independent|accessdate=19 December 2012}}</ref> In 2001, land was bought in order to build a new stadium,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/l/luton_town/1194646.stm|title=New stadium plan for Luton|date=28 February 2001|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=19 December 2012}}</ref> and in 2003 the club's commitment to the 15,000-seat stadium project was reiterated.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/l/luton_town/2689105.stm|title=Hatters promised new stadium|date=23 January 2003|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=19 December 2012}}</ref> However, the plans were cancelled in 2005, reportedly due to [[London Luton Airport]]'s attempt to expand in the area;<ref name=\"Hatters change new stadium plan\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/l/luton_town/4397624.stm|title=Hatters change new stadium plan|date=1 November 2005|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=19 December 2012}}</ref> the airport denied this was the case.<ref name=\"Luton WSC\">{{cite journal|last=Rose|first=Neil|date=October 2007|title=Town crier|url=http://www.wsc.co.uk/the-archive/32-Managers/628-town-crier|journal=When Saturday Comes|accessdate=19 December 2012}}</ref> This prompted the club to propose a 20,000-seater stadium development to be built outside the town's boundaries, near the villages of [[Harlington, Bedfordshire|Harlington]] and [[Toddington, Bedfordshire|Toddington]], near junction 12 of the M1.<ref name=\"Hatters change new stadium plan\" /><ref name=\"Luton WSC\" /> Fierce opposition by the fans and the eventually slide into administration saw these plans evaporate.{{citation needed|date=December 2012}} [[Kenilworth Road]] was converted to all-seater capacity of around 10,200 following the club's promotion into the Championship in 2005, and in October 2012 the club announced their intention to add more seats to two stands.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.leightonbuzzardonline.co.uk/sport/luton-town-fc/sweet-stadium-development-plans-are-progressing-1-4401924|title=Sweet: Stadium development plans are progressing|last=Wood|first=Mark|date=24 October 2012|work=Leighton Buzzard Observer|accessdate=13 October 2013|publisher=Johnston Publishing}}</ref>\nLuton now have planning permission for a 17,500 (rising to 23,500) at Power Court in the centre of the town.\n\n===Middlesbrough===\n\n* Stadium: [[Riverside Stadium]]\n* Capacity: 34,742<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.efl.com/clubs-and-competitions/sky-bet-championship/clubs/middlesbrough/|title=EFL Official Website - Middlesbrough|website=www.efl.com|access-date=2019-12-18}}</ref>\n*''Current stadium status'': New.\n\nFollowing Middlesbrough's promotion back to the Premier League full house have become the norm again and ground expansion a real future possibility. Much will depend on the clubs on-field success and the chairman's willingness to expand though. They have planning permission to expand by another 7,000 seats.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mfc.co.uk/page/club/stadium-story |title=The Story Of The Stadium |publisher=Middlesbrough FC |accessdate=13 October 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130902035155/http://www.mfc.co.uk/page/club/stadium-story |archivedate=2 September 2013 |df=dmy }}</ref> If [[England]] had been successful in bidding to host the [[2018 FIFA World Cup]], the expansion would have been likely to occur to ensure consideration as a World Cup venue.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://old.fsf.org.uk/ground-guide/stadiums/middlesbrough/riverside-stadium/ |title=The Football Supporters' Federation \u2013 Middlesbrough |publisher=Fsf.org.uk |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20131013193345/http://old.fsf.org.uk/ground-guide/stadiums/middlesbrough/riverside-stadium/ |archivedate=13 October 2013 |accessdate=25 March 2017 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> However, England lost the bid.\n\nMiddlesbrough have played at the Riverside since 1995, when they moved from [[Ayresome Park]] in the first relocation of a top division club's stadium for 72 years. The stadium, which held 30,000 seated fans on its completion, is located on the site of a former chemical works on the banks of the Middlesbrough dock and its channel to the [[River Tees]]. The land for the stadium was gifted to the club by the [[Teesside Development Corporation]] for a nominal \u00a31 fee in the hope it would spur development of the disused former dock area. The stadium was the largest newly built stadium in post-war England, and the initial success of the new ground is considered to have spurred on other clubs such as [[Sunderland A.F.C.|Sunderland]] and [[Derby County]] to move from their traditional homes to newly built Taylor-compliant stadiums in designated redevelopment zones.\n\nAyresome Park's location meant that it would have impractical to achieve an all-seater capacity of more than 20,000.\n\nThe stadium took a mere 32 weeks to build, with the planned relocation being announced in late 1993 and work beginning just a year later.\n\nDemand meant the stadium was expanded in 1998 to take the capacity to 35,100, but subsequent reorganisation and the installation of a big screen has seen the capacity reduced marginally to 34,742. Following promotion to the premier league further reorganisation has reduced capacity further to 33,746.\n\n===Millwall===\n\n* Stadium: [[The Den]]\n* Capacity: 20,146<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.efl.com/clubs-and-competitions/sky-bet-championship/clubs/millwall/|title=EFL Official Website - Millwall|website=www.efl.com|access-date=2019-12-18}}</ref>\n*''Current stadium status'': New/Looking for move.\n\nThe New Den, as it was initially known to distinguish it from its predecessor, was the first new all-seater stadium in England to be completed after the [[Taylor Report]] on the [[Hillsborough disaster]] of 1989. It was designed with effective crowd management in mind (particularly given Millwall's crowd problems at The Old Den), with the escape routes being short and direct. After chairman Reg Burr decided that it would not be viable to redevelop The Old Den as an all-seater stadium, he announced in 1990 that the club would relocate to a new stadium in the Senegal Fields area in south Bermondsey. Originally, it was planned to have a seating capacity of between 25,000 and 30,000, however, the club opted to wait so the capacity was kept to just over 20,000.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.millwall-history.org.uk/the_den5.htm|title=Moving On: The New Den|website=www.millwall-history.org.uk}}</ref>\n\nMillwall played their final game at The Old Den on 8 May 1993 after 83 years and then moved to the new stadium a quarter-of-a-mile away from Cold Blow Lane. The \u00a316 million New Den was opened by [[John Smith (Labour Party leader)|John Smith]], the leader of the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] and of [[Leader of the Opposition (United Kingdom)|the Opposition]] at the time, on 4 August 1993 prior to a prestigious friendly against [[Sporting Clube de Portugal|Sporting Portugal]], which Sporting won 2\u20131. The Den was the first new stadium constructed for a professional football team in London since 1937.\n\nIn September 2016 [[Lewisham London Borough Council|Lewisham Council]] approved a [[compulsory purchase order]] of land surrounding The Den rented by Millwall, as part of a major redevelopment of the \"New Bermondsey\" area. The plans are controversial because the developer, Renewal, is controlled by [[Offshore company|offshore companies]] with unclear ownership, and is seen by the club and local community to be profiteering by demolishing existing homes and businesses as well as Millwall's car-park & the highly acclaimed and well recognised Millwall Community Trust \u2013 to build up to 2,400 new private homes, with no council housing and less than 15% of 'affordable housing'. Millwall had submitted their own plans for regeneration centred around the football club itself, but the council voted in favour of Renewal's plans.<ref name=\"Renewal\">{{cite news| title = Millwall Football Club 'to fight' compulsory purchase order\n| url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-london-37306839| work=BBC News| date=8 September 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2016 ''[[Private Eye]]'' reported how Renewal had been founded by a former Lewisham Council leader and senior officer, suggesting potential bias, and that the decision to approve Renewal's plans may have been made as long ago as 2013 despite the fact that no due diligence had been able to be carried out by [[PricewaterhouseCoopers]] due to \"poor\" and \"limited\" access to information and management at Renewal, which is registered in the [[Isle of Man]].<ref>{{cite magazine |last= |first= |date=9 December 2016 |title=Pitch battle |url= |magazine=[[Private Eye]] |location=London |publisher=Pressdram Ltd <!--|accessdate=27 December 2016-->}}</ref>\n\nIn the face of mounting community opposition and media scrutiny, the Council said in January 2017 it will not proceed with the CPO.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2017/jan/27/how-local-resistance-and-press-scrutiny-saved-millwalls-stadium | title=How the battle to save Millwall's stadium was won | date=27 January 2017 | author=Ronay, Barney |accessdate=28 January 2017}}</ref> However, it was later reported to be taking legal advice regarding other avenues of securing the CPO, and Council cabinet members will decide how to proceed after a \"review\". ''Private Eye'' reported that Millwall are continuing to explore relocation options in Kent.<ref>{{cite magazine |last= |first= |date=10 February 2017 |title=Load of Bullocks |url= |magazine=[[Private Eye]] |location=London |publisher=Pressdram Ltd <!--|accessdate=14 February 2017-->}}</ref>\n\n===Nottingham Forest===\n\n* Stadium: [[City Ground]]\n* Capacity: 30,445<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.efl.com/clubs-and-competitions/sky-bet-championship/clubs/nottingham-forest/|title=EFL Official Website - Nottingham Forest|website=www.efl.com|access-date=2019-12-18}}</ref>\n*''Current stadium status'': Reconstructed.\n\n[[Nottingham Forest F.C.|Nottingham Forest]] currently play at the 30,602 capacity [[City Ground]]. The club had plans to move into a 50,000-seat new stadium in the [[Clifton, Nottingham|Clifton]] area of the city.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://world.nottinghamforest.co.uk/page/NewsDetail/0,,10308~1054789,00.html |title=Reds Unveil New Super Stadium Plans |date=20 July 2007 |work=nottinghamforest.co.uk |access-date=14 April 2010 |publisher=Nottingham Forest F.C. |df=dmy-all}}</ref> The club subsequently were also thinking of relocating to the Gamston area of [[West Bridgford]] or the Eastcroft area of Nottingham\n\nOn 28 February 2019 the club confirmed an extended lease on the City Ground. This extended lease means the club is now able to proceed with plans to redevelop the City Ground and surrounding area. Central to this redevelopment will be the replacement of the current Peter Taylor Stand with a new 10,000-seater stand, and improvements to the Trentside area, Brian Clough and Bridgford Stands. \nThe new Peter Taylor Stand will see the introduction of a museum, a new club shop, range of hospitality lounge options and restaurants and executive boxes.<ref>https://www.cartwrightcommunications.com/blog/city-ground-redevelopment-what-you-need-to-know/</ref>\n\nThe club is hopeful that building work will commence at the end of the 2019-20 season. The new, modern, state-of-the-art structure will see the City Ground's capacity become the highest in the East Midlands, reaching 38,000 after completion.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nottinghamforest.co.uk/news/2019/february/major-stadium-redevelopment-to-go-ahead-at-nottingham-forest|title=Major Redevelopment of the City Ground|publisher=Nottingham Forest Football Club|date=28 Feb 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Preston North End===\n\n* Stadium: [[Deepdale]]\n* Capacity: 23,404<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.efl.com/clubs-and-competitions/sky-bet-championship/clubs/preston-north-end/|title=EFL Official Website - Preston North End|website=www.efl.com|access-date=2019-12-18}}</ref>\n*''Current stadium status'': Reconstructed.\n\n[[Preston North End F.C.|Preston NE]] completed its Invincibles Stand in 2008. [[Deepdale|Deepdale's]] capacity is 24,000.<ref name=\"Dspace.dial.pipex.com\">{{cite web |url=http://footballgroundguide.com/preston_north_end/ |title=Internet Football Ground Guide \u2013 Deepdale, Preston North End FC |publisher=Football Ground Guide |accessdate=13 October 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131017095046/http://www.footballgroundguide.com/preston_north_end/ |archivedate=17 October 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> The quadrants could possibly be linked to create a larger bowl configuration of 30,000.\n\n===Queens Park Rangers===\n\n* Stadium: [[Loftus Road]]\n* Capacity: 18,439<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.efl.com/clubs-and-competitions/sky-bet-championship/clubs/queens-park-rangers/|title=EFL Official Website - Queens Park Rangers|website=www.efl.com|access-date=2019-12-18}}</ref>\n*''Current stadium status'': Reconstructed.\n\n[[Queens Park Rangers F.C.|Queens Park Rangers]] have long harboured ambitions of playing in a larger stadium, with relocation first being considered in the 1990s, after they were founder members of the Premier League, although originally the redevelopment option was taken, with Loftus Road being converted into an all-seater stadium with its capacity below 20,000.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.qpr1st.co.uk/newspages/news030501.htm |title=QPR 1st Front Page |publisher=Qpr1st.co.uk |date= |accessdate=14 April 2010}}</ref> This will either be done by expanding their existing [[Loftus Road]] ground from its current 19,000 all-seater capacity or by locating to a new stadium elsewhere in West London, with a ground share in [[White City, London|White City]] with [[Fulham F.C.|Fulham]] commonly mentioned.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.queensparkrangersfc.com/newsnov1605.htm |title=Archived copy |access-date=5 April 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080519004538/http://www.queensparkrangersfc.com/newsnov1605.htm |archive-date=19 May 2008 |url-status=dead }}</ref> QPR achieved promotion to the Premier League in 2011, and owner Tony Fernandes announced in November 2011 that the club were looking for sites in west London to build a new stadium, with a capacity around 40,000.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/15919454 |title=QPR looking for sites in west London to build a new stadium |publisher=BBC |date=28 November 2011 |accessdate=8 March 2012}}</ref> The planned stadium is called [[New Queens Park]].\n\n===Reading===\n\n* Stadium: [[Madejski Stadium]]\n* Capacity: 24,161<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.efl.com/clubs-and-competitions/sky-bet-championship/clubs/reading/|title=EFL Official Website - Reading|website=www.efl.com|access-date=2019-12-18}}</ref>\n*''Current stadium status'': New.\n\n[[Reading F.C.|Reading]] announced plans for the expansion of the [[Madejski Stadium]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/berkshire/content/articles/2006/10/11/stadium_expansion_feature.shtml |title=Berkshire \u2013 Sport \u2013 Madejski Stadium expansion plans |publisher=BBC |date= |accessdate=14 April 2010}}</ref> The proposal involves increasing the stadium to 38,000 seats by expanding all stands except the West Stand, and rebuilding the roof.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.footballgroundguide.com/reading.htm#Future%20Developments |title=Internet Football Grounds Guide \u2013 Madejski Stadium, Reading FC |publisher=Footballgroundguide.com |date= |accessdate=14 April 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110519180431/http://www.footballgroundguide.com/reading.htm#Future%20Developments |archive-date=19 May 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> These plans were dependent on Reading staying in the Premiership.;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rugbynetwork.net/boards/read/s97.htm?99,8947029 |title=The Craic www.londonirish.org \u2013 Madejski Stadium Expansion |publisher=Rugbynetwork.net |date= |accessdate=14 April 2010}}</ref> following relegation in 2008, the plans are uncertain. But since Reading were promoted back to the Premier League in 2012 after winning the Championship the plans look to be on as new owner Anton Zingarevich said he would extend the stadium if Reading stay in the Premier League after their first season back. A new railway station [[Reading GreenPark railway station|Reading GreenPark]] was opening near to the ground,<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20071211225018/http://www.greenpark.co.uk/factfile/newreadingstation.shtml GreenPark \u2013 Reading GreenPark Station]}</ref> but was later cancelled.<ref name=\"Millward 2011\">{{cite news|last=Millward|first=David|title=Green Park station plan hits the buffers|url=http://www.getreading.co.uk/news/local-news/green-park-station-plan-hits-4208736|accessdate=13 October 2013|newspaper=Get Reading|date=27 October 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe Madejski Stadium was opened in 1998, having first been proposed in 1994 as Reading climbed up the league and construction of an all-seater stadium was necessary. [[Elm Park (stadium)|Elm Park]] was deemed unsuitable for renovation due to its confined location and the ambitions of chairman [[John Madejski]] to establish Reading in the top flight (although promotion was not achieved until 2006), so the decision to build a new stadium was made.\n\n===Sheffield Wednesday===\n\n* Stadium: [[Hillsborough Stadium|Hillsborough]]\n* Capacity: 39,732<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.efl.com/clubs-and-competitions/sky-bet-championship/clubs/sheffield-wednesday/|title=EFL Official Website - Sheffield Wednesday|website=www.efl.com|access-date=2019-12-18}}</ref>\n*''Current stadium status'': Reconstructed.\n\n[[Sheffield Wednesday F.C.|Sheffield Wednesday]] announced in the summer of 2009 plans for a [[Hillsborough Stadium#Stadium upgrade plans|\u00a322m upgrade of the stadium]] and an increase in capacity to 44,825 with no viewing restrictions. Should this happen, it will bring the stadium up to [[FIFA]] standards for hosting [[FIFA World Cup|World Cup]] matches.\n\nTo remove any viewing restrictions the current pillars that support the roof of the [[Hillsborough Stadium#Spion Kop|Kop]] and [[Hillsborough Stadium#West Stand|West Stand]] will be removed. An 'iconic' roof structure will support the Kop's roof while the West Stand will have a completely new roof. The [[Hillsborough Stadium#North West Corner|North West Terrace]] will get a roof and a corner of seating will be added between the Kop and [[Hillsborough Stadium#North Stand|North Stand]] with a roof. The current layout of tiers on the West Stand will be radically changed and a new tier of seats will be added as well as a 'new specific learning zone' between the new upper tier and present upper tier. The mega-store and gymnasium behind the North Stand will be demolished and the North Stand will be expanded to create the 'biggest classroom in Europe' as well as 'enterprise zones' and 17 boxes. The [[Hillsborough Stadium#South Stand|South Stand]] floor plan and stadium surroundings will be improved to comply with FIFA requirements. Stadium parking and access will be improved as will the exterior appearance of all stands.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://world.swfc.co.uk/page/News/0,,10304~1759975,00.html |title=Hillsborough \u2013 a vision of the future |date=16 December 2009 |work=swfc.co.uk |access-date=19 August 2009 |publisher=Sheffield Wednesday F.C. |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n[[Hillsborough Stadium|Hillsborough]] became all-seated for the start of the 1993\u201394 season when the Kop and North West Corner were both seated. The Leppings Lane terrace was seated for the start of the 1991\u201392 season \u2013 just over two years since the [[Hillsborough disaster|disaster which occurred on it]].\n\n===Stoke City===\n\n* Stadium: [[Bet365 Stadium]]\n* Capacity: 30,089<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.efl.com/clubs-and-competitions/sky-bet-championship/clubs/stoke-city/|title=EFL Official Website - Stoke City|website=www.efl.com|access-date=2019-12-18}}</ref>\n*''Current stadium status'': New.\n\n[[Stoke City F.C.|Stoke City]] have played at the venue now known as [[bet365 Stadium]] since 1997, replacing [[Victoria Ground]] as their home stadium. Construction of the stadium cost \u00a314.7million and construction works took about 10 months to complete. The bet365 Stadium opened with a capacity of 27,740 spectators, which was reduced from 28,384 due to segregation between the home and away fans.\n\nIn 2009, the club unveiled plans to expand the stadium by filling in one or two of the stadium's open corners. This would add around 3,000 seats, taking the total capacity of the stadium to over 30,000. Filling in one corner would cost approximately \u00a33 million. In November 2009, chairman [[Peter Coates]] said that the club would make a decision to expand the stadium capacity at the end of the season and was dependent on the club's [[Premier League]] survival. These plans were revived in 2010 and 2012, but the club decided not to expand on both occasions.\n\nFinally in April 2016, the club announced that work to fill in the south-east corner would begin the following January. Construction of the new corner commenced in January 2017 and was completed in time for the start of the 2017\u201318 season. This added around 1,800 seats and took the stadium's capacity to just over 30,000.<ref>http://www.stokesentinel.co.uk/work-to-start-on-major-bet365-stadium-expansion/story-30089470-detail/story.html</ref>\n\n===Swansea City===\n\n* Stadium: [[Liberty Stadium]]\n* Capacity: 21,088<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.efl.com/clubs-and-competitions/sky-bet-championship/clubs/swansea-city/|title=EFL Official Website - Swansea City|website=www.efl.com|access-date=2019-12-18}}</ref>\n*''Current stadium status'': New.\n\n[[Swansea City A.F.C.|Swansea]] moved to the purpose built 20,520 all-seater stadium [[Liberty Stadium]] in 2005, several years after relocation was first planned. This replaced [[Vetch Field]] which had been their home since they were founded and was unsuitable for expansion, and would have had a low all-seater capacity, although relocation plans were first formulated at a time when Swansea were in the league's fourth tier.\n\nThe club's current stadium is designed to allow expansion to over 40,000 seats. Construction commenced in the autumn of 2003 with the opening game at the stadium being a friendly between Swansea and [[Fulham F.C.|Fulham]] on 23 July 2005.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.swanseacity.net/club/liberty_stadium |title=Liberty Stadium |publisher=Swanseacity.net |date=1 May 2012 |accessdate=13 October 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2013, with a third season in the Premier League being secured, they submitted plans to increase the stadium capacity to 33,000, an increase of around 11,000.\n\n===West Bromwich Albion===\n\n* Stadium: [[The Hawthorns]]\n* Capacity: 26,850<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.efl.com/clubs-and-competitions/sky-bet-championship/clubs/west-bromwich-albion/|title=EFL Official Website - West Bromwich Albion|website=www.efl.com|access-date=2019-12-18}}</ref>\n*''Current stadium status'': Reconstructed.\n\nIn spite of the club playing in the Premier League for all but five seasons since 2002, the capacity of [[The Hawthorns]] has been reduced over previous years due to a redevelopment of the West Stand (formerly the Halfords Land Stand). Chairman Jeremy Piece announced at the end of the 2010\u201311 season plans to increase the capacity of the Hawthorns to 30,000 over 3 years. It is not yet clear how this will be achieved; however, it could mean rebuilding the Halfords Lane End or rebuilding the East Stand corners. The current capacity of just under 27,000 was first reached in 1994, when The Hawthorns became all-seater. {{Citation needed|date=May 2010}}\n\n=== Wigan Athletic ===\n\n* Stadium: [[DW Stadium]]\n* Capacity: 25,113<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.efl.com/clubs-and-competitions/sky-bet-championship/clubs/wigan-athletic/|title=EFL Official Website - Wigan Athletic|website=www.efl.com|access-date=2019-12-18}}</ref>\n* ''Current stadium status'': New.\n\n==League One==\n\n=== Accrington Stanley ===\n\n* Stadium: [[Crown Ground|Wham Stadium]]\n* Capacity: 5,450<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.efl.com/clubs-and-competitions/sky-bet-league-one/clubs/accrington-stanley/|title=EFL Official Website - Accrington Stanley|website=www.efl.com|access-date=2019-12-18}}</ref>\n*''Current stadium status'': Reconstructed.\n\n===AFC Wimbledon===\n\n* Stadium: [[Kingsmeadow]]\n* Capacity: 4,850<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.efl.com/clubs-and-competitions/sky-bet-league-one/clubs/afc-wimbledon/|title=EFL Official Website - AFC Wimbledon|website=www.efl.com|access-date=2019-12-18}}</ref>\n*''Current stadium status'': Reconstructed; preparing to build new ground (New [[New Plough Lane|Plough Lane]]).\n\nOn their foundation in 2002, [[AFC Wimbledon]] moved in with [[Kingstonian]] at [[Kingsmeadow]], purchasing the ground.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/2888371.stm |title=AFC Wimbledon bid for new home|work=BBC News|date=26 March 2003|accessdate=14 April 2010}}</ref> They do have long-term plans to relocate the club to the [[London Borough of Merton]], the traditional home of [[Wimbledon F.C.]], from whom they originated. There was speculation that the club might try to build a new ground at the [[Wimbledon Stadium]] site, currently used for greyhound racing, which was put up for sale in September 2007.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://betting.betfair.com/greyhound-racing/wimbledon-racing/are-afc-wimbledon-going-back-t-130907.html |title=Are AFC Wimbledon going back to the dogs?|publisher=Betfair|date=13 September 2007|accessdate=14 April 2010|first=Darrell|last=Williams}}</ref>\n\nThis speculation eventually proved true; AFC Wimbledon received final approval to build a new ground there in September 2016. The [[New Plough Lane|new stadium]] will initially seat 11,000 and is planned to be open for the 2020\u201321 season.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/sport/football/afc-wimbledon-cleared-to-build-new-stadium-on-plough-lane-as-secretary-of-state-opts-not-to-call-in-a3355401.html |title=AFC Wimbledon cleared to build new stadium on Plough Lane as Secretary of State opts not to 'call in' plans |first=Sam |last=Long |newspaper=[[London Evening Standard]] |date=27 September 2016 |accessdate=23 November 2016}}</ref>\n\nDemolition of the old [[Plough Lane]] begun on 16 March 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.afcwimbledon.co.uk/news/2018/march/demolition-work-starts-to-clear-the-way-for-new-stadium/|title=Demolition work starts to clear the way for new stadium|website=www.afcwimbledon.co.uk|language=en-gb|access-date=2019-12-18}}</ref> The new [[New Plough Lane|Plough Lane]] scheduled to be completed for 2020/21 season.\n\n===Blackpool===\n\n* Stadium: [[Bloomfield Road]]\n* Capacity: 17,338<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.efl.com/clubs-and-competitions/sky-bet-league-one/clubs/blackpool2/|title=EFL Official Website - Blackpool|website=www.efl.com|access-date=2019-12-19}}</ref>\n*''Current stadium status'': Reconstructed.\n\nThe South Stand was originally projected to be complete by May 2009.<ref name=\"BFC1340591\">{{cite news|title=Official Club Statement |work=blackpoolfc.co.uk |publisher=Blackpool F.C. |date=8 July 2008 |url=http://www.blackpoolfc.co.uk/page/NewsDetail/0,,10432~1340591,00.html |accessdate=19 August 2008 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120503100042/http://www.blackpoolfc.co.uk/page/NewsDetail/0%2C%2C10432~1340591%2C00.html |archivedate=3 May 2012 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> On 14 November 2009 it was revealed that the football club hope to work with [[Urban Regeneration Company]], to build a new East Stand that would contain both seating and office/retail space rather than as originally planned for just seating. This will mean a larger stand is to be built which will require additional land to be acquired.<ref name=\"Gazette5824539\">{{cite news|last=Parkinson|first=Shelagh| title = Oyston pledge to build final Seasiders stand| newspaper = Blackpool Gazette| date = 14 November 2009| url = http://www.blackpoolgazette.co.uk/news/local/oyston-pledge-to-build-final-seasiders-stand-1-386660| accessdate = 13 October 2013 }}</ref> The new South Stand was opened in March 2010 and is similar in design to the Stanley Matthews and North stands.\n\nOn 13 May 2010, Karl Oyston pledged that construction of the East Stand would begin immediately, so long as they gain promotion to the [[Premier League]].\n<ref name=\"BFC East Stand\">{{cite news | title = Oyston's East Stand Premier Promise| newspaper = Blackpool Gazette | date = 13 May 2010 | url = http://www.blackpoolgazette.co.uk/sport/oyston-s-east-stand-premier-promise-1-842375| accessdate = 13 October 2013}}</ref> On 14 June the temporary seating comprising the East Stand was removed, which was replaced with a 5,070-seat covered temporary stand, which raised the capacity to around 15,500.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.blackpoolgazette.co.uk/sport/pool-reveal-east-stand-plans-1-842959|title=Pool reveal East Stand plans|work=Blackpool Gazette|date=11 June 2010|accessdate=13 October 2013}}</ref>\n\nFrom 28 August 2010, the capacity of Bloomfield Road was raised to 16,220 after the new temporary East Stand was completed.<ref name=\"bc\">{{cite web|title=Agenda Information for Public Protection Sub-Committee meeting |work=Gen Safety Cert |publisher=Blackpool Council |url=http://www.blackpool.gov.uk/Services/M-R/MeetingsMinutesandAgendas/Agenda.htm?GUID=927A79BE-1DCF-4423-8E77-A96006CB9775 |archive-url=http://webarchive.nationalarchives.gov.uk/20110930024940/http://www.blackpool.gov.uk/Services/M-R/MeetingsMinutesandAgendas/Agenda.htm?GUID=927A79BE-1DCF-4423-8E77-A96006CB9775 |url-status=dead |archive-date=30 September 2011 |accessdate=13 October 2013 }}</ref>\n\nThe South-East corner of Bloomfield Road was \"filled-in\" in 2012. This increased the capacity by around 500 seats.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.footballgroundguide.com/leagues/england/league-one/bloomfield-road-blackpool.html|title=Bloomfield Road - Blackpool FC - Football Ground Guide|website=www.footballgroundguide.com}}</ref>\n\n===Bolton Wanderers===\n\n* Stadium: [[University of Bolton Stadium]]\n* Capacity:28,723<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.efl.com/clubs-and-competitions/sky-bet-league-one/clubs/bolton-wanderers/|title=EFL Official Website - Bolton Wanderers|website=www.efl.com|access-date=2019-12-19}}</ref>\n*''Current stadium status'': New.\n[[Bolton Wanderers F.C.|Bolton Wanderers]] moved into their new [[University of Bolton Stadium]] in 1997, having previously played at [[Burnden Park]] since 1895. The University of Bolton Stadium has an all-seated capacity of 28,723. The plans for relocation were formulated in the early 1990s, when the club was still in the third tier of the English league but had ambitions of reaching the top flight (achieved in 1995). Burnden Park was an antiquated structure that would have been unsuitable for modernisation, especially as a section of terracing had been sold off in the mid 1980s to make way for a supermarket, and so the decision was made to build a new stadium elsewhere.\n\n=== Bristol Rovers ===\n\n* Stadium: [[Memorial Stadium (Bristol)|Memorial Stadium]]\n* Capacity: 12,296<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.efl.com/clubs-and-competitions/sky-bet-league-one/clubs/bristol-rovers/|title=EFL Official Website - Bristol Rovers|website=www.efl.com|access-date=2019-12-19}}</ref>\n*''Current stadium status'': Reconstructed.\n[[Bristol Rovers F.C.|Bristol Rovers]] had gained planning permission to move into a purpose-built 21,700 all seater stadium at the [[University of the West of England|University of the West of England's]] Frenchay campus, on the outskirts of Bristol.<ref>{{cite news |title=Bristol Rovers new stadium plans approved |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-gloucestershire-18898457 |work=BBC |publisher=bbc.co.uk |date=19 July 2012 |accessdate=3 February 2013}}</ref> [[UWE Stadium]] would have replaced the club's current [[Memorial Stadium (Bristol)|Memorial Stadium]] home which was to have been demolished and sold to [[Sainsbury's]] who had planning permission to build a new store on the site.<ref>{{cite news |title=Bristol Rovers' ground Sainsbury's store bid approved |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-bristol-21048441 |work=BBC |publisher=bbc.co.uk |date=16 January 2013 |accessdate=3 February 2013}}</ref> The sale of the Memorial Stadium to Sainsbury's would have partly funded the UWE Stadium project. Following numerous delays (including a Judicial Review launched by local members of the Green Party) it emerged Sainsbury's were attempting to terminate their contract to buy the site.<ref>{{cite news |title=Bristol Rovers new stadium could be delayed by legal move |url=http://www.bristolpost.co.uk/EXCLUSIVE-Bristol-Rovers-new-stadium-delayed/story-19780633-detail/story.html |work=[[Bristol Post]] |publisher=bristolpost.co.uk |date=11 September 2013 |accessdate=15 November 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131202230015/http://www.bristolpost.co.uk/EXCLUSIVE-Bristol-Rovers-new-stadium-delayed/story-19780633-detail/story.html |archivedate=2 December 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Sainsbury's eventually won a high court case with Rovers pull out of the contract, meaning Rovers would not receive the funding to build the new stadium.<ref>{{cite web|title=Bristol Rovers lose case over Sainsbury's stadium deal |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-bristol-33503419 |work=BBC News |date=13 July 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe club were later bought by [[Jordan]]ian Al-Qadi family<ref>{{cite web|title=NEW OWNERS FOR BRISTOL ROVERS |url=http://www.bristolrovers.co.uk/news/article/new-owners-for-bristol-rovers-2962972.aspx |publisher=Bristol Rovers F.C. |date=19 February 2016 |accessdate=21 April 2016}}</ref> with new president, [[Wael al-Qadi]] saying a new stadium is a \"key requirement\" for the new owners.<ref>{{cite web |title=BRISTOL ROVERS TAKEOVER: Jordanians say new stadium required to make ownership \"flourish\" |url=http://www.bristolpost.co.uk/BRISTOL-ROVERS-TAKEOVER-Jordanians-say-new/story-28770258-detail/story.html |author=James McNamara |work=Bristol Post |date=19 February 2016 |accessdate=21 April 2016 }}{{Dead link|date=July 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nThis turned out not to be the case, as in February 2018 Wael Al-Qadi said the club's plan was now to redevelop the Memorial Stadium stand-by-stand,<ref>{{cite web|title=Wael Al-Qadi gives update about Memorial Stadium redevelopment and Bristol Rovers' new training ground |url=https://www.bristolpost.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/wael-al-qadi-gives-update-1231868 |publisher=Bristol Live |date=19 February 2018 |accessdate=23 November 2018}}</ref> but then in July 2018 new CEO Martyn Starnes confirmed the club would only be adding one extra temporary tented stand during the 2018/19 season<ref>{{cite web|title=New Bristol Rovers CEO Martyn Starnes clarifies long-term stadium plan |url=https://www.bristolpost.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/martyn-starnes-bristol-rovers-stadium-1781565 |publisher=Bristol Live |date=16 July 2018 |accessdate=23 November 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Burton Albion ===\n\n* Stadium: [[Pirelli Stadium]]\n* Capacity: 6,912<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.efl.com/clubs-and-competitions/sky-bet-league-one/clubs/burton-albion/|title=EFL Official Website - Burton Albion|website=www.efl.com|access-date=2019-12-19}}</ref>\n* ''Current stadium status'': Reconstructed.\n\n===Coventry City===\n\n* Stadium: [[St Andrew's (stadium)|St Andrew's Trillion Trophy Stadium]]\n* Capacity: 29,409<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.efl.com/clubs-and-competitions/sky-bet-league-one/clubs/coventry-city/|title=EFL Official Website - Coventry City|website=www.efl.com|access-date=2019-12-19}}</ref>\n*''Current stadium status'': Reconstructed. Ground sharing with Birmingham City's [[St Andrew's (stadium)|St Andrew's Trillion Trophy Stadium]] for 2019/20 season.\n\n[[Coventry City F.C.|Coventry City]] moved to the 32,500 seater [[Ricoh Arena]] in 2005,<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://world.ccfc.co.uk/page/RicohArena/0,,10269,00.html |title=Ricoh Arena |date=17 December 2007 |work=ccfc.premiumtv.co.uk |access-date=14 April 2010 |publisher=Coventry City F.C.}}</ref> leaving their historic home [[Highfield Road]] which was the first all-seater ground in England. Coventry had long planned a move to a purpose-built 45,000-seat stadium, with original suggestions including a retractable roof and pitch \u00e0 la Dutch club [[SBV Vitesse|Vitesse Arnhem]]. [[Coventry]] had even hoped to become the home of the new national stadium, joining [[Birmingham]] and [[London]] in the race to be the [[Wembley Stadium|new Wembley]], but were unsuccessful in their bid. The Ricoh Arena includes a vast exhibition centre built onto the main stand. Despite a slight increase in attendance figures since moving from Highfield Road, Coventry City's continued failure to regain their place among the upper echelons of the League structure means there are always many empty seats at the Ricoh Arena.\n\nA long-winded saga involving unpaid rent stretching back to August 2012<ref>{{cite news|date=9 August 2012|title=Coventry City could face court over Ricoh Arena rent bill|work=BBC News|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-coventry-warwickshire-19191323|accessdate=18 May 2013}}</ref> resulted in the club being \"locked out\" of the Ricoh Arena in May 2013.<ref>{{cite news|date=3 May 2013|title=Coventry City: Ricoh Arena exit contingency plans in place|work=BBC Sport|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/england/22396786|accessdate=18 May 2013}}</ref> In response, the club announced that they planned to build a new stadium and move out of the Ricoh Arena.<ref>{{cite news|date=18 May 2013|title=Coventry City plan to build new stadium after Ricoh Arena dispute|work=BBC Sport|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/22581748|accessdate=18 May 2013}}</ref> They eventually returned to the Ricoh for the 2014\u201315 season. Coventry City are now tenants of the [[rugby union]] [[Premiership Rugby|Premiership]] side [[Wasps RFC|Wasps]], which purchased the facility in late 2014. However, the club's owners are intent on developing their own 20,000 capacity stadium within the city limits by 2020.\n\nOn 7 June 2019 it was reported that talks between SISU and Wasps had again broken down meaning that Coventry would have to play their [[2019\u201320 EFL League One|2019\u201320]] \"home\" matches at [[Birmingham City F.C.|Birmingham City's]] [[St Andrew's (stadium)|St Andrew's]] ground.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/48557082|title=Coventry City to groundshare with Birmingham City for 2019-20 season|date=2019-06-07|access-date=2019-12-19|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\n===Doncaster Rovers===\n\n* Stadium: [[Keepmoat Stadium]]\n* Capacity: 15,231<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.efl.com/clubs-and-competitions/sky-bet-league-one/clubs/doncaster-rovers/|title=EFL Official Website - Doncaster Rovers|website=www.efl.com|access-date=2019-12-19}}</ref>\n*''Current stadium status'': New.\nIn December 2006 the [[Keepmoat Stadium]] in [[Doncaster]] held its first sporting fixture. even though it did not have its official opening until August 2007 when they played Manchester United in a pre-season friendly.\n\n===Fleetwood Town===\n\n* Stadium: [[Highbury Stadium (Fleetwood)|Highbury Stadium]] (Fleetwood)\n* Capacity: 5,327<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.efl.com/clubs-and-competitions/sky-bet-league-one/clubs/fleetwood-town/|title=EFL Official Website - Fleetwood Town|website=www.efl.com|access-date=2019-12-19}}</ref>\n*''Current stadium status'': Reconstructed.\n[[Fleetwood Town F.C.|Fleetwood Town]] have invested heavily in [[Highbury Stadium, Fleetwood|Highbury Stadium]] recently following many promotions and increased attendances in recent years. In February 2007 the new Percy Ronson Stand was opened. A \u00a3500,000-plus development the stand is all terracing, and holds 1,243. In July 2007, further plans for the stadium development were announced which included three new stands. The plans were finalized in December 2007 and in March 2008, planning permission was given for the first phase, construction of the north and west terraces. Construction began in May 2008, and was completed for the start of the 2008\u201309 season. In May 2010, a couple of days before Fleetwood's playoff final at the stadium work began on the new west stand. The stadium was completed in Spring 2011 and opened on 16 April 2011 for Fleetwood's game against [[Altrincham F.C.]], which they won 3\u20131. The stadium's capacity is now 5,500; it is the [[List of English football stadiums by capacity|118th largest stadium by capacity in England]] and the sixteenth largest in their [[Conference National|league]].<ref name=\"ftfccapacity\">\n{{cite web |url=http://www.fleetwoodtownfc.com/News/news.php?subaction=showfull&id=1302104205&archive=&start_from=&ucat=1& |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110822090855/http://www.fleetwoodtownfc.com/News/news.php?subaction=showfull&id=1302104205&archive=&start_from=&ucat=1& |archivedate=22 August 2011 |title=Highbury Stadium Capacity|publisher= Fleetwood Town FC|date=6 April 2011 |accessdate=13 October 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Gillingham===\n\n* Stadium: [[Priestfield Stadium|Priestfield]]\n* Capacity: 11,582<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.efl.com/clubs-and-competitions/sky-bet-league-one/clubs/gillingham/|title=EFL Official Website - Gillingham|website=www.efl.com|access-date=2019-12-19}}</ref>\n*''Current stadium status'': Reconstructed.\n[[Priestfield Stadium]] has been entirely rebuilt since 1997, but [[Gillingham F.C.|Gillingham]] chairman [[Paul Scally]] has made clear his intention of moving to a new stadium, despite Gillingham dropping from the Championship to League Two since 2005.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/g/gillingham/3130036.stm|title=Scally considers Gills future|publisher=BBC|accessdate=5 November 2007|date=22 September 2003}}</ref> Although the club have since bounced back to [[Football League One|League One]], and subsequently being relegated back into League Two the following season, the chairman has announced plans for a new stadium are on hold due to the current financial climate. In 2012 the club announced plans to build a 15,000\u201318,000-seater stadium at the Mill Hill site off of Yokusuka Way. Also on the 40-acre complex would be a supermarket, a hotel, a tennis academy, fast food restaurants, a nursery and a fitness centre.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.kentonline.co.uk/kentonline/home/2012/april/21/new_plans_for_gills_stadium.aspx|title=New plans for Gillingham FC stadium unveiled|date=20 April 2012|work=kentonline.co.uk|first=Alan|last=McGuinness|publisher=KM Group}}</ref>\n\n===Ipswich Town===\n\n* Stadium: [[Portman Road]]\n* Capacity: 30,311<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.efl.com/clubs-and-competitions/sky-bet-league-one/clubs/ipswich-town/|title=EFL Official Website - Ipswich Town|website=www.efl.com|access-date=2019-12-19}}</ref>\n*''Current stadium status'': Reconstructed.\n\nIpswich have plans to modernise [[Portman Road]] stadium should they be promoted back to the [[Premier League]], via 'Project Leap'. This would involve the area for the 3,000 seats needed for Premier League away teams, as the current area for away fans is not big enough, and would mean expanding into premium season ticket holders seating. They have played in the league's second tier continuously since 2002, longer than any other club currently in that division.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.twtd.co.uk/ipswich-town-news/19122|title=Town Already Planning for Great Leap Forward|date=3 September 2011|publisher=TWTD.co.uk|accessdate=13 October 2013}}</ref>\n\n=== Lincoln City ===\n\n* Stadium: [[Sincil Bank]]\n* Capacity: 10,120<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.efl.com/clubs-and-competitions/sky-bet-league-one/clubs/lincoln-city/|title=EFL Official Website - Lincoln City|website=www.efl.com|access-date=2019-12-19}}</ref>\n* ''Current stadium status'': Reconstructed.\n\n===Milton Keynes Dons===\n\n* Stadium: [[Stadium MK]]\n* Capacity: 30,500<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.efl.com/clubs-and-competitions/sky-bet-league-one/clubs/mk-dons/|title=EFL Official Website - Milton Keynes Dons|website=www.efl.com|access-date=2019-12-19}}</ref>\n*''Current stadium status'': New.\n\n[[Milton Keynes Dons F.C.|Milton Keynes Dons]] opened their [[Stadium MK]] home in 2007.  The original opening capacity was 22,000.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/w/wimbledon/6366309.stm|title=Milton Keynes stadium is on track|date=15 February 2007|work=BBC News|accessdate=14 April 2010}}</ref> Plans exist to increase the capacity to between 46,000 and 55,000 seats, but with England's failure to win the bidding for the [[2018 FIFA World Cup]] any improvements to increase the stadium's attendance would be dependent on promotion to the [[Premier League]] at least.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.mkdons.com/page/NewsDetail/0,,10420~1790528,00.html|title=World Cup Stadium Plans Unveiled|date=14 September 2009|work=mkdons.com|accessdate=7 February 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110510203941/http://www.mkdons.com/page/NewsDetail/0%2C%2C10420~1790528%2C00.html|archivedate=10 May 2011|publisher=Milton Keynes Dons F.C.|df=dmy}}</ref> In November 2011, MK Dons announced that they would expand Stadium MK to 32,000<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/15636043.stm|title=Stadium MK expansion to 32,000 in \u00a356m plan|date=8 November 2011|work=BBC News|accessdate=10 November 2011}}</ref> for the [[2012\u201313 in English football|2012\u201313 season]]. However, it was only at the end of the season that development began on the upper tier seating.\n\n===Oxford United===\n\n* Stadium: [[Kassam Stadium]]\n* Capacity: 12,500<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.efl.com/clubs-and-competitions/sky-bet-league-one/clubs/oxford-united/|title=EFL Official Website - Oxford United|website=www.efl.com|access-date=2019-12-19}}</ref>\n*''Current stadium status'': New.\n[[Oxford United F.C.|Oxford United]] have plans to purchase the [[Kassam Stadium]] and to build a fourth side to it. Now that they have regained [[the Football League|Football League]] status and attendances rise to sufficiently justify it, this is increasingly likely.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.footballgroundguide.com/oxford_united/ |title=Oxford United FC, Kassam Stadium |publisher=Football Ground Guide |accessdate=13 October 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131018210518/http://www.footballgroundguide.com/oxford_united/ |archivedate=18 October 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/o/oxford_utd/8749002.stm |title=Owner Ian Lenagan upbeat on Oxford future |work=BBC Sport |date=19 June 2010 |accessdate=19 June 2010}}</ref>\nThe stadium was first planned in 1995 and construction began in 1997, but financial difficulties saw construction suspended shortly after it begin, and the relocation from the dilapidated [[Manor Ground, Oxford|Manor Ground]] was not completed until 2001. By then, two relegations in three seasons had dragged the club from Division One to Division Three, coinciding with a fall in attendances, and this was the reason for the stadium initially only having three sides incorporating 12,500 seats. The planned fourth stand would take the capacity to around 16,000.\n\n===Peterborough United===\n\n* Stadium: [[London Road Stadium|ABAX Stadium]]\n* Capacity: 15,314<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.efl.com/clubs-and-competitions/sky-bet-league-one/clubs/peterborough-united/|title=EFL Official Website - Peterborough United|website=www.efl.com|access-date=2019-12-19}}</ref>\n*''Current stadium status'': Reconstructed.\n[[Peterborough United F.C.|Peterborough United]] have played at [[London Road Stadium|London Road]] since 1934, although due to its age and the fact that it has terracing the club are considering options to move. A number of alternative sites have been put forward in [[Peterborough#Local government|Peterborough council's]] January 2009 [[Area Action Plan]] for the City Centre Area.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.opportunitypeterborough.co.uk/IGS/21_01_2009/CCAAP%20Documents/07_CCAAP_Part3_Culture_Sport.pdf |title=Peterborough CC City Centre Area Action Plan \u2013 Culture and Sport |format=PDF |accessdate=14 April 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131216220424/http://opportunitypeterborough.co.uk/IGS/21_01_2009/CCAAP%20Documents/07_CCAAP_Part3_Culture_Sport.pdf |archivedate=16 December 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> This document's consultation period has now closed and thus the publication of the final AAP is awaited for more information on preferred sites for a new stadium.\n\nAt the end of October during the 2012\u201313 season, demolition of the away terrace (Moyes End) will commence. This making way for a new all seater stand, but leaving visiting supporters with only 3\u20134 thousand seats for the remainder of the 2012\u201313 season.\n\n===Portsmouth===\n\n* Stadium: [[Fratton Park]]\n* Capacity: 20,620<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.efl.com/clubs-and-competitions/sky-bet-league-one/clubs/portsmouth/|title=EFL Official Website - Portsmouth|website=www.efl.com|access-date=2019-12-19}}</ref>\n*''Current stadium status'': Reconstructed.\n\n[[Portsmouth F.C.|Portsmouth]] had the smallest stadium in the [[Premier League]] during the [[Premier League 2007-08|2007\u201308 season]]. The board planned to remedy this by rebuilding [[Fratton Park]] turning the pitch round 90 degrees. This was then abandoned in favour of a 35,000 'Pompey Village' plan, and then superseded by the ambitious proposal ship-like Portsmouth Dockland Stadium which was planned to hold 36,000 seated spectators, hoping to have ready in 2011.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/p/portsmouth/6591049.stm|title=Pompey announce new stadium plan|work=BBC News|date=25 April 2007|accessdate=14 April 2010}}</ref> However, it has been revealed that Portsmouth F.C. are now preparing to build a 36,000-seater stadium at [[Horsea Island]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/p/portsmouth/6591049.stm |title=Football &#124; My Club &#124; Portsmouth &#124; Pompey announce Horsea Island stadium plan |publisher=BBC |date=25 April 2007 |accessdate=13 October 2013}}</ref>\n\nPortsmouth have been considering relocation since the early 1990s, but had upgraded their stadium to an all-seater capacity as a short-term measure. In May 2009 all stadium relocation plans were put on hold. The club are looking to expand the current Fratton Park stadium by going back to its original plan of turning it around and increasing capacity to 30,000.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.portsmouth.co.uk/news/local/pompey-urged-to-get-on-with-fratton-redevelopment-1-1228906|title=Pompey urged to get on with Fratton redevelopment|work=portsmouth.co.uk|date=20 March 2009|accessdate=13 October 2013}}</ref> However, administration and further relegation means Fratton Park will remain in its same state until the club clear the balance sheet.\n\n=== Rochdale ===\n\n* Stadium: [[Spotland Stadium|The Crown Oil Arena]]\n* Capacity: 10,249<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.efl.com/clubs-and-competitions/sky-bet-league-one/clubs/rochdale/|title=EFL Official Website - Rochdale|website=www.efl.com|access-date=2019-12-19}}</ref>\n* ''Current stadium status'': Reconstructed.\n\n===Rotherham United===\n\n* Stadium: [[New York Stadium|ASSEAL New York Stadium]]\n* Capacity: 12,021<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.efl.com/clubs-and-competitions/sky-bet-league-one/clubs/rotherham-united/|title=EFL Official Website - Rotherham United|website=www.efl.com|access-date=2019-12-19}}</ref>\n*''Current stadium status'': New.\n\nIn 2008 [[Rotherham United F.C.|Rotherham United]] expressed dissatisfaction with their [[Millmoor]] home<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rotherhamunited-mad.co.uk/news/tmnw/we_deserve_better_than_millmoor__brearley_372966/index.shtml|title=We deserve better than Millmoor \u2013 Brearley|date=18 January 2008|work=rotherhamunited-mad.co.uk|accessdate=13 October 2013}}</ref> and began to look into the construction of a new stadium in the town.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thestar.co.uk/features/talks-on-a-new-football-stadium-for-millers-next-to-shopping-centre-1-232890|title=Talks on a new football stadium for Millers next to shopping centre|last=Parkin|first=Ray|date=6 February 2008|work=Sheffield Star|accessdate=13 October 2013|publisher=Johnston Press}}</ref> At the start of the 2008\u201309 season Rotherham United temporarily moved to the [[Don Valley Stadium]] in [[Sheffield]] due to ownership disputes over Millmoor.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.donvalleystadium.co.uk/news/1071/rotherham_united.html|title=Rotherham United Head to Don Valley Stadium|work=donvalleystadium.co.uk|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080604032317/http://www.donvalleystadium.co.uk/news/1071/rotherham_united.html|archivedate=4 June 2008|publisher=Sheffield International Venues}}</ref> [[The Football League]] told the club that they must return to [[Rotherham]] by 2012<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/r/rotherham_utd/7500608.stm|title=Rotherham future remains unclear|date=10 July 2008|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=14 April 2010}}</ref> which they have done.\n\nThe club moved to the 12,000-capacity [[New York Stadium]], which opened in July 2012.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rotherhamadvertiser.co.uk/news/88770/new-stadium-on-target-for-2012-opening.aspx|title=New stadium on target for 2012 opening|last=Beddows|first=David|date=25 February 2011|work=Rotherham Advertiser|accessdate=30 May 2011|publisher=Garnett Dickinson Group}}</ref>\n\n===Shrewsbury Town===\n\n* Stadium: [[New Meadow]]\n* Capacity: 9,875<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.efl.com/clubs-and-competitions/sky-bet-league-one/clubs/shrewsbury-town/|title=EFL Official Website - Shrewsbury Town|website=www.efl.com|access-date=2019-12-19}}</ref>\n*''Current stadium status'': New.\n\n[[Shrewsbury Town F.C.|Shrewsbury Town]] moved to the [[New Meadow]] in Summer 2007.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/shropshire/content/articles/2007/02/14/new_meadow_fan_view_feature.shtml|title=Shropshire \u2013 Sport \u2013 New stadium \u2013 a fan's view|publisher=BBC|date=12 July 2007|accessdate=14 April 2010|first=Sam|last=Morris}}</ref> In November 2007 the club announced that the [[New Meadow]] would be expanded by filling in the corners between the Roland Wycherley Stand, South Stand and West Stand, bringing the overall capacity up to 12,500. Work was hoped to commence summer 2008, however, plans were put on hold to concentrate on events on field.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.footballgroundguide.com/shrewsbury_town.htm |title=Internet Football Ground Guide \u2013 New Meadow, Shrewsbury Town FC |publisher=Footballgroundguide.com |accessdate=14 April 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110519180501/http://www.footballgroundguide.com/shrewsbury_town.htm |archivedate=19 May 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n===Southend United===\n\n* Stadium: [[Roots Hall]] \n* Capacity: 12,392<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.efl.com/clubs-and-competitions/sky-bet-league-one/clubs/southend-united/|title=EFL Official Website - Southend United|website=www.efl.com|access-date=2019-12-19}}</ref>\n*''Current stadium status'': Reconstructed.\n\nBecause [[Roots Hall]] is difficult to expand, [[Southend United F.C.|Southend United]] have committed to moving to a new home at [[Fossetts Farm Stadium|Fossetts Farm]] which will have 22,000 seats. The development proposal was finally given full approval by the [[Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government]] in July 2008.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.southendunited.co.uk/page/NewStadiumDetail/0,,10444~1336808,00.html |title=FINAL APPROVAL GIVEN FOR NEW STADIUM |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090402151838/http://www.southendunited.co.uk/page/NewStadiumDetail/0%2C%2C10444~1336808%2C00.html |archivedate=2 April 2009 |publisher=Southend United F.C. |work=southendunited.co.uk |date=17 July 2008 |accessdate=14 April 2010 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Following delays associated with obtaining the necessary funds, minor changes to the scheme were submitted to and approved by the council. However, by summer 2010, work has yet to commence on the new site as the club continued to suffer from huge financial difficulties. Although supermarket chain Sainsbury's, who intend to build a new hypermarket complex on the Roots Hall site, reached a deal with the club's owners to loan suitable capital to continue its operation, including supplying the cash that allowed the club to avoid several winding-up applications during 2010, there is still no firm date set for the beginning of construction.<ref>{{cite web|author=Footymad Limited |url=http://www.southendunited-mad.co.uk/roll/ed21/fossetts_farm_section/index.shtml |title=Fossetts Farm \u2013 Southend United FC \u2013 Shrimpers24 Index |publisher=Southendunited-mad.co.uk |date= |accessdate=13 October 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Sunderland===\n\n* Stadium: [[Stadium of Light]]\n* Capacity: 49,000<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.efl.com/clubs-and-competitions/sky-bet-league-one/clubs/sunderland/|title=EFL Official Website - Sunderland|website=www.efl.com|access-date=2019-12-19}}</ref>\n*''Current stadium status'': New.\n\n[[Sunderland A.F.C.|Sunderland's]] [[Stadium of Light]] is designed to allow expansion to 64,000 seats. In 2003 the club received planning permission to add another 7,200 seats to the South Stand which would have taken capacity to 56,000 but the plans were put on hold due to Sunderland's relegation.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.footballgroundguide.com/sunderla.htm |title=Internet Football Ground Guide \u2013 Stadium Of Light, Sunderland Football Club |publisher=Footballgroundguide.com |accessdate=14 April 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110519180437/http://www.footballgroundguide.com/sunderla.htm |archivedate=19 May 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> In 2007 chairman [[Niall Quinn]] said the club had no current plans to increase capacity.\n\nThe Stadium of Light was one of the first new stadiums to be built during the modern era, opening in 1997 as replacement for 99-year-old [[Roker Park]], with then chairman [[Bob Murray (businessman)|Bob Murray]] having decided in the early 1990s that a new stadium was the best option as Roker Park was unsuitable for converting into an all-seater stadium as its confined location would have given a capacity much lower than the club would have wanted. The land on which the Stadium of Light would eventually be built was identified as the site for a new stadium by 1995, with the plan for a 34,000-seat stadium being altered to allow for 42,000-seat capacity after promotion to the Premier League was achieved the following year. It initially had more than 42,000 seats but this was taken to more than 48,000 in 2001. The original plan for a new stadium next to the [[Nissan]] [[NMUK|car factory]] was abandoned following objections by the carmaker.\n\n===Tranmere Rovers===\n\n* Stadium: [[Prenton Park]]\n* Capacity: 16,567<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.efl.com/clubs-and-competitions/sky-bet-league-one/clubs/tranmere-rovers/|title=EFL Official Website - Tranmere Rovers|website=www.efl.com|access-date=2019-12-19}}</ref>\n*''Current stadium status'': Reconstructed.\n\n[[Tranmere Rovers F.C.|Tranmere Rovers]] originally had plans to expand [[Prenton Park]]'s capacity to 30,000 should the club have reached the Premier League. With this now looking unlikely, the club are looking to replace their ageing Main Stand for a more modern structure.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.liverpooldailypost.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/eight-acre-parcel-land-holds-key-5514830|title=AGM told land deal key to Tranmere Rovers' long-term future|last=Hilton|first=Nick|date=15 March 2008|newspaper=Liverpool Daily Post}}</ref>\n\nTranmere have been linked with a new stadium as part of the \u00a34.5 Billion \"Wirral Waters\" Scheme, That has recently been given the go ahead. The capacity may be lowered from the current Prenton Park due to dwindling attendances.{{Citation needed|date=August 2011}}\n\n===Wycombe Wanderers===\n\n* Stadium: [[Adams Park]]\n* Capacity: 9,448<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.efl.com/clubs-and-competitions/sky-bet-league-one/clubs/wycombe-wanderers/|title=EFL Official Website - Wycombe Wanderers|website=www.efl.com|access-date=2019-12-19}}</ref>\n*''Current stadium status'': New.\n\nIn 2007 it was announced that [[Wycombe Wanderers F.C.|Wycombe Wanderers]] in partnership with [[Wasps RFC|London Wasps]] were looking to build a new 20,000-capacity ground in [[High Wycombe]] to replace the current [[Adams Park]] (only built in 1990 to replace [[Loakes Park]]) where the capacity is capped, and further expansion is not possible.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.bucksfreepress.co.uk/sport/2099516.wasps_target_wycombe_training_site/|title=Wasps Target Wycombe Training Site|date=8 March 2008|accessdate=13 October 2013|publisher=Bucks Free Press|work=bucksfreepress.co.uk}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://world.wycombewanderers.co.uk/page/LatestNews/0,,10430~1098887,00.html |title=THE VIEW FORWARD &#124; Wycombe Wanderers &#124; News &#124; Latest News &#124; Latest News |date=24 August 2007 |publisher=Wycombme Wanderers FC |access-date=13 October 2013 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==League Two==\n\n=== Bradford City ===\n\n*Stadium: [[Valley Parade]]\n* Capacity: 25,136<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.efl.com/clubs-and-competitions/sky-bet-league-two/clubs/bradford-city/|title=EFL Official Website - Bradford City|website=www.efl.com|access-date=2019-12-19}}</ref>\n* ''Current stadium status'': Reconstructed.\n\n===Cambridge United===\n\n*Stadium: [[Abbey Stadium]]\n* Capacity: 8,127<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.efl.com/clubs-and-competitions/sky-bet-league-two/clubs/cambridge-united/|title=EFL Official Website - Cambridge United|website=www.efl.com|access-date=2019-12-19}}</ref>\n*''Current stadium status'': Reconstructed.\n\n[[Cambridge United F.C.|Cambridge United]] had been investigating the possibility of improving their [[Abbey Stadium]] home, but have abandoned redeveloping the stadium, and are instead proposing a move to a 10,000-capacity stadium and sporting village in one of two new sites. The first proposed site is named NIAB2 \u2013 located on land between Huntingdon Road and Histon Road \u2013 while the second and favoured option is located south of the city in [[Trumpington, Cambridgeshire|Trumpington]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cambridge-news.co.uk/Sport/Cambridge-United/Us-revealed-preferred-choice-for-new-stadium-20122011.htm|archive-url=https://archive.today/20120721031421/http://www.cambridge-news.co.uk/Sport/Cambridge-United/Us-revealed-preferred-choice-for-new-stadium-20122011.htm|url-status=dead|archive-date=21 July 2012|title=U's revealed preferred choice for new stadium|work=Cambridge News|publisher=Yattendon Group plc|date=20 December 2011|accessdate=22 December 2011|first=Michael|last=Vaughton}}</ref>\n\n=== Carlisle United ===\n\n*Stadium: [[Brunton Park]]\n* Capacity: 18,202<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.efl.com/clubs-and-competitions/sky-bet-league-two/clubs/carlisle-united/|title=EFL Official Website - Carlisle United|website=www.efl.com|access-date=2019-12-19}}</ref>\n* ''Current stadium status'': Reconstructed.\n\n===Cheltenham Town===\n\n*Stadium: [[Whaddon Road]]\n* Capacity: 7,066<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.efl.com/clubs-and-competitions/sky-bet-league-two/clubs/cheltenham-town/|title=EFL Official Website - Cheltenham Town|website=www.efl.com|access-date=2019-12-19}}</ref>\n*''Current stadium status'': Reconstructed.\n\nIn 2008, plans to build a new 10,000-seater stadium at [[Cheltenham Racecourse]] were mooted.<ref>{{cite news|title=Cheltenham eye racecourse move|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/c/cheltenham_town/7478240.stm|publisher=BBC|date=27 June 2008|accessdate=15 November 2012}}</ref> In September 2011 things were said by [[Edward Gillespie]] to be \"moving forward\".<ref>{{cite news|title=Talks continue over Cheltenham Town racecourse move|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/15076747|publisher=BBC|date=27 September 2011|accessdate=15 November 2012}}</ref> However, by December these plans had been shelved.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/16262693|title=Cheltenham Town decide against racecourse move|publisher=BBC|date=20 December 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2012 the club announced that they plan to redevelop their existing [[Whaddon Road]] stadium by building a new 3,000-capacity stand.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/17288246|title=Cheltenham chairman plans Whaddon Road redevelopment|publisher=BBC|date=7 March 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Colchester United===\n\n*Stadium: [[Colchester Community Stadium]]\n* Capacity: 10,105<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.efl.com/clubs-and-competitions/sky-bet-league-two/clubs/colchester-united/|title=EFL Official Website - Colchester United|website=www.efl.com|access-date=2019-12-19}}</ref>\n*''Current stadium status'': New.\n\n[[Colchester United F.C.|Colchester United]] took possession of a new stadium, funded by the local council, in July 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eadt.co.uk/news/u-s-given-keys-to-new-stadium-1-189972|title=U's given keys to new stadium|first=Annie|last=Davidson|website=East Anglian Daily Times}}</ref> The [[Colchester Community Stadium]] cost \u00a316 million to build and has a capacity of 10,000 seats. There is potential for future expansion to 18,000.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/c/colchester_united/6922395.stm |title=BBC SPORT &#124; Football &#124; My Club &#124; Colchester United &#124; Colchester given \u00a32m ground boost |work=BBC News |date=30 July 2007 |accessdate=14 April 2010}}</ref>\n\n===Crawley Town===\n\n*Stadium: [[Broadfield Stadium|The People's Pension Stadium]]\n* Capacity: 6,134<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.efl.com/clubs-and-competitions/sky-bet-league-two/clubs/crawley-town/|title=EFL Official Website - Crawley Town|website=www.efl.com|access-date=2019-12-19}}</ref>\n*''Current stadium status'': Reconstructed.\n\n[[Crawley Town F.C.|Crawley Town]] expanded [[Broadfield Stadium]] in 2012 by rebuilding the East Stand, increasing capacity at the stadium by 2,151 and constructing new turnstile blocks, toilets and concession areas as well as improved floodlighting.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.crawleytownfc.com/page/LatestNews/0,,11025~2713332,00.html |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120404105001/http://www.crawleytownfc.com/page/LatestNews/0%2C%2C11025~2713332%2C00.html |archivedate=4 April 2012 |title=Let's fill the East Stand |publisher=Crawley Town FC |date=4 April 2012 |accessdate=13 October 2013 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\nand Crawley Town Football Club also have new plans to construct a bigger and better stadium with a larger capacity in the nearby area known as Bewbush within the town.\n\n=== Crewe Alexandra ===\n\n*Stadium: [[Gresty Road|The Alexandra Stadium]]\n* Capacity: 10,153<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.efl.com/clubs-and-competitions/sky-bet-league-two/clubs/crewe-alexandra/|title=EFL Official Website - Crewe Alexandra|website=www.efl.com|access-date=2019-12-19}}</ref>\n*''Current stadium status'': Reconstructed.\n\n[[Crewe Alexandra F.C.|Crewe Alexandra]] are hoping to expand their stadium, [[Alexandra Stadium]] to 16,700. However, Crewe are looking for benefactors to donate funding for the project. With this money, the 3 smaller stands will all have 2 tiers, each holding another 2,000\u20132,500 spectators each. Also, a new interactive score board will be placed at the stadium above the Wulvern Housing stand.\n\n=== Exeter City ===\n\n*Stadium: [[St James Park (Exeter)|St James Park]] (Exeter)\n* Capacity: 8,541<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.efl.com/clubs-and-competitions/sky-bet-league-two/clubs/exeter-city/|title=EFL Official Website - Exeter City|website=www.efl.com|access-date=2019-12-19}}</ref>\n* ''Current stadium status'': Reconstructed.\n\n=== Forest Green Rovers ===\n\n*Stadium: [[The New Lawn]]\n* Capacity: 5,147<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.efl.com/clubs-and-competitions/sky-bet-league-two/clubs/forest-green-rovers/|title=EFL Official Website - Forest Green Rovers|website=www.efl.com|access-date=2019-12-19}}</ref>\n*''Current stadium status'': New.\n\n===Grimsby Town===\n\n*Stadium: [[Blundell Park]]\n* Capacity: 9,027<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.efl.com/clubs-and-competitions/sky-bet-league-two/clubs/grimsby-town/|title=EFL Official Website - Grimsby Town|website=www.efl.com|access-date=2019-12-19}}</ref>\n*''Current stadium status'': Reconstructed.\n\nSince the mid-1990s the club has been pursuing a move to a new stadium elsewhere in the area. In the late 1990s the club submitted a planning application for a new stadium on the western outskirts of Grimsby at [[Great Coates]], adjacent to the [[A180 road (England)|A180 dual carriageway]]. The provisionally titled Conoco Stadium was to be funded by a partnership with a major retailer and would be built with a capacity of 14,000 that could be expanded up to 21,000 (to meet Premier League requirements) in a matter of weeks by building the entire structure of the stadium but not installing any facilities or seats in the four corners of the stadium until they were required.\n\nThe new stadium would have included facilities to match the best Premier League clubs including a substantial increase in match-day hospitality areas, more [[Luxury box|corporate boxes]] of a far higher standard, more cafe and bar areas including for away supporters, significantly more toilets, larger and more versatile player dressing rooms, wider seats with more legroom, a hard-wearing hybrid pitch capable of withstanding multiple rugby and football matches being played on it every week and facilities that could be used throughout the year for corporate events.\n\nThe aim was to open the new stadium for the start of the 2001/2002 season. After considerable opposition to the plans from local residents delayed the project, the new stadium received planning permission from [[North East Lincolnshire Council]] in November 2000. The [[Government Office|Government Office for Yorkshire and the Humber]] approved the plan in February 2002, [[Conoco]] agreed naming rights to the stadium in April 2002 and the revised opening date was set for the start of the 2003/2004 season. At the end of 2002 retailers [[Woolworths Group|Woolworths]] and [[B&Q]] pulled out of the scheme and opening was set back again to the 2005/2006 season. After planning permission was refused in 2003 due to issues with the release of the land the club resubmitted a planning application in 2006<ref>{{cite news |title=Mariners submit new stadium plans |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/g/grimsby_town/4644178.stm |publisher=BBC Sport |date=24 January 2006 |accessdate=26 February 2007}}</ref> along the same lines as the earlier proposal that was awarded permission by the council in 2007. Due to the [[Great Recession|economic crisis of 2008]] and struggling performances on the pitch<ref>https://www.grimsbytelegraph.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/grimsby-2010-linwood-relegation-drinking-2881519</ref> the stadium's planning permission expired in 2010 and the Great Coates proposal was no longer considered viable.\n\nAfter committing to seeking a new site for a new stadium in 2011 the club actively pursued a range of potential stadium sites in an around Grimsby.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-humber-18867377 | publisher=BBC Sport | title=Grimsby land assessed for football stadium and leisure complex | date=17 July 2012 | accessdate=19 February 2015}}</ref> After a long feasibility study the momentum was clearly behind a site off [[Peaks Parkway]] two miles South of Grimsby. The club submitted a planning application for a less ambitious 14,000 capacity stadium along with an adjoining retail development in November 2016.<ref>{{cite news |title=Grimsby Town's 5-year goal is new stadium & Mariners keen to secure lease on Peaks Parkway site |url=http://www.grimsbytelegraph.co.uk/TOWN-s-5-year-goal-net-new-stadium/story-24533016-detail/story.html |newspaper=Grimsby Telegraph |date=14 November 2014 |accessdate=19 February 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150219001040/http://www.grimsbytelegraph.co.uk/TOWN-s-5-year-goal-net-new-stadium/story-24533016-detail/story.html |archivedate=19 February 2015 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Opponents to the Peaks Parkway scheme argued that the use of a greenfield site over various brownfield alternatives and the proximity of the stadium to a cemetery made it unsuitable and the council took the site off the table in October 2018.<ref name=\"grimsbytelegraph.co.uk\">https://www.grimsbytelegraph.co.uk/news/peaks-parkway-stadium-plans-off-2168102</ref>\n\nIn October 2018 the council indicated a preference for Freeman Street and the East Marsh to be used as a new location for a new stadium as part of a major regeneration project of this part of the town.<ref name=\"grimsbytelegraph.co.uk\"/> Advantages of this site include extensive regeneration of the area and the use of a brownfield site but disadvantages include parking and transport as the new stadium would be within the town itself.\n\nTalk of using [[Port of Grimsby#Fish Docks (1857\u2013)|Grimsby Fish Dock]] as a site for a new stadium has increased since July 2019.<ref name=\"grimsbytelegraph.co.uk\"/> Advantages of this site are the use of the underused but iconic docks which could be directly incorporated into the design and ample scope for parking and transport links. Disadvantages include the potential cost of filling in the docks and land decontamination. The [[2019 United Kingdom general election|2019 General Election]] produced a Conservative victory in the [[Great Grimsby (UK Parliament constituency)|Great Grimsby Constituency]] and this may have a significant effect on the stadium plans. As Conservative policy is to support the creation of [[Free economic zone|Free Ports]] after leaving the [[European Union]]<ref>https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/49198825</ref> there is an opportunity for the town to attract more inward investment and for the ports to grow. This would make the fish docks site less desirable as it could limit the regeneration of the fishing industry and the regeneration opportunities of the Freeman Street site more attractive to government as it considers funding.\n\nAt the end of December 2019 the leader of the council stated that regeneration of the Freeman Street area with a new stadium on it was \"top of his wish list for 2020\".<ref>https://www.grimsbytelegraph.co.uk/news/grimsby-news/freeman-street-top-leaders-wish-3675684</ref>\n\n=== Leyton Orient ===\n\n*Stadium: [[Brisbane Road|The Breyer Group Stadium]]\n* Capacity: 9,271<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.efl.com/clubs-and-competitions/sky-bet-league-two/clubs/leyton-orient/|title=EFL Official Website - Leyton Orient|website=www.efl.com|access-date=2019-12-19}}</ref>\n* ''Current stadium status'': Reconstructed.\n\n=== Macclesfield Town ===\n\n*Stadium: [[Moss Rose]]\n* Capacity: 6,355<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.efl.com/clubs-and-competitions/sky-bet-league-two/clubs/macclesfield-town/|title=EFL Official Website - Macclesfield Town|website=www.efl.com|access-date=2019-12-19}}</ref>\n* ''Current stadium status'': Reconstructed.\n\n=== Mansfield Town ===\n\n*Stadium: [[Field Mill|One Call Stadium]]\n* Capacity: 9,186<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.efl.com/clubs-and-competitions/sky-bet-league-two/clubs/mansfield-town/|title=EFL Official Website - Mansfield Town|website=www.efl.com|access-date=2019-12-19}}</ref>\n* ''Current stadium status'': Reconstructed.\n\n===Morecambe===\n\n*Stadium: [[Globe Arena (football stadium)|Globe Arena]]\n* Capacity: 6,476<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.efl.com/clubs-and-competitions/sky-bet-league-two/clubs/morecambe/|title=EFL Official Website - Morecambe|website=www.efl.com|access-date=2019-12-19}}</ref>\n*''Current stadium status'': New.\n\n[[Morecambe F.C.|Morecambe]] moved from its previous ground at [[Christie Park (Morecambe, England)|Christie Park]] to [[Globe Arena (football stadium)|The Globe Arena]] at the start of the [[2010-11 Football League|2010\u201311 season]].<ref name=\"mns\">{{cite web |url=http://www.morecambestadium.co.uk/ |title=WELCOME TO THE FUTURE \u2013 Globe Arena &#124; Morecambe new ground &#124; Globe Construction &#124; new ground stadium Morecambe &#124; Morecambe regeneration &#124; Westgate developm |publisher=Morecambe Stadium |accessdate=14 April 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100212043206/http://www.morecambestadium.co.uk/ |archive-date=12 February 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The ground has a capacity of 6000, comprising 2000 seats and 4000 standing spaces.<ref name=\"mns\" />\n\n=== Newport County ===\n\n*Stadium: [[Rodney Parade]]\n* Capacity: 8,700<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.efl.com/clubs-and-competitions/sky-bet-league-two/clubs/newport-county/|title=EFL Official Website - Newport County|website=www.efl.com|access-date=2019-12-19}}</ref>\n* ''Current stadium status'': Reconstructed.\n\n=== Northampton Town ===\n\n*Stadium: [[Sixfields Stadium|Sixfields]]\n* Capacity: 7,798<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.efl.com/clubs-and-competitions/sky-bet-league-two/clubs/northampton-town/|title=EFL Official Website - Northampton Town|website=www.efl.com|access-date=2019-12-19}}</ref>\n*''Current stadium status'': New.\n\n===Oldham Athletic===\n\n*Stadium: [[Boundary Park]]\n* Capacity: 13,513<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.efl.com/clubs-and-competitions/sky-bet-league-two/clubs/oldham-athletic/|title=EFL Official Website - Oldham Athletic|website=www.efl.com|access-date=2019-12-19}}</ref>\n*''Current stadium status'': Reconstructed.\n\n[[Boundary Park]] has been all-seater stadium since the mid-1990s, though the improvements were very much a task of refurbishment rather than reconstruction.  The only reconstruction happened at the Rochdale Road End of the ground where the old traditional open terrace was replaced by a 4,600 capacity all seated stand.  The Chadderton Road End on the opposite side of the ground simply had seats bolted onto the terrace, whilst the Main Stand and Broadway Stand had seats added to the lower tiers of the stand.\n\nThere were plans in the late 1990s for a move to a new 20,000 all seater stadium on adjoining waste ground, but these were scrapped.\n\nBecause of these problems, the club announced in the summer of 2009 that it was considering moving to a new stadium in Failsworth.  However, the Charities Commission later turned down the application.\n\nOn 28 July 2011 Oldham Metropolitan Borough Council offered the club \u00a35.7 million to help with their redevelopment fund of Boundary Park, which would involve the redevelopment of the Broadway Stand.\n\nPlanning approval for the new North Stand was confirmed in April 2013, including a 2,671 capacity stand, a health and fitness suite, supporters' bar and event facilities.  Demolition and preparatory work started in the summer of 2013.\nConstruction of the new North Stand is still ongoing, although the seating area in the stand was open for use on 17 October 2015 for the home match against Sheffield United.  The new North Stand is significantly taller than the stand that it replaced although the capacity for supporters is roughly the same, bringing the ground capacity up to 13,512.  The additional height allows for office space, corporate hospitality, retail opportunities and a gymnasium.\n\n===Plymouth Argyle===\n\n*Stadium: [[Home Park]]\n* Capacity: 16,388<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.efl.com/clubs-and-competitions/sky-bet-league-two/clubs/plymouth-argyle/|title=EFL Official Website - Plymouth Argyle|website=www.efl.com|access-date=2019-12-19}}</ref>\n*''Current stadium status'': Reconstructed; further improvements on hold.\n[[Home Park]] has seen large-scale changes to the ground in recent years. The first stage of reconstruction at the ground took place in 2001, with the replacement of 3 stands with an all-seater horseshoe-shaped stand. Following the construction, the club then planned to rebuild the main grandstand. This initially did not materialize, and following the financial crisis at the club in 2010 and 2011, future stadium plans were put on hold.\n\nAfter [[Plymouth Argyle]] went into administration, the club was taken over by local business owner James Brent, and fresh plans for a new Mayflower Grandstand were submitted to [[Plymouth City Council]]. The plans included the stand itself, as well as a new 1500-seat-capacity ice rink, 10-screen cinema and a hotel that would provide funds for the club. The plans received planning permission on 15 August 2013, with Brent suggesting that development could begin immediately. The old grandstand was planned to be demolished in late October 2013, but was put on hold after rival plans for similar leisure facilities at Bretonside were approved.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.plymouthherald.co.uk/new-plan-home-park-grandstand-cinema-deal/story-26859816-detail/story.html|title=New plan for Home Park grandstand as cinema deal 'scuppered'|date=8 July 2015|accessdate=22 December 2016|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150909184918/http://www.plymouthherald.co.uk/New-plan-Home-Park-grandstand-cinema-deal/story-26859816-detail/story.html|archive-date=9 September 2015|publisher=Plymouth Herald}}</ref> In September 2016, Brent told the [[Plymouth Herald]] that he hoped a 'redeveloped grandstand' would be completed in time for the 400th anniversary of the [[Mayflower]] sailing in 2020 when the city of Plymouth will host significant celebrations.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.plymouthherald.co.uk/plymouth-argyle-supremo-james-brent-wants-new-home-park-grandstand-by-2020/story-29733938-detail/story.html|title=New grandstand at Home Park 'well before 2020' says James Brent|date=20 September 2016|accessdate=22 December 2016|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160921190352/http://www.plymouthherald.co.uk/plymouth-argyle-supremo-james-brent-wants-new-home-park-grandstand-by-2020/story-29733938-detail/story.html|archive-date=21 September 2016|publisher=Plymouth Herald}}</ref>\n\n===Port Vale===\n\n*Stadium: [[Vale Park]]\n* Capacity: 19,052<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.efl.com/clubs-and-competitions/sky-bet-league-two/clubs/port-vale/|title=EFL Official Website - Port Vale|website=www.efl.com|access-date=2019-12-19}}</ref>\n*''Current stadium status'': Reconstructed.\n[[Port Vale F.C.|Port Vale]]'s [[Vale Park]] saw the Lorne Street stand demolished in 1998, and work began on a \u00a33 million all-seater replacement. However, with the overall capacity of 19,052 already more than adequate, the stand remained uncompleted. Two periods in administration in 2002 and again in 2012, made it extremely difficult to fund completion but new owner and Chairman, Norman Smurthwaite, has indicated that seating will be installed in the last remaining area when attendances justify it.\n\n=== Salford City ===\n\n*Stadium: [[Moor Lane|The Peninsula Stadium]]\n* Capacity: 5,106<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.efl.com/clubs-and-competitions/sky-bet-league-two/clubs/salford-city/|title=EFL Official Website - Salford City|website=www.efl.com|access-date=2019-12-19}}</ref>\n* ''Current stadium status'': Reconstructed.\n\n===Scunthorpe United===\n\n*Stadium: [[Glanford Park]]\n* Capacity: 9,088<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.efl.com/clubs-and-competitions/sky-bet-league-two/clubs/scunthorpe-united/|title=EFL Official Website - Scunthorpe United|website=www.efl.com|access-date=2019-12-19}}</ref>\n*''Current stadium status'': New; looking for move.\n\n[[Scunthorpe United]]'s [[Glanford Park]] was built in 1988. A 6000 housing estate idea was created on the outskirts of Scunthorpe and a 12000 all seater stadium was envisaged for Scunthorpe United to play their home games at. The chairman felt that their Glanford Park was limiting the club and he wanted to have a stadium that could house concerts, conferences and be a 24/7 7 days a week used venue. Planning permission was given by the North Lincolnshire council in mid-2016.\n\n=== Stevenage ===\n\n*Stadium: [[Broadhall Way|Lamex Stadium]]\n* Capacity: 6,722<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.efl.com/clubs-and-competitions/sky-bet-league-two/clubs/stevenage/|title=EFL Official Website - Stevenage|website=www.efl.com|access-date=2019-12-19}}</ref>\n* ''Current stadium status'': Reconstructed.\n\n=== Swindon Town ===\n\n*Stadium: [[County Ground (Swindon)|County Ground]]\n* Capacity: 15,728<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.efl.com/clubs-and-competitions/sky-bet-league-two/clubs/swindon-town/|title=EFL Official Website - Swindon Town|website=www.efl.com|access-date=2019-12-19}}</ref>\n* ''Current stadium status'': Reconstructed.\n\n===Walsall===\n\n*Stadium: [[Bescot Stadium|The Banks's Stadium]]\n* Capacity: 11,300<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.efl.com/clubs-and-competitions/sky-bet-league-two/clubs/walsall/|title=EFL Official Website - Walsall|website=www.efl.com|access-date=2019-12-19}}</ref>\n*''Current stadium status'': New.\n\n[[Walsall F.C.]] have announced they have gained planning permission to rebuild the William Sharp End, adding an extra 2,300 seats and raising overall capacity at the [[Bescot Stadium]] to 13,500.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.footballgroundguide.com/walsall.htm|title=Internet Football Ground Guide \u2013 Banks's Stadium Walsall FC|publisher=Footballgroundguide.com|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110519180447/http://www.footballgroundguide.com/walsall.htm|archivedate=19 May 2011|accessdate=14 April 2010|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nBescot Stadium was opened in 1990 to replace nearby [[Fellows Park]], and originally had a capacity of just under 10,000, of which approximately two thirds was seated. The construction of a new all-seater stand on the site of the terraced section took place in 2002.\n\n==National League==\n===A.F.C. Fylde===\n\n* Stadium: [[Mill Farm]]\n* Capacity: 6,000<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.afcfylde.co.uk/mill-farm/|title=Mill Farm|website=AFC Fylde|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-01-09}}</ref>\n*''Current stadium status'': New.\n[[A.F.C. Fylde]] moved to Kellamergh Park, in 2006 in order to meet the ground criteria for promotion to the [[North West Counties Football League]]. On 19 January 2008 the club announced plans for a further move to yet another new stadium at an unnamed {{convert|26|acre|m2|adj=on}} site.<ref name=\"NLP471\">{{cite news|last=Jones|first=Howard|title=Kirkham On The Move|work=The Non-League Paper|date=20 January 2008|url=http://www.thenonleaguefootballpaper.com/article.asp?aid=2220&jid=58&sud=471|accessdate=21 January 2008|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110717020304/http://www.thenonleaguefootballpaper.com/article.asp?aid=2220&jid=58&sud=471|archivedate=17 July 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nOn 2016, A.F.C. Fylde moved to their newest ground, Mill Farm with 6,000 capacity.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://stadiumdb.com/stadiums/eng/mill_farm|title=Mill Farm \u2013 StadiumDB.com|website=stadiumdb.com|access-date=2020-01-09}}</ref>\n\n=== Aldershot Town ===\n\n* Stadium: [[Recreation Ground (Aldershot)|The EBB Stadium]]\n* Capacity: 7,100<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.chelseafc.com/en/about-chelsea/about-the-academy|title=About The Academy {{!}} Official Site {{!}} Chelsea Football Club|website=ChelseaFC|access-date=2020-01-09}}</ref>\n* ''Current stadium status'': Reconstructed.\n\n===Barnet===\n\n* Stadium: [[The Hive Stadium|The Hive]]\n* Capacity: 6,500<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.barnetfc.com/club/the-stadium/|title=The Hive London - Barnet Football Club|website=www.barnetfc.com|access-date=2020-01-09}}</ref>\n*''Current stadium status'': New.\n[[Barnet F.C.|Barnet]] were forced to move in a hurry to their training complex '[[The Hive Stadium|The Hive]]' in 2013. The complex had the shell of a small stadium with two abandoned end terraces behind the main building. Between February and August 2013 the pitch was renovated, terraces restored, 750 seats built into the back of the existing building and a new 2700 capacity stand built along the opposite touchline. Construction re-commenced in November 2015 with the main building (now renamed East Stand) being extended to provide a medical centre, ticket office and enlarge the banqueting facilities. A gradual process is underway to convert the stadium to all seated and enhance facilities at the site with the North terrace replaced by a 1868 capacity stand in the style of the new west stand due for completion in September 2016. The Chairman has confirmed that replacement of the South Terrace, extension of the West Stand and an improvement of the current partial roof of the East stand and a New sports hall will be scheduled once the existing work is complete.\n\n===Barrow===\n\n* Stadium: [[Holker Street|Progression Solicitors Stadium]]\n* Capacity: 5,045<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.footballgroundguide.com/leagues/conference/conference-premier/barrow-holker-street.html|title=Barrow AFC {{!}} Furness Building Society Stadium {{!}} Football Ground Guide|website=www.footballgroundguide.com|access-date=2020-01-15}}</ref>\n*''Current stadium status'': Reconstructed.\n[[Barrow A.F.C.]] are investigating building a new stadium in the Docklands section of the town, which would be shared with the [[Barrow Raiders]] rugby league side.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newsandstar.co.uk/a-vision-for-the-future-of-barrow-1.158414?referrerPath=home%2F2.1962|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20131013211128/http://www.newsandstar.co.uk/a-vision-for-the-future-of-barrow-1.158414?referrerPath=home%2F2.1962|url-status=dead|title=News & Star - A vision for the future of Barrow|date=13 October 2013|archivedate=13 October 2013|website=archive.is}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rugbyleague.org/index.php?act=Print&client=printer&f=4&t=43498 |title=Rugby League Fans Forums [Powered by Invision Power Board&#93; |publisher=Rugbyleague.org |accessdate=13 October 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090214025904/http://www.rugbyleague.org/index.php?act=Print&client=printer&f=4&t=43498 |archivedate=14 February 2009 }}</ref>\n\n=== Boreham Wood ===\n\n* Stadium: [[Meadow Park (Borehamwood)|Meadow Park]]\n* Capacity: 5,000<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.footballgroundguide.com/leagues/conference/conference-premier/boreham-wood-fc-meadow-park.html|title=Boreham Wood FC {{!}} Meadow Park {{!}} Football Ground Guide|website=www.footballgroundguide.com|access-date=2020-01-15}}</ref>\n*''Current stadium status'': Reconstructed.\n\n===Bromley===\n\n*''Current stadium status'': Reconstructed.\n\nIn April 2017, [[Bromley F.C.|Bromley]] announced plans to redevelop the South end of their [[Hayes Lane]] stadium.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bromleyfc.tv/site/bromley-fc-announces-significant-investment-into-hayes-lane/|title=Bromley FC announces significant investment into Hayes Lane|first=Bromley|last=FC|date=30 April 2017|publisher=}}</ref> The plans include an all-seater stand with capacity of up to 1,450 incorporating indoor sports facilities for community use. While planning permission has been achieved, work is yet to commence as of May 2018.\n\n===Chesterfield===\n\n*''Current stadium status'': New.\n\n[[Chesterfield F.C.|Chesterfield]] were looking to move out of their dated Saltergate ground for several years in other locations around the town before planning permission was granted at the former Dema glassworks in July 2008.<ref name=\"Stadium and store application granted\">{{cite news| url=http://www.yorkshirepost.co.uk/localnews/Stadium-and-store-application-granted.4261764.jp|title=Stadium and store application granted|date=16 July 2008|newspaper=Yorkshire Post|accessdate=16 July 2008}}</ref>\nThe new ground opened in 2010 and was called, for sponsorship reasons, the b2net Stadium. In 2012 after the purchase of b2net by Swedish company Proact the stadium name changed to its current name, the [[Proact Stadium]].<ref name=\"name change\">{{cite news|url=http://www.derbyshiretimes.co.uk/sport/chesterfield-fc/blues-ground-renamed-proact-stadium-1-4829055|title=Blues ground renamed Proact Stadium |date=13 August 2010|publisher=Derbyshire Times|accessdate=20 August 2012}}</ref> \nThe ground has a capacity of 10,504 all seated and was built at a cost of \u00a313,000,000. The stadium was designed to be easily expanded in the future.\n\n=== FC Halifax Town ===\n\n*''Current stadium status'': Reconstructed.\n\n[[FC Halifax Town|Halifax]] had at one point been planning further ground improvements to [[The Shay]], increasing the Main Stand to take capacity to over 10,000. Financial difficulties meant that development had to put on hold for the foreseeable future, leaving the Main Stand half-finished.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.conferencegrounds.co.uk/halifax_town.htm#Future%20Developments |title=Conference Football Ground Guide |publisher=Conferencegrounds.co.uk |date= |accessdate=14 April 2010}}</ref>\n\nWith the club resurrected as ''FC Halifax Town'' in the Northern Premier League First Division (North), the Main Stand was completed in March 2010.\n\n=== Maidstone United ===\n\n*''Current stadium status'': New.\n\nThe [[Maidstone United F.C.|club]] that re-formed following the dissolution of the [[Maidstone United F.C. (1897)|original Maidstone United]] played at Sittingbourne, while constructing a new stadium at [[James Whatman Way]]. The new stadium (named the [[Gallagher Stadium]]) opened in July 2012 and has a capacity of 2,500 with 450 seats. In the summer of 2015, the main stand is being expanded and, along with additional upgrades, will increase the capacity to 3,000. The club is also at the forefront of introducing 3G pitches to lower league football. The stadium is used 7 days a week with the pitch standing up well to heavy use by all levels of community football. They are yet to have a game postponed for weather / pitch reasons.\n\n===Solihull Moors===\n\n*''Current stadium status'': Reconstructed.\n\n[[Solihull Moors]] have secured a ground share agreement at their Damson Park home with [[Birmingham & Solihull R.F.C.]], home to professional rugby union side, the Bees. The clubs have submitted (Nov08) planning applications for facility and ground improvements which will see the Borough of Solihull offered a centre of excellence and a Community Foundation which will benefit its own populace and beyond. Solihull Moors were founded in 2007 by a merger of local sides [[Moor Green F.C.|Moor Green]] and [[Solihull Borough F.C.|Solihull Borough]].\n\n===Sutton United===\n\n*''Current stadium status'': Reconstructed.\n\n[[Sutton United F.C.|Sutton United]]'s ground, [[Gander Green Lane]], has a rather distant terrace at the east end,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.suttonunited.net/info_stadium.html|title=Club Info: The Borough Sports Ground|publisher=Sutton United F.C.|accessdate=5 November 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101130074847/http://suttonunited.net/info_stadium.html|archivedate=30 November 2010|df=dmy-all}}</ref> and the club hope to bring the terrace much closer to the goal, along with several other improvements to the clubhouse.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.suttonunited.net/community_fdp_facilityplan.html|title=Football Development Plan \u2013 Ground Facilities|publisher=Sutton United F.C.|accessdate=5 November 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101130111224/http://suttonunited.net/community_fdp_facilityplan.html|archive-date=30 November 2010|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==National League North==\n===A.F.C. Telford===\n\n*''Current stadium status'': New.\n\n[[A.F.C. Telford United]] play at the [[New Bucks Head]] It was originally built for [[Telford United F.C.|Telford United]] to play at before they went bankrupt. The stadium is on the same site as the original Bucks Head, which had been home to Telford United and [[Wellington Town]] for over a century. The stadium was completed in 2003, and has a capacity of 6,300. It is covered on three out of four sides. The stadium lease and assets are currently held by [[Telford and Wrekin]] Council, completed in 2003 and was the 111th largest football stadium in [[England]].\n\n===Bradford Park Avenue===\n\n*''Current stadium status'': Reconstructed.\n\n[[Bradford Park Avenue A.F.C.|Bradford Park Avenue]] had been planning to leave their current [[Horsfall Stadium]] for the redeveloped [[Odsal Stadium|Grattan Stadium]], which would be shared with [[Bradford Bulls]]. With this redevelopment being continually delayed, through, Avenue are now planning to build a new 20,000-capacity stadium in South [[Leeds]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/news/2060478.avenue_unveil_new_stadium_plan/|title=Avenue unveil new stadium plan|date=21 February 2008|accessdate=13 October 2013|first=Jo|last=Winrow|work=Telegraph & Argus|location=Bradford|publisher=Newsquest}}</ref>\n\n===Darlington 1883===\n\n*''Current stadium status'': Plans Submitted.\n\nAfter the demise of [[Darlington F.C.|Darlington]] in 2012, fan owned [[Darlington 1883]] was formed, they left the Darlington Arena to groundshare with [[Bishop Auckland F.C.|Bishop Auckland]] at Heritage Park. Darlington entered into an agreement with Darlington Rugby Club to redevelop Blackwell Meadows and plans were submitted to the local council at the end of 2014.<ref>{{cite news|title=Plans to redevelop Blackwell Meadows for Darlington FC and Darlington RFC groundshare submitted to council planners |url=http://www.thenorthernecho.co.uk/news/local/darlington/11673723.Plans_to_redevelop_Blackwell_Meadows_for_Darlington_FC_and_Darlington_RFC_groundshare_submitted_to_council_planners/ |newspaper=Northern Echo |date=15 December 2014 |accessdate=5 January 2015}}</ref> The club hope to move into Blackwell Meadows sometime in the 2015\u201316 Season\n\n===FC United of Manchester===\n\n*''Current stadium status'': New.\n\nSince the club's formation in 2005, [[F.C. United of Manchester|F.C. United]] have not had their own home ground. Instead, they share a ground with [[Bury F.C.]], using their [[Gigg Lane]] ground.\n\nIn March 2010, the club announced plans to build their own 5,000-capacity football ground in [[Newton Heath]], the original home of Manchester United. Manchester City Council initially approved, but within a year had backed out from funding the stadium. The council pledged to help FC United build a stadium in a new location with reduced costs,<ref>{{Cite news|title=Manchester City Council pulls funds |url=http://fc-utd.co.uk/story.php?story_id=3458 |work=fc-utd.co.uk |publisher=FC United of Manchester |date=4 March 2011 |accessdate=4 March 2011 }}</ref> and the alternative site was announced in April 2011 in the Broadhurst Park area of [[Moston, Greater Manchester|Moston]], Manchester.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.manchester.gov.uk/egov_downloads/1A_-_FC_United.pdf|title=Report for Resolution \u2013 FC United Options Review|work=manchester.gov.uk|publisher=Manchester City Council|format=PDF|date=6 April 2011|accessdate=24 April 2011}}</ref> After many delays due to legal challenges by a small number of residents, work finally got underway in November 2013. The club hopes to be playing at [[Broadhurst Park]] for the start of the 2015\u201316 season.\n\n===Gainsborough Trinity===\nIn November 2009, Trinity chairman Peter Swann announced that he intends to build a new 4,000-seat stadium for the club.<ref>{{cite news|title=4,000 seater stadium planned for Gainsborough|url=http://www.thisislincolnshire.co.uk/4-000-seat-stadium-plan-Gainsborough/story-11196472-detail/story.html|work=thisislincolnshire.co.uk|date=5 November 2009|accessdate=28 December 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120405073105/http://www.thisislincolnshire.co.uk/4-000-seat-stadium-plan-Gainsborough/story-11196472-detail/story.html|archive-date=5 April 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref> The club was hopeful that the new stadium will be open for the beginning of the 2013\u201314 season,<ref>{{cite news|title=New stadium plans for Gainsborough Trinity reveal multiple-sport and retail complex|url=http://www.thisislincolnshire.co.uk/New-stadium-plans-Gainsborough-Trinity-reveal/story-16678040-detail/story.html|date=9 August 2012|accessdate=28 December 2012|work=Lincolnshire Echo|publisher=Northcliffe Media|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120912011816/http://www.thisislincolnshire.co.uk/New-stadium-plans-Gainsborough-Trinity-reveal/story-16678040-detail/story.html|archive-date=12 September 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref> however, in September 2012, Swann announced that the plans will be cancelled, due to his ill health.<ref>{{cite news|title=End of road for stadium plans|url=http://www.worksopguardian.co.uk/news/local/end-of-road-for-stadium-plans-1-4881052|work=Worksop Guardian|accessdate=28 December 2012|date=13 October 2013}}</ref> The current plan is for Swann to buy the stadium from current owners the Blues Club, and spend \u00a3500,000 improving it.<ref>{{cite news|title=Gainsborough Trinity chairman vows to spend \u00a3500k to redevelop Northolme|url=http://www.thisislincolnshire.co.uk/Gainsborough-Trinity-chairman-vows-spend-pound/story-17321572-detail/story.html|archive-url=https://archive.today/20130505113042/http://www.thisislincolnshire.co.uk/Gainsborough-Trinity-chairman-vows-spend-pound/story-17321572-detail/story.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=5 May 2013|date=15 November 2012|accessdate=28 December 2012|work=thisislincolnshire.co.uk}}</ref> {{As of|2012|12|27}}, talks are ongoing.<ref>{{cite news|title=Owners of Gainsborough Trinity's Northolme ready to thrash out a deal|url=http://www.thisislincolnshire.co.uk/Owners-Gainsborough-Trinity-s-Northolme-ready/story-17684701-detail/story.html|date=27 December 2012|accessdate=28 December 2012|work=thisislincolnshire.co.uk|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121230070634/http://www.thisislincolnshire.co.uk/Owners-Gainsborough-Trinity-s-Northolme-ready/story-17684701-detail/story.html|archive-date=30 December 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n===Hereford FC===\n\n*''Current stadium status'': Reconstructed.\n\nThe terraced Blackfriars Street End at [[Edgar Street]] was closed in 2009 after failing a safety inspection. The club now plan to build a 1,600 seater stand in its place, bringing capacity up to 7,650. \n[[Hereford United]] were wound up by the High Court in December 2014 after failure to provide assurances that club debts would be paid. A new phoenix club, [[Hereford F.C.]] have been set up and will play at Edgar Street.\n\n===Leamington===\n\n*''Current stadium status'': New\n\n[[Leamington F.C.|Leamington's]] current home The New Windmill Ground, was opened on the site of a former farmer's field in 2000. Previous to this the club had been without a home and unable to play since 1988 when they were evicted from their previous location The Windmill Ground. When it was opened The New Windmill Ground had few facilities but two new stands and increased terracing, along with better toilets and medical facilities have since been added.\n\nIn 2017 plans were approved for a new stadium to replace their current ground, to be located in the Gallow's Hill area of town. The current ground would then be used to house [[Romanichal|travellers]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Plans approved for 5,000 seater stadium in Leamington|url=https://www.coventrytelegraph.net/news/local-news/plans-approved-5000-seater-football-12888476|date=13 April 2017|accessdate=23 July 2019|work=coventrytelegraph.net}}</ref> As of April 2019 work was yet to start.<ref>{{cite news|title=Leamington FC\u2019s new ground could also be \u2018commercial hub\u2019|url=https://www.leamingtoncourier.co.uk/news/leamington-fc-s-new-ground-could-also-be-commercial-hub-1-8884332|date=7 April 2019|accessdate=23 July 2019|work=coventrytelegraph.net}}</ref>\n\n===Stockport County===\n\n*''Current stadium status'': Reconstructed.\n\n[[Edgeley Park]] has been under discussion for redevelopment of the away end, called the Railway End, as they planned to add an extra tier and roof to the stand. However, due to land behind the stadium being owned by the council, who are currently not willing to sell the land, these plans have been put on hold. Another plan was to build the Popular side and add another tier with executive boxes, but all these plans have been put on hold.\n\nThe stadium achieved an 11,000-seat capacity in the late 1990s, when the club was playing in Division One. At one stage there were plans for County to relocate to [[Maine Road]] once [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] vacated it in 2003,<ref>{{cite news|title=Elwood remains upbeat as clouds hang over Stockport|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/competitions/championship/2994431/Nationwide-League-Elwood-remains-upbeat-as-clouds-hang-over-Stockport.html|work=The Telegraph|first=Peter|last=Gardener|date=11 December 2000|accessdate=15 November 2012}}</ref> but these plans were scrapped and Maine Road has since been demolished.<ref>{{cite news|title=Maine Road through the ages|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/m/man_city/3011895.stm|work=BBC Sport|date=11 May 2003|accessdate=15 November 2012|first=Chris|last=Bevan}}</ref>\n\n===York City===\n\n*''Current stadium status'': Reconstructed.\n\nAt one point [[York City F.C.|York City]] were investigating improving [[Bootham Crescent]], but have now switched their plans to the construction of a new stadium to be shared with the [[York City Knights]] rugby club.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.yorkpress.co.uk/sport/1307188.york_city_fc_on_verge_of_stadium_deal/|title=York City FC on verge of stadium deal|work=The Press|location=York|publisher=Newsquest|date=4 April 2007 |accessdate=27 November 2012|first=Gavin|last=Aitchison}}</ref>\n\n==National League South==\n===Bath City===\n\n*''Current stadium status'': Reconstructed.\n\n[[Bath City F.C.]] had plans to move from [[Twerton Park]] to join with [[Bath Rugby]] at [[Recreation Ground (Bath)|The Rec]] which has a capacity of 10,600. There are long-term plans at the club to find a new home.\n\n===Braintree Town===\n*''Current stadium status'': Reconstructed.\n[[Braintree Town F.C.]] unveiled plans for a new 6,000-capacity stadium at Panfield Lane in March 2012 with club chairman Lee Harding indicating they anticipate it being ready in time for the start of the 2016\u201317 season.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thisistotalessex.co.uk/Grand-designs-600-Braintree-homes-stadium/story-15362519-detail/story.html|title=Grand designs for 600 Braintree homes and a stadium|date=1 March 2012|work=Braintree Chronicle|accessdate=8 March 2012|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120304062546/http://www.thisistotalessex.co.uk/Grand-designs-600-Braintree-homes-stadium/story-15362519-detail/story.html|archive-date=4 March 2012|publisher=Total Essex}}</ref> In the mean time the club is redeveloping the Quag End of their existing [[Cressing Road]] ground to bring it up to [[Conference National]] standards.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.gazette-news.co.uk/news/9534690.Harding_still_confident_as_weather_hits_Braintree_s_ground_hopes/|title=Harding still confident as weather hits Braintree's ground hopes|last=Spurgeon|first=Simon|date=16 February 2012|work=gazette-news.co.uk|accessdate=13 October 2013|publisher=Gazette News}}</ref>\n\n===Gloucester City===\n*''Current stadium status'': Reconstructed.\n[[Gloucester City A.F.C.|Gloucester City]] are currently groundsharing with [[Cheltenham Town]] at the Abbey Business stadium (Whaddon Road) in [[Cheltenham]] following the flooding of their [[Gloucester City A.F.C.#Stadium|Meadow Park]] stadium in 2007. Gloucester spent one season groundsharing with [[Forest Green Rovers F.C.|Forest Green Rovers]] at [[The New Lawn]] in [[Nailsworth]] and in Cirencester. The club now look set for a return to their old ground at Meadow Park in [[Gloucester]]. Currently scaled down plans are going through the council.\n{{Citation needed|date=October 2008}}\n\n===Truro City===\n*''Current stadium status'': Reconstructed.\nAs part of their strategy to become the first [[Cornwall|Cornish]] side to gain League status, [[Truro City F.C.]] have plans to build a new [[Stadium for Cornwall]] at a new site to the north of the city at Pencoose Farm, [[Kenwyn]]<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.trurocityfc.co.uk/Page3.aspx?PageID=303|title=HEANEY UNVEILS \u00a36m NEXT STEP IN CITY SOCCER REVOLUTION|publisher=Truro City F.C.|work=trurocityfc.co.uk|date=18 May 2007|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100108073748/http://www.trurocityfc.co.uk/Page3.aspx?PageID=303|archivedate=8 January 2010|url-status=dead}}</ref> which will include a 16,000-all-seater stadium, sports bar, training facilities and a youth academy.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thefa.com/News/competitions/fa-vase/2007/may/FAVase_Heaney|title=Heaney's Truro ambition|publisher=The Football Association|work=thefa.com|first=Tony|last=Incenzo|date=13 May 2007|accessdate=13 October 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Other Non-League==\nIn February 2010 a Charitable Trust called the Haythornthwaite Sports Foundation unveiled plans for a new Community Sports Complex at Greenlands Farm which will comprise Indoor and outdoor Sports Facilities catering for local junior football, cricket and other sports plus a new home for AFC Fylde with an initial capacity of 1400. Public Consultations took place in February 2010 with further announcements expected in summer 2010.\n\n===Aylesbury United===\n*''Current stadium status'': Reconstructed.\n[[Aylesbury United F.C.|Aylesbury United]] have been ground sharing with [[Chesham United F.C.|Chesham United]] and currently with Leighton Town since their eviction from Buckingham Road in 2006. There are plans to move into a new 10,000-seat stadium if plans to build a sports village are approved.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.bucksherald.co.uk/sport/ducks-to-get-new-ground-in-sports-village-1-607394|title=Ducks to get new ground in Sports Village?|work=Bucks Herald|publisher=Johnston Press|date=30 April 2008}}</ref>\n\n===Cambridge City===\n*''Current stadium status'': Reconstructed.\nThe club face a potential eviction from their [[City Ground, Cambridge|City Ground]] home in 2010. Their long-term future regarding a new stadium is unclear, and it is possible they may be forced to share with their cross-city rivals, [[Cambridge United F.C.|Cambridge United]] at the [[Abbey Stadium]] or relocate to another settlement on a temporary basis.\n\n===Grays Athletic===\n*''Current stadium status'': Reconstructed.\n[[Grays Athletic F.C.|Grays Athletic]] had plans to redevelop the [[New Recreation Ground]] to facilitate entry into the football league.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.conferencegrounds.co.uk/grays_athletic.htm |title=Blue Square Premier Football Ground Guide \u2013 Recreation Ground, Grays Athletic FC |publisher=Conferencegrounds.co.uk |accessdate=14 April 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100406081437/http://www.conferencegrounds.co.uk/grays_athletic.htm |archivedate=6 April 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> The club are now seeking to pursue the construction of a new stadium. It is proposed they will ground share with another club while the new arena is built.<ref>{{cite news|title=Club Statement|url=http://www.graysathletic.co.uk/news/archives/002305.html|first=Kevin|last=Lamb|work=graysathletic.co.uk|publisher=Grays Athletic F.C.|date=9 November 2007|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080725051114/http://www.graysathletic.co.uk/news/archives/002305.html|archivedate=25 July 2008|url-status=dead}}</ref> However, it was announced on 12 April 2008 that Grays Athletic plan to move to a [[New Grays Athletic Stadium|new stadium]] in [[Aveley]], [[Thurrock]].\n\n===Histon===\n*''Current stadium status'': Reconstructed.\n[[Histon F.C.|Histon]] are rebuilding the Bridge Road End, bringing the [[seating capacity]] of the stadium up to 1700 and the overall capacity of their [[Glassworld Stadium]] to over 4000.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.conferencegrounds.co.uk/histon.htm#Future |title=Blue Square Premier Football Ground Guide \u2013 Glassworld Stadium, Bridge Road, Histon FC |publisher=Conferencegrounds.co.uk |date=30 November 2008 |accessdate=13 October 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110724094851/http://www.conferencegrounds.co.uk/histon.htm#Future |archivedate=24 July 2011 }}</ref>\n\n===Kettering Town===\n*''Current stadium status'': Up for sale\n[[Kettering Town F.C.|Kettering]] have aspirations to move to a new stadium somewhere in the borough, with problems lying in securing funding and securing the lease on current ground, [[Rockingham Road]]. Chairman Imraan Ladak insisted plans were on track, with a site identified and potential funding sourced; however, in 2011 Kettering Town moved to [[Nene Park]], former home of rivals [[Rushden & Diamonds F.C.|Rushden & Diamonds]].\n\n===Matlock Town===\n*''Current stadium status'': Reconstructed.\nMatlock are in process of rebuilding the North Stand, to bring the stadium capacity up to 2,757, from the previous 2,214 capacity .\n\n===St Albans City===\n*''Current stadium status'': Reconstructed.\nIn 2006 the chairman of the club threatened to move them out of [[St Albans]] if the council would not back plans to build a new 10,000-stadium on Green Belt land on the outskirts of [[St Albans]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.ukinvestmentadvice.co.uk/st-albans-city-fc-green-belt.htm|title=St Albans City FC opt for Green Belt Stadium|publisher=UK Investment Advice|work=ukinvestmentadvice.co.uk|date=1 June 2006|accessdate=14 April 2010|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060813133856/http://www.ukinvestmentadvice.co.uk/st-albans-city-fc-green-belt.htm|archivedate=13 August 2006|url-status=live}}</ref> Little has been of the proposition since, and the current [[Clarence Park, St Albans|Clarence Park]] has been given a superficial makeover. In 2013, the club submitted a planning application for a new stadium.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sacfc.co.uk/index.php/the-club/city-of-st-albans-stadium.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=3 May 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150526025345/http://www.sacfc.co.uk/index.php/the-club/city-of-st-albans-stadium.html |archivedate=26 May 2015 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n===St Helens Town===\n*''Current stadium status'': Proposed.\n[[St Helens Town F.C.]] currently share [[Brocstedes Park]] with [[Ashton Town F.C.]], and may return to the town to a stadium to be built as part of the redevelopment of the Ruskin Drive sports complex.\n\n===Warrington Town===\n*''Current stadium status'': New.\n[[Warrington Town]] announced plans to move from Cantilever Park to a new 5,000\u20136,000 all-seater stadium at the new Omega Development site next to the M62 near Burtonwood.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.pitchero.com/clubs/warringtontown/news/new-stadium-plan-841144.html |author=Gary Skentelbery |title=New Stadium plan |date=24 January 2013 |accessdate=25 January 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Weymouth===\n*''Current stadium status'': Reconstructed.\nOn 27 August 2008, [[Weymouth F.C.]] outlined plans to construct a new 6,000 all-seater stadium, hoped to be open by 2012 when the area hosts sailing events during the [[London Olympics 2012|London Olympics]]. A large part of the cost would be offset by the sale and redevelopment of the existing [[Wessex Stadium]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/w/weymouth/7584639.stm|title=Weymouth vision for new stadium|work=BBC News|date=27 August 2008|accessdate=14 April 2010}}</ref>\n\n===Worcester City===\n*''Current stadium status'': Reconstructed.\n[[Worcester City F.C.|Worcester City]] are planning to move to a new stadium, leaving [[St George's Lane]] after more than a century. They have entered into an agreement with developers St Mowden to construct a new 6000-seat stadium at Nunnery Way. Following a deal falling through. Worcester presently play their home games at Victoria Park. Home of Bromsgrove Sporting.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.worcestercityfc.co.uk/NewStadium/tabid/393/Default.aspx|title=Plans Announced|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090212181858/http://www.worcestercityfc.co.uk/NewStadium/tabid/393/Default.aspx|archivedate=12 February 2009|url-status=dead|publisher=Worcester City F.C.|work=worcestercityfc.co.uk|date=4 October 2007|accessdate=14 April 2010}}</ref>\n\n===Workington===\n*''Current stadium status'': Reconstructed.\nFollowing their recent rise in status, [[Workington A.F.C.|Workington]] are redeveloping their [[Borough Park (Workington)|Borough Park]] home, to comply with FA regulations.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://boroughpark.tripod.com/ |title=Borough Park \u2013 Home Of Workington AFC |publisher=Boroughpark.tripod.com |date= |accessdate=14 April 2010}}</ref> The ground formerly played host to league football until the club's relegation in 1977.\n\n== Expelled clubs ==\n\n===Bury===\n\n*''Current stadium status'': Reconstructed.\n{{Unreferenced section|date=July 2017}}\nIn early 2015 many [[Bury F.C.|Bury]] supporters began speculating that the club were planning a move to nearby Pilsworth at former retail park, Park 66. The site is 2.3 miles from Bury's current home [[Gigg Lane]]. Currently a bowling alley, cinema and several restaurants sit abandoned. The site would be large enough for a stadium if the abandoned buildings were to be demolished. If a stadium were to be built there would be easy access from the nearby M66 motorway. However, in 2016 chairman Stewart Day ruled out Park 66 and is now in talks with Bury Council to try to find a suitable site closer to the town centre.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Proposed British Football Stadiums}}\n{{Football in England table cells}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Developments Of Stadiums In English Football}}\n[[Category:Lists of association football stadiums in England]]\n[[Category:Proposed stadiums in the United Kingdom]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2018}}\nA large number of English football clubs have ongoing schemes to redevelop existing grounds, or to move to newly constructed stadiums. A trend towards all-seater stadiums was initially prescribed by the [[Taylor Report]], and was originally a condition only of [[Premier League]] admission. It has now become a requirement that within three years of a club's first promotion to [[Football League Championship|the Championship]] all paying spectators are seated, even if the club is subsequently relegated. This page provides an (incomplete) list and description of those clubs who have planned new stadiums or refurbishments, or who have already moved/refurbished since around the time of the Taylor Report.\n\nThe following list includes clubs that are based in [[Wales]] but play in the [[English football league system]].\n\n==History==\nWhen [[Scunthorpe United F.C.|Scunthorpe United]] moved to [[Glanford Park]] in 1988, it was the first time a [[The Football League|Football League]] club had moved to a new purpose-built home since 1956.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/chesters-grounds-for-hope-built-in-just-30-weeks-the-deva-stadium-has-allowed-frustrated-fans-to-welcome-their-team-home-from-exile-1542436.html|title=Chester's grounds for hope|newspaper=The Independent|date=25 August 1992|accessdate=19 May 2010|location=London|first=Phil|last=Shaw}}</ref> Up to this point, most sides were playing in grounds that had been largely structurally unchanged for most of the 20th century. One of the few clubs to play in a completely rebuilt post [[World War II]] stadium was [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]], whose stadium had been rebuilt due to bomb damage during the war, and significantly altered in the 1960s and again in the early 1980s.\n\nGround improvements were seldom, most clubs rarely reached their capacity on a regular basis, and poor facilities were commonplace \u2013 this particularly being the case between 1979 and 1986, when attendances fell, with this fall in spectators being blamed largely on increased [[Football hooliganism|hooliganism]], as well as the [[Early 1980s recession|economic downturn]] and sharp rise in unemployment that occurred in the early 1980s. The main source of income came from gate receipts, and most additional money was spent on transfers. It was not until the growing concern in the 1980s about the safety of existing stadiums, that clubs began to examine the possibilities offered by redeveloping their grounds. This was first highlighted in May 1985, when 56 fans were burnt to death [[Bradford City stadium fire|in a fire]] at the [[Bradford City F.C.|Bradford City]] stadium, and even more so in the aftermath of the [[Hillsborough disaster]] of April 1989, which led to the death of 96 [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] fans at an [[FA Cup]] semi-final. Poor maintenance was seen as the main reason for the fire at Bradford, while the presence of perimeter fencing and standing areas (as well as loss of police control) were seen as the main factors in the Hillsborough tragedy.\n\nIn January 1990, the [[Taylor Report]] recommended the conversion of all [[Football League]] stadiums to all-seater arenas<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.footballnetwork.org/dev/communityfootball/violence_taylor_report.asp |title=The Taylor Report |publisher=Footballnetwork.org |date=15 April 1989 |accessdate=13 October 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080415180944/http://www.footballnetwork.org/dev/communityfootball/violence_taylor_report.asp |archivedate=15 April 2008 }}</ref> although this was subsequently applied just to the top two levels with effect from the [[1994-95 in English football|1994\u201395 season]]. The report had ordered third and fourth tier teams to follow suit by 1999, but clubs at this level were allowed to continue with standing accommodation.\n\nThis was given governmental financial assistance, and while unpopular with many fans, attendances began to rise again in the 1990s.\n\nThe new all-seater arrangement tended to be more popular with both the clubs and football authorities, as they had the combined benefits of being safer and more profitable.\n\nThe boom in television rights following the creation of the [[Premier League]] in 1992 allowed a number of clubs to further expand their stadiums, or even move to new ones. Realising the commercial possibilities of new stadiums, many ambitious outfits constructed purpose-built stadiums often on the outskirts of cities or in urban regeneration areas. It has become common for clubs to tie these new stadiums in with residential or leisure complexes.\n\nA number of lower-league clubs had plans for ground improvements halted following the collapse of [[ITV Digital]] and the lucrative broadcasting contract they had agreed.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/business/1896732.stm |title=BUSINESS &#124; ITV Digital goes broke |work=BBC News |date=27 March 2002 |accessdate=14 April 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/business/1961343.stm |title=BUSINESS &#124; The fallout from ITV Digital's collapse |work=BBC News |date=1 May 2002 |accessdate=14 April 2010}}</ref> Following the re-sale of rights, a number of these programmes have been re-activated in recent years, and some of the heaviest stadium redevelopment has been in the lower divisions. Most teams with ambitions of eventual promotion to the Premier League have plans for continued work on their grounds to bring them up to an appropriate standard. Even the biggest clubs have been affected, [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] have heavily rebuilt and expanded [[Old Trafford]] since 1992, while [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] moved to the [[Emirates Stadium]] in 2006.\n\nIn 2015, every stadium in England have to adhere to Accessible Stadia guideline, which each clubs are required to have a certain minimum number of amenity and easy access spaces with accessible toilets. Since then most of England stadium have more accessibility for disabled.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://disabilityhorizons.com/2019/05/accessible-football-stadiums-reviewed-part-1/|title=Accessible football stadiums reviewed by wheelchair user and football fan|date=2019-05-01|website=Disability Horizons|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-01-14}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://sgsa.org.uk/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/Accessible-Stadia-Supplementary-Guidance.pdf|title=Accessible Stadia Supplementary guidance|last=|first=|publisher=Sports Ground Safety Authority|year=2015|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref>\n\nUnder the bullet ''Current stadium status'' below, \"New\" means built after 1988 and replacing a former venue, while \"Reconstructed\" means the club has merely made improvements to their stadium.\n\n{{Expand list|date=August 2008}}\n\n==Premier League==\n===AFC Bournemouth===\n\n* Stadium: [[Dean Court|Vitality Stadium]] \n* Capacity: 11,364<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|url=https://premierleague-static-files.s3.amazonaws.com/premierleague/document/2019/08/02/add6ee50-25c6-4474-8854-edf8a56c23c1/2019-20-PL-Handbook-020819.pdf|title=Premier League Handbook Season 2019/20|last=|first=|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref>\n*''Current stadium status'': Reconstructed.\n[[A.F.C. Bournemouth|Bournemouth's]] [[Dean Court]] ground was completely rebuilt in 2001, with the pitch rotated ninety degrees from its original position. The stadium was also moved away from adjacent housing. Although it was rebuilt as a three sided stadium, seats were placed on the undeveloped South End in the autumn of 2005. These seats were removed when the club was relegated to the bottom tier in 2008 but installed once more following promotion back to League One in 2010. Following promotion to the [[Sky Bet Championship]] in 2013 the club installed a larger, roofed temporary stand, bringing the total ground capacity just shy of 12,000. This was named after club legend, the [[Ted MacDougall]] Stand. After a successful debut [[Premier League]] campaign, the club submitted a planning application to Bournemouth Borough Council to redevelop the temporary Ted MacDougall Stand with a much larger one which would take the capacity of the ground to 14,529.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.afcb.co.uk/news/article/south-stand-afc-bournemouth-stadium-expansion-plans-3012635.aspx|title=South Stand: See the full plans for AFC Bournemouth's potential South Stand development|last=afcb.co.uk|access-date=19 January 2017}}</ref> However these plans have been put on hold and just nine months later the club announced that they were seeking a new site on which to build a new stadium, with a view to being ready for the 2020/21 season.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.afcb.co.uk/news/article/2016-17/club-statement-afc-bournemouth-vitality-stadium-3459607.aspx|title=Club statement: AFC Bournemouth chief executive Neill Blake makes statement on Vitality Stadium|last=afcb.co.uk|access-date=19 January 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Arsenal===\n\n* Stadium: [[Emirates Stadium]]\n* Capacity: 60,704<ref name=\":0\" />\n*''Current stadium status'': New.\n[[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] moved to the [[Emirates Stadium]] in 2006, which has massively boosted club income.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/a/arsenal/7009944.stm |title=BBC SPORT &#124; Football &#124; My Club &#124; Arsenal &#124; Arsenal bullish over \u00a3200m income |work=BBC News |date=24 September 2007 |accessdate=14 April 2010}}</ref> At present, the capacity is 60,355 (seated), with currently no public plans to expand it despite strong average attendances of 60,025 in the Premier League. Emirates Stadium is the third largest club ground in England, after Old Trafford and Tottenham\u2018s new White Hart Lane. The Emirates replaced [[Arsenal Stadium|Highbury]], where the club had been based since 1913, which itself had been substantially updated in the early 1990s and reduced capacity from 59,000 to an all-seater 38,500 by 1993. However, this was deemed inadequate by 1998 and led to the club's directors deciding that relocation was necessary, prompting the club to build a new stadium, with the site at Ashburton Grove being selected in November 1999 (after a bid to buy [[Wembley Stadium]] failed) and work beginning in the spring of 2004. It finally opened for the [[2006-07 in English football|2006\u201307 season]].\n\n===Aston Villa===\n\n* Stadium: [[Villa Park]]\n* Capacity: 42,095<ref name=\":0\" />\n*''Current stadium status'': Reconstructed.\n[[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]] have planning permission to increase [[Villa Park]] from 42,000 to 50,000 seats by expanding the North Stand. Villa Park has been all-seater since 1994, when the Holte End was rebuilt, but did not reach its current capacity until the Trinity Road Stand was rebuilt in the [[2000-01 in English football|2000\u201301 season]]. No major developments have taken place since, although plans have been in the pipeline since the late 1990s to take the stadium's capacity to more than 50,000\n\n===Brighton and Hove Albion===\n\n* Stadium: [[Falmer Stadium|The American Express Community Stadium]]\n* Capacity: 30,750<ref name=\":0\" />\n*''Current stadium status'': New.\n\nBrighton's 14-year wait for a permanent home came to an end when Brighton moved to [[Falmer Stadium]], in 2011, with a capacity of 22,000 seats. The stadium had built into its design the ability to have capacity increased to 30,750, which has been completed as of the end of the 2012\u201313 season. This has been done by filling in all four corners of the stadium and adding an extra tier to the top of the East Stand. Extra corporate boxes and hospitality suites have also been added to the existing South Stand mezzanine, and the 1901 Club West Stand middle tier has been extended around each corner.\n\nBrighton had been without a permanent home since May 1997, when they left the [[Goldstone Ground]] after 95 years after it was sold to a developer in an effort to ease the club's financial crisis. Two seasons were spent ground-sharing with [[Gillingham F.C.|Gillingham]] before the club returned to Brighton to a temporary home at [[Withdean Athletics Stadium]], although the aim from the outset was to build a new stadium in the Falmer area.\n\n===Burnley===\n\n* Stadium: [[Turf Moor]]\n* Capacity: 21,944<ref name=\":0\" />\n*''Current stadium status'': Reconstructed.\n\nSince consolidating their place in the [[Premier League]], [[Burnley F.C.|Burnley]] have made several structural and cosmetic improvements to [[Turf Moor]].\nWork has been completed outside the stadium including new a new club shop and corporate facilities, and work has begun building two purpose-built corner stands between the James Hargreaves, [[Jimmy McIlroy]] and [[Bob Lord (football chairman)|Bob Lord]] stands that will house disabled supporters. This work is due to be completed in time for the 2018\u201319 season.\n\n===Chelsea===\n\n* Stadium: [[Stamford Bridge (stadium)|Stamford Bridge]]\n* Capacity: 40,834<ref name=\":0\" />\n*''Current stadium status'': Reconstructed. Reconstruction on hold indefinitely.\n\nFollowing [[Roman Abramovich]]'s takeover, [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]] have examined expanding their current home at [[Stamford Bridge (stadium)|Stamford Bridge]] to a capacity of over 50,000.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/c/chelsea/4630618.stm |title=BBC SPORT &#124; Football &#124; My Club &#124; Chelsea &#124; Chelsea plan Bridge redevelopment |work=BBC News |date=20 January 2006 |accessdate=14 April 2010}}</ref> Numerous problems over health and safety issues have stalled this, because due to the stadium's location fans can only exit onto the [[Fulham Road]].<ref>{{cite book | author=Glanvill | year=2006 | title=Chelsea FC: The Official Biography | page=76}}</ref> The club have thus been linked with moves to a number of potential sites in west [[London]], including a site at [[Earl's Court]], although the club have indicated no such plans exist.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.mirrorfootball.co.uk/news/Chelsea-have-reiterated-their-desire-to-stay-at-Stamford-Bridge-claiming-history-and-tradition-outweigh-the-desire-for-bigger-crowds-article596067.html |title=Chelsea rule out move from the Bridge |newspaper=Daily Mirror |date=7 October 2010 |accessdate=15 March 2011}}</ref> A further stumbling block is that the club's [[naming rights]] are owned by the [[Chelsea Pitch Owners]], which also owns the Stamford Bridge [[Freehold (law)|freehold]]. As a condition for using the Chelsea FC name, the club has to play its first team matches at Stamford Bridge. A move to a new stadium could mean the club having to change their name.<ref>{{cite book | author=Glanvill | year=2006 | title=Chelsea FC: The Official Biography | pages=91\u201392}}</ref> Stamford Bridge was extensively rebuilt between 1993 and 1998, with three stands being replaced and the circular track between the pitch and stands being removed, and the only pre-1993 stand at the stadium being the 1974 East Stand structure. This achieved a 34,000 all-seater capacity which had been given the go-ahead in July 1990. The current capacity of just under 42,000 was reached in 2001.\n\nIn November 2015, Chelsea Football Club announced that they have submitted plans to the Local Authority to build a new 60,000 seater stadium on the Stamford Bridge site, which would match the current capacity of Arsenal's Emirates Stadium and only be surpassed by Old Trafford, and Tottenham's new stadium in the Premier League.\n\n===Crystal Palace===\n\n* Stadium: [[Selhurst Park|Selhurt Park]]\n* Capacity: 25,486<ref name=\":0\" />\n*''Current stadium status'': Reconstructed.\n\nIn January 2011, [[Crystal Palace F.C.|Crystal Palace]] announced plans to move from their run-down [[Selhurst Park]] home to return to the [[Crystal Palace National Sports Centre]] (on the site of the original ground the club left in 1915, a stadium that also hosted the [[FA Cup final]] from 1895 to 1914). The plans involve demolishing the existing structure and redeveloping it into a 40,000-seater [[Crystal Palace Park (stadium)|purpose-built football stadium]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cpfc.co.uk/page/News/0,,10323~2271669,00.html |title=Eagles Fly Home |publisher=Crystal Palace F.C. |work=cpfc.co.uk |date=28 June 2011 |accessdate=4 November 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110907152719/http://www.cpfc.co.uk/page/News/0%2C%2C10323~2271669%2C00.html |archivedate=7 September 2011 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.]] also released plans to redevelop the NSC into a 25,000-seater stadium, maintaining it as an athletics stadium, as part of their plans to redevelop the [[Olympic Stadium (London)|Olympic Stadium]] after the [[2012 Summer Olympics]] and [[2012 Summer Paralympics|Paralympics]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goal.com/en-gb/news/2896/premier-league/2011/01/28/2327743/tottenham-release-images-of-proposed-crystal-palace |title=Tottenham release images of proposed Crystal Palace Athletics Stadium |publisher=Goal.com |date=28 January 2011 |accessdate=4 November 2011}}</ref> However, Spurs' failure to secure the site, which instead went to [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]] has left the road clear for Palace to pursue the site.\n\nTheir current [[Selhurst Park]] home has been all-seater since the mid 1990s, holding more than 26,000 spectators. In December 2017, the club announced plans to undertake a redevelopment of the Main Stand at Selhurst Park, raising the capacity to approximately 34,000, with the new structure ready by 2021.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/sport/football/crystal-palace-reveal-plan-to-build-new-100m-main-stand-at-selhurst-park-a3709841.html |title=Crystal Palace reveal plan to build new \u00a3100m main stand at Selhurst Park |last=Muro |first=Giuseppe |date=4 December 2017 |website=standard.co.uk |publisher=Evening Standard |access-date=29 January 2018 |quote=}}</ref>\n\n===Everton===\n\n* Stadium: [[Goodison Park]]\n* Capacity: 39,414<ref name=\":0\" />\n*''Current stadium status:'' Reconstructed.\n\n[[Everton F.C.|Everton]] were planning to relocate to a [[Everton Kirkby Project|new stadium]] in [[Kirkby]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/merseyside/7168024.stm |title=England &#124; Merseyside &#124; Everton submit new stadium plans |work=BBC News |date=2 January 2008 |accessdate=14 April 2010}}</ref> This generated a large amount of controversy,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nsno.co.uk/news.php?item.2426.1 |title=Nil Satis Nisi Optimum: Keep Everton in Our City |publisher=Nsno.co.uk |date=31 March 1906 |accessdate=13 October 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080305073134/http://www.nsno.co.uk/news.php?item.2426.1 |archivedate=5 March 2008 }}</ref> as it was beyond the city limits of [[Liverpool]]. In June 2008 Kirkby council approved the new stadium, however, following a public inquiry that was held in December 2008, the stadium was rejected by the Secretary of State in November 2009.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/news/liverpool-news/everton-fcs-plans-50000-seater-3457040|title=Everton FC's plans for a 50,000-seater stadium could by delayed by a year|date=14 March 2009|newspaper=Liverpool Echo|accessdate=13 October 2013}}</ref>\n\nIt is planned to have 50,401 seats initially, with potential to increase to 60,000 at a later date. The club's current stadium has been all-seater (with a capacity of just over 40,000) since 1994, when a new stand was built at one end of the ground. The Main Stand was built in 1970, while the two remaining stands are refurbished interwar structures.\n\nThe first plans for relocation were announced in 1996. A site at [[King's Dock, Port of Liverpool|King's Dock]] was identified and bid for in 2000, with a view to building a new stadium with 55,000 to 60,000 seats.<ref>{{cite news|title=Goodison exit moves ever closer|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/e/everton/959934.stm|work=BBC Sport|date=6 October 2000|accessdate=15 November 2012}}</ref> These plans were then shelved in 2003 when chairman [[Bill Kenwright]] said that the club could not raise adequate funds.<ref>{{cite news|title=Everton move off|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/2399479/Everton-move-off.html|work=The Telegraph|date=11 April 2003|accessdate=15 November 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Leicester City===\n\n* Stadium: [[King Power Stadium]]\n* Capacity: 32,261<ref name=\":0\" />\n*''Current stadium status'': New.\n\nLeicester have announced plans to extend the King Power Stadium to 42,000 seats.<ref name=\"foxes\">{{cite web|title=Leicester City could increase capacity at the King Power Stadium to 42,000|url=http://www.leicestermercury.co.uk/Leicester-City-increase-capacity-King-Power/story-26656839-detail/story.html|website=Leicester Mercury|accessdate=5 April 2016|date=8 June 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160102235844/http://www.leicestermercury.co.uk/Leicester-City-increase-capacity-King-Power/story-26656839-detail/story.html|archive-date=2 January 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> The owners announced in June 2015 that they had begun the application for permission to build. This expansion plan will most likely extend the east stand, and possibly the south stand (Kop) into 2-tier stands.\n\nThe club have played at their 32,500-seat stadium since relocating from nearby [[Filbert Street]] in 2002. They had spent 111 years at Filbert Street and converted it into an all-seater format in 1993 with the construction of one new stand and the refurbishment of the three others, but a run of success in the top flight prompted demand for tickets vastly outstripping supply, and the stadium's confined location made expansion difficult, so by 1998 the decision was made to build a new stadium. However, the relocation to a new stadium took place in the same year as relegation from the Premier League, putting a huge strain on the club's finances and leading to a spell in [[Receivership|administration]] as debts reached more than \u00a330million.\n\n===Liverpool===\n\n* Stadium: [[Anfield]]\n* Capacity: 53,394<ref name=\":0\" />\n*''Current stadium status'': Reconstructed. 7,000 Anfield Road expansion plan.\n\nIn May 2002, [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] announced plans to build a new 55,000-seat [[Stanley Park Stadium|stadium]] in [[Stanley Park, Liverpool|Stanley Park]], near their current [[Anfield]] home.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/liverpool/content/articles/2007/11/07/liverpoolfc.shtml |title=Liverpool's new stadium in Stanley Park moves a step closer |publisher=BBC |date=7 November 2007 |accessdate=14 April 2010 |first=Simon |last=Moffatt}}</ref> The stadium's planned capacity was then increased to more than 66,000, with preliminary construction beginning in 2007.\n\nAnfield has been all-seater since the mid-1990s, when the Spion Kop was rebuilt two years after the completion of the Centenary Stand on the southern side of the stadium. The Main Stand dates back to the early 1970s, while the Anfield Road Stand was already all-seater when it was rebuilt in 1997.\n\nConstruction of the new stadium, however, was halted in 2008 due to lack of funds combined with the [[Late 2000s recession|onset of the recession]].\n\nThe relocation was first proposed in 2000, when the club had been hoping to have a 70,000-seat stadium ready for the 2004\u201305 season. In May 2002 it was decided that relocation was a more viable option than expansion, when the plans were amended for a less expensive 55,000-seat stadium to be built.\n\n<span>In April 2014 Liverpool F.C. signed a legal agreement with Liverpool City Council and Your Housing Group to redevelop the surrounding Anfield area. This is seen as a significant step towards the renovation of the stadium. The redevelopment was worth around \u00a3260 million.</span><ref>{{cite news| title=Liverpool sign heads of terms on road to Anfield stadium redevelopment | first=Andy|last=Hunter|work=The Guardian|date=17 April 2014|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2014/apr/17/liverpool-heads-of-terms-anfield-stadium-redevelopment |accessdate=18 April 2014 }}</ref><span> On 9 September 2016, the first phase of expansion was completed, bringing the total capacity 54,047. On 10 September, the newly renovated Anfield was opened for its first use in a [[Premier League]] game against [[Leicester City F.C.|Leicester City]]. Plans to expand the Anfield Road stand have been announced to increase the capacity to over 60,000. However, as of yet these plans have not been officially published.</span>\n\nAnfield Road expansion plan were allowed to be expired on September 2019<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thisisanfield.com/2019/11/photos-how-anfield-will-change-as-liverpool-release-images-of-anfield-road-end-plans/|title=PHOTOS: How Liverpool's Anfield Road end expansion will look|date=2019-11-29|website=This Is Anfield|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-12-18}}</ref> and Liverpool resubmitted a new \u00a360M plan which will push Anfield capacity into 61,000. The expansion plan includes granting permission of permanent hosting concert and other major events such as American Football<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.liverpoolfc.com/news/announcements/375238-liverpool-fc-launches-public-consultation-anfield-road-expansion|title=LFC launches first-stage public consultation on proposed Anfield Road Stand expansion|website=Liverpool FC|access-date=2019-12-18}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newcivilengineer.com/latest/liverpool-fc-submits-plans-60m-stadium-expansion-03-12-2019/|title=Liverpool FC submits plans for \u00a360M stadium expansion|last=Stein|first=Joshua|date=2019-12-03|website=New Civil Engineer|language=en|access-date=2019-12-18}}</ref>\n\n===Manchester City===\n\n* Stadium: [[City of Manchester Stadium|Etihad Stadium]]\n* Capacity: 55,017<ref name=\":0\" />\n*''Current stadium status'': New \u2013 expansion to 54,000 completed August 2015.\n\nCity have played at the [[City of Manchester Stadium]] since 2003 (it was completed for the [[2002 Commonwealth Games|previous year's]] [[Commonwealth Games]]) and for the previous 80 years had played at [[Maine Road]], which had been converted into an all-seater format during the 1990s with the construction of two new stands, giving it a capacity of just over 35,000, although in its early days it had held crowds of more than 80,000.\n\nThe decision to relocate to the City of Manchester Stadium was made in 1997, in place of previous plans for Maine Road to be expanded to 45,000 seats, which had initially been postponed a year earlier due to City's relegation.\n\nManchester City were taken over by the [[Abu Dhabi United Group]] in September 2008, and quickly earmarked land around Eastlands for redevelopment. A memorandum of understanding has since been formed with Manchester City Council, and City jointly own 200 acres of land in the vicinity of Eastlands.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Club statement: East Manchester|url=http://www.mcfc.co.uk/news/club-news/2011/march/club-announcement-east-mcr |work=mcfc.co.uk|publisher=Manchester City F.C.|date=3 March 2011}}</ref> In July 2011, the City of Manchester Stadium was renamed the Etihad Stadium which would help fund the redevelopment.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Revealed: Sporting mecca at the heart of Etihad's record sponsorship of Manchester City|url=http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/greater-manchester-news/revealed-sporting-mecca-at-the-heart-of-etihads-865129|work=Manchester Evening News|publisher=Trinity Mirror|date=9 July 2011|first=Deborah|last=Linton}}</ref> The first developments include a new state-of-the-art training complex for Manchester City and the local community is to be built nearby the Etihad Stadium with a centrepiece bridge linking the complex to the stadium.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Our Proposal |url=http://www.cityfootballacademy.co.uk/the-vision/our-plans/ |work=cityfootballacademy.co.uk |accessdate=13 October 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20131013164502/http://www.cityfootballacademy.co.uk/the-vision/our-plans/ |archivedate=13 October 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nAfter two seasons with virtually every league match selling out, City announced that they were in the process of applying for planning permission for an expansion of approximately 13,500 seats, which would make the ground the second largest club ground in the [[United Kingdom]], and the seventh largest stadium of any type in the same, at approximately 61,000 total seats.<ref>{{Cite news |title=MCFC invites fans to join stadium expansion waiting list |url=http://www.mcfc.co.uk/News/Club-news/2013/October/Stadium-waiting-list |work=mcfc.co.uk |date=10 October 2013}}</ref>\n\nAfter receiving planning permission for stadium expansion on 14 February 2014, City announced their intention to begin construction of a third tier of seating on the South Stand only.<ref name=\"expansionstatement\">{{cite web |url=http://www.mcfc.co.uk/News/Club-news/2014/February/Club-statement-14-February? |title=Club Statement 14 February |date=14 February 2014 |accessdate=14 February 2014}}</ref> Although they noted that permission has been received for expansion to the North Stand along with further pitch-side seating, the club is at present holding off on these projects.<ref name=\"expansionstatement\" /> With the South Stand expansion adding approximately 6,250 seats, the new capacity of the stadium after construction will be just above 54,000.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-manchester-26168685 |title=Manchester City's Etihad Stadium expansion approved |date=13 February 2014 |accessdate=14 February 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2015, the 7,000 seat third tier on the South Stand was completed, in time for the start of the 2015\u201316 football season. The expansion was designed to be in keeping with the existing roof design. A North Stand third tier has planning approval and work on it is expected to begin by 2017, increasing capacity to around 61,000.\n\n===Manchester United===\n\n* Stadium: [[Old Trafford]]\n* Capacity: 74,879<ref>{{Cite book|title=Premier League Handbook 2018/19|last=|first=|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref>\n*''Current stadium status'': Reconstructed.\n\nSince 1992, [[Old Trafford]] has undergone a massive facelift converting the stadium into a 76,000 all-seater, the largest club stadium in the [[United Kingdom]].\n\nOld Trafford has been United's home since 1910, and after decades of gradual development (and a complete rebuild following bomb damage in [[World War II]]) became largely all-seater in the [[1992-93 in English football|1992\u20131993 season]] when the Stretford End was rebuilt, and completely all-seater the following season once the Scoreboard Paddock had been converted, giving it the country's largest capacity at club level with more than 45,000 seats, although demand for tickets vastly outstripped supply. Further redevelopment took place in [[1995-96 in English football|1995\u201396]] when the 30-year-old North Stand was bulldozed to make way for a new three-tier structure. The other two stands at Old Trafford were expanded in the [[1999-2000 in English football|1999\u20132000 season]] and the latest expansion took place in [[2006-07 in English football|2006\u201307]] with the enlargement of seating in the quadrants. There have been proposals for the South Stand to become triple-tiered; also this would increase the capacity to 92,300 (a higher capacity than even Wembley Stadium); however, the railway station and tracks have hindered such ideas and seem to be on ice for the foreseeable future. If this expansion did take place, it would even allow for attendances that were not seen in the days when Old Trafford had standing areas.\n\n===Newcastle United===\n\n* Stadium: [[St James' Park]]\n* Capacity: 52,305<ref name=\":0\" />\n*''Current stadium status'': Reconstructed.\n\nIn 2007 under the chairmanship of [[Freddy Shepherd]], [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]] announced plans to increase the capacity of [[St James' Park]] by 8,000 to 60,000 by rebuilding the Gallowgate End as part of a \u00a3300m scheme to redevelop the stadium and its surrounding area.<ref>\n{{cite news\n | title =Newcastle announce ground plans\n | work =[[BBC News]]\n | publisher =[[bbc.co.uk]]\n | date =2 April 2007\n | url =http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/n/newcastle_united/6517989.stm\n | accessdate =2 April 2007}}</ref> This would cure [[St James' Park]] of its current lopsided appearance.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.footballgroundguide.com/newcastle_united.htm |title=The Internet Football Grounds Guide \u2013 St James Park, Newcastle United |publisher=Footballgroundguide.com |accessdate=14 April 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110519180422/http://www.footballgroundguide.com/newcastle_united.htm |archivedate=19 May 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> The plans appeared to have been shelved upon the 2007 takeover and review of the club by [[Mike Ashley (businessman)|Mike Ashley]], who subsequently announced in 2008 he would be selling the club. The club had trouble selling out games in the 2008\u201309 season as Newcastle headed towards relegation after 16 years in the Premier League, and also in the promotion winning campaign of 2009\u201310, as they played at a lower level.\n\nSt James's Park was initially revamped between 1992 and 1995 to give it a 36,000-seat capacity, but the most recent expansion did not take place until 1999\u20132000, in time for the 2000\u201301 season. In 1995, with demand for tickets exceeding the initial all-seater capacity, there had been plans relocate to a new 50,000-seat stadium at [[Castle Leazes]], but these were abandoned in favour of expanding the existing stadium.\n\n===Norwich City===\n\n* Stadium: [[Carrow Road]]\n* Capacity: 27,359<ref name=\":0\" />\n*''Current stadium status'': Reconstructed.\n\n[[Norwich City F.C.|Norwich City]] increased the capacity of [[Carrow Road]] to 27,000 over the Summer of 2010; nearly 20 years after the conversion to an all-seater stadium had given it a capacity of more than 21,000. There are plans to further expand Carrow Road by around 8,000 either by the redevelopment of the Geoffrey Watling City Stand or by adding a second tier to the Jarrold Stand, taking the capacity to around 35,000 seats. The initial conversion to an all-seater capacity in the early 1990s saw the stadium have more than 21,000 seats.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/n/norwich/9366650.stm|title=Norwich City consider full-on push for promotion|date=19 January 2011|publisher=BBC|accessdate=8 March 2012}}</ref> The club confirmed in September 2012 that the feasibility of a 7,000-seat development has been backed by the [[University of East Anglia]], based on factors such as \"population growth, and real numbers, such as socio-economic data, and not instinct or intuition.\"<ref name=\"EDP\">{{cite news|url=http://www.edp24.co.uk/sport/norwich-city-fc/norwich_city_playing_squad_comes_first_then_carrow_road_expansion_says_david_mcnally_1_152427|title=Norwich City playing squad comes first \u2013 then Carrow Road expansion, says David McNally|last=Cuffley|first=David|date=20 September 2012|work=Eastern Daily Press|accessdate=21 September 2012|publisher=Archant}}</ref> The likely cost has been estimated at \u00a320m, but that \"Currently, every spare penny is reinvested in the first team squad and this is something that the board wishes to continue in the short term.\"<ref name=\"EDP\" />\n\nThe building of a [[Holiday Inn]] franchise in one corner of the ground, has somewhat diminished possibilities for the future enlargement of Carrow Road. However, the club is looking at options to build a small stand in front of the hotel in the short-term.<ref name=\"EDP\" />\n\n===Sheffield United===\n\n* Stadium: [[Bramall Lane]]\n* Capacity: 32,125<ref name=\":0\" />\n*''Current stadium status'': Reconstructed.\n\n[[Sheffield United F.C.|Sheffield United]] announced in 2009 plans to redevelop the Kop Stand, extending it backwards to create an additional 3,215 seats, alongside adding an additional tier to the South Stand. Planned for when the club were promoted back to the [[Premier League]], these would also include significant upgrades to the concourse. While these are yet to be completed, the permission to build was secured in 2009, and the plans were most recently resubmitted for approval in 2017.<ref name=\"sufc.co.uk\">{{cite news|url= https://www.sufc.co.uk/news/2017/december/south-stand-plans/|title=South Stand Plans|publisher=Sheffield United F.C.|accessdate=7 December 2017}}</ref> The developments were planned to be built through two phases, with the Kop first, taking capacity up to 37,000, followed by the South Stand.<ref name=\"insidermedia.com\">{{cite news|url= https://www.insidermedia.com/news/yorkshire/blades-to-kickstart-bramall-lane-redevelopment|title=Blades To Kickstart Bramall Lane Redevelopment|publisher=Insider Media|accessdate=11 November 2015}}</ref> The additional tier for the South Stand would potentially provide 5,400 seats.\n\n[[Bramall Lane]] became all-seater in the mid-1990s after completion of two new stands and the refurbishment of two existing stands. The most recent addition to the stadium is the Westfield Corner, filling in the gap between the South and Bramall Lane stands, which was completed in summer 2006.\n\n===Southampton===\n\n* Stadium: [[St Mary's Stadium]]\n* Capacity: 32,384<ref name=\":0\" />\n*''Current stadium status'': New.\n\n[[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]] left [[The Dell (Southampton)|The Dell]] for a new ground, [[St Mary's Stadium]], in 2001. The stadium has a capacity of 32,505 and is currently the largest football stadium in the South of England (excluding London). Relocation had been in the pipeline since the 1980s, although Southampton had converted The Dell into an all-seater stadium in the early 1990s as a temporary measure, leaving it with a capacity of less than 16,000.\n\n===Tottenham Hotspur===\n\n* Stadium: [[Tottenham Hotspur Stadium]]\n* Capacity: 62,303<ref name=\"capacity\">{{cite news|url=https://www.tottenhamhotspur.com/the-stadium/local/|title=Local: Information for local residents and businesses|publisher=Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|accessdate=18 December 2019}}</ref>\n*''Current stadium status'': New.\n\n[[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham]] have been planning a larger stadium since the late 1990s, however, it was undecided whether this strategy would involve expanding [[White Hart Lane]] (which has held some 36,000 all-seated fans since the early 1990s) or moving to a new site.  Spurs announced in the [[Northumberland Development Project]] (NDP) on 30 October 2008 that the club planned to build a new stadium on the existing White Hart Lane site combined with land purchased or optioned to the north, creating a [[New Tottenham Hotspur stadium|56,250-seater stadium]].<ref name=\"Sheringham\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/t/tottenham_hotspur/8326735.stm|title=Spurs aim for new stadium by 2012|last=Sheringham|first=Sam|date=26 October 2009|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=31 March 2015}}</ref> The new development would include leisure facilities, shops, housing, a club museum, public space and also a new base for the Tottenham Hotspur Foundation. Initial public consultations took place in December 2008 and a further consultations on the NDP's more detailed plans were held at the start of April 2009.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.tottenhamhotspur.com/news/club-reveal-next-stage-plans-for-northumberland-development-project-010109/|title=Club reveal next stage plans for the NDP |publisher=THFC |date=3 April 2009|accessdate=13 October 2013}}</ref> A planning application was submitted to [[Haringey Council]] in October 2009. However, following criticism by [[English Heritage]] and other conservation groups about the proposed demolition of listed buildings, the club withdrew the plans in May 2010 in favour of a revised plan which retained the listed buildings and improved the public areas around the stadium.<ref>[http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/sport/football/premier_league/tottenham/article7131149.ece Tottenham's plans to redevelop White Hart Lane shown red card ''Times online''] Accessed 22 May 2010</ref>\n\nOn 30 September 2010 the Planning Committee of Haringey Council unanimously approved the revised planning application and the [[Mayor of London]] gave his approval on 25 November 2010.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/t/tottenham_hotspur/9228658.stm Tottenham's White Hart Lane stadium plans approved BBC Sport online], Accessed 25 November 2010</ref>\n\nAfter an extended period of negotiations with Haringey Council and the Mayor of London, leading to a [[Town and Country Planning Act 1990#Section 106|Section 106 agreement]], planning permissions were issued on 20 September 2011.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/14996725.stm|title=Tottenham sign planning agreement to build new stadium|publisher=BBC|date=20 September 2011}}</ref> Following the [[2011 England riots|riots in Tottenham, other parts of London and elsewhere in England]] in August 2011, the [[Greater London Authority]] and Haringey Council announced on 28 September that it would relieve the club of all community infrastructure payments that planners would normally require, estimated at \u00a38.5m, and to provide a further \u00a38.5m for regeneration and infrastructure projects.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-london-15095674|title=Club reveal next stage plans for Northumberland Development Tottenham stadium: Club offered White Hart Lane deal|publisher=BBC |date=28 September 2011|accessdate=18 November 2011}}</ref> On 11 July 2014 the Secretary of State for the [[Department for Communities and Local Government]] announced that a [[compulsory purchase order]] had been granted for the outstanding parcel of land required for the development of the new stadium site.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/new-tottenham-hotspur-stadium-scheme-gets-the-green-light|title=New Tottenham Hotspur stadium scheme gets the green light|date=11 July 2014|publisher=Department for Communities and Local Government|accessdate=13 July 2014}}</ref> In February 2015 this compulsory purchase order was subject to an unsuccessful legal challenge by the business that owned the land.<ref name=\"highcourt\">[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/tottenham-hotspur/11424828/Tottenham-plans-for-new-stadium-given-massive-boost-as-business-looking-to-block-move-loses-High-Court-appeal.htmlTottenham plans for new stadium given massive boost as business looking to block move loses High Court appeal.] ''[[Daily Telegraph]]''<span wfd-id=\"5307\"> 20 February 2015</span>, Accessed 20 February 2015</ref> The anticipated stadium opening date was revised several times.<ref name=\"stadiumopening\">[http://m.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-london-30831515 Tottenham Hotspur stadium dispute firm in court challenge BBC News online 15 January 2015], Accessed 25 May 2015</ref>\n\nThe new stadium, [[Tottenham Hotspur Stadium]], opened with a ceremony on 3 April 2019 before its first competitive Premier League game, which was against [[Crystal Palace F.C.|Crystal Palace]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/sport/football/tottenham/tottenham-hotspur-stadium-opening-ceremony-spurs-pay-homage-to-regeneration-of-local-area-after-2011-a4108686.html |title=Tottenham Hotspur stadium opening ceremony: Spurs pay homage to regeneration of local area after 2011 riots |date=3 April 2019 |work=Evening Standard |accessdate=4 April 2019 |first= Jack |last=Rosser }}</ref> It opened with a stadium capacity of 62,062 which has since been increased to 62,303.<ref name=capacity /> The new stadium features two pitches\u2014an advanced artificial pitch to be used primarily for [[American football]], and a slide-in grass pitch to be used for association football. This is similar to the setup of the [[Sapporo Dome]] in Japan, a venue used for both baseball and association football. On 7 July 2015, Tottenham and the [[National Football League]] (NFL) announced that the new stadium would host at least [[NFL International Series|two NFL games each season]] from 2018 through to 2027.<ref>{{cite press release|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000500560/article/nfl-tottenham-hotspur-ink-10year-stadium-partnership |title=NFL, Tottenham Hotspur ink 10-year stadium partnership |publisher=National Football League |date=7 July 2015 |accessdate=11 July 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe capacity was further increased on 5 August 2019 with additional 148 seat, increased the overall capacity into 62,214.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://talksport.com/football/582476/tottenham-stadium-update-spurs-capacity/|title=Spurs given permission to increase capacity of Tottenham Hotspur Stadium|last=161385360554578|date=2019-08-05|website=talkSPORT|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-18}}</ref> Further 89 seats were added on 17 December 2019 and the capacity increased into 62,303 after being granted permission from Haringey Council.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tottenhamhotspur.com/news/2019/december/application-to-increase-stadium-capacity-approved/|title=Application to increase stadium capacity approved|website=Tottenham Hotspur|language=en|access-date=2019-12-18}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.90min.com/posts/6520023-tottenham-granted-permission-to-increase-stadium-capacity-for-the-second-time-since-opening|title=Tottenham Granted Permission to Increase Stadium Capacity for the Second Time Since Opening|date=2019-12-18|website=90min.com|language=en|access-date=2019-12-18}}</ref>\n\n===Watford===\n\n* Stadium: [[Vicarage Road]]\n* Capacity: 22,200<ref name=\":0\" />\n*''Current stadium status'': Reconstructed.\n\n[[Watford F.C.|Watford]] play their home games at the 20,877 seater [[Vicarage Road|Vicarage Road Stadium]] after the new 3,400 East Stand, known as the Sir Elton John stand, was completed.\n\nIn June 2015, the club announced that the staircases of the Sir Elton John stand would be removed and replaced with 700 seats.<ref>{{cite web|title=Extra Sir Elton John Stand Capacity|url=http://www.watfordfc.com/news/article/stadium-2483443.aspx|publisher=Watford FC|accessdate=11 June 2015}}</ref> The club announced that the North East corner would be transformed and 400 seats added to it,<ref>{{cite web |title=North-East Corner Transformation To Begin |url=http://www.watfordfc.com/news/article/150608-vicarage-road-stadium-north-east-corner-2486084.aspx |publisher=Watford FC |accessdate=11 June 2015}}</ref> thus taking the total capacity to 22,000.\n\n===West Ham United===\n\n* Stadium: [[London Stadium]]\n* Capacity: 60,000<ref name=\":0\" />\n*''Current stadium status'': New.\n\n[[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]] shelved plans for a new stadium in east London at a Parcelforce depot adjacent to [[West Ham tube station]] following their chairman's bankruptcy in the Icelandic financial crisis. In October 2010 the club formally registered an interest in conjunction with [[Newham Borough Council]] in taking over the nearby [[Olympic Stadium (London)|2012 Olympic Stadium]]. The plan involved a 60,000-capacity stadium and the retention of the running track. A converted Olympic stadium would be part of the 2018 World Cup bid. On 12 November 2010 the [[Olympic Park Legacy Company]] (OPLC) announced that West Ham and Tottenham Hotspur were the two preferred bidders to take over the Olympic stadium after the 2012 Olympics.<ref name=\"bbc.co.uk\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-london-11746496|title=Tottenham and West Ham lead London 2012 stadium bid|accessdate=12 November 2010|date=12 November 2010|work=BBC News}}</ref>\n\nThe OPLC announced on 11 February 2011 that [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham]] had been selected as the preferred bidder for the Olympic Stadium. The decision was subsequently ratified by Government departments and the Mayor of London.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-london-12424549|title=West Ham chosen as preferred Olympic Stadium tenant|work=BBC News|accessdate=12 February 2011}}</ref> However, following a legal challenge by Tottenham Hotspur and Leyton Orient over the operation of the bidding process the Olympic Park Legacy Company decided in October 2011 to nullify the first bid process, change the legacy handover arrangements, and launch a new bidding process to look for consortiums to lease the stadium.<ref name=\"olympicstadiumbid\">{{cite news| url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-london-14646806 | work=BBC News | title=Spurs win right to challenge 2012 stadium decision | date=24 August 2011}}</ref> In March 2012 West Ham and Newham Council submitted a bid under the revamped process.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/olympics/17489659|work=BBC Sport|title=London 2012: West Ham bid to be Olympic Stadium tenants|date=23 March 2012}}</ref>\n\nUpton Park had been all-seater since the mid 1990s, the most recent development being the construction of the Dr Martens Stand in the [[2000-01 in English football|2000\u201301 season]] which gave the club a 35,000 capacity, up from the 26,000 capacity reached in the mid 1990s when Upton Park first became all-seater.\n\nAt the start of the 2016\u201317 season, West Ham left Upton Park and moved into the Olympic Stadium (Renamed The London Stadium), which now has a revised capacity of 60,000, and is designed with retractable seating so the athletics track can still be used.\n\n===Wolverhampton Wanderers===\n\n* Stadium: [[Molineux Stadium]]\n* Capacity: 32,050<ref name=\":0\" />\n*''Current stadium status'': Reconstructed.\n\nPlans were announced in May 2010 to expand the capacity of [[Molineux Stadium|Molineux]] by the 2014\u201315 season from 29,303 to 36,000, with work beginning at the end of the 2010\u201311 season on the replacement of the Stan Cullis Stand. The new Stan Cullis Stand was completed at the end of the 2011\u201312 season, raising the stadium's capacity to approximately 31,700.<ref name=\"Wolves.co.uk\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wolves.co.uk/page/News/0,,10307~2581694,00.html |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120620051640/http://www.wolves.co.uk/page/News/0%2C%2C10307~2581694%2C00.html |archivedate=20 June 2012 |title=Wolves To Postpone Steve Bull Stand Redevelopment |publisher=Wolverhampton Wanderers FC |date=20 January 2012 |accessdate=13 October 2013 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> In January 2012 the club announced that the redevelopment of the Steve Bull Stand, which had been set to begin in 2012, had been postponed.<ref name=\"Wolves.co.uk\" /> The Jack Harris Stand and Billy Wright Stand will also remain unchanged until the club indicates otherwise.\n\nTwo of the stadium's four current stands were built in the early 1990s. The original Stan Cullis Stand was also built at this juncture (replacing the old North Bank Stand terraces), but was replaced itself in 2011\u201312 after just two decades use.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.shropshirestar.com/video/2012/08/10/wolves-unveil-new-stan-cullis-stand/|title=Wolves unveil new Stan Cullis stand|newspaper=[[Shropshire Star]]|date=10 August 2012 |accessdate=21 January 2019}}</ref> The Steve Bull Stand, currently the oldest part of the stadium, was built in 1979. With the completion of three new stands in 1993, in addition to the one opened just fourteen years earlier, Molineux was at the time one of the largest club stadiums in England, but has since been eclipsed by many other clubs who have relocated to new stadiums or expanded their existing ones.\n\n== Premier League Stadium Expanded Capacity ==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! width=\"20\" | Rank\n! width=\"150\" | Stadium\n! width=\"65\" | Capacity\n! width=\"125\" | Club\n! width=\"65\" | Committed Expanded Capacity\n! width=\"20\" | Rank with Expansion\n! Notes\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 1 ||[[Old Trafford]]|| style=\"text-align:center;\" |74,879\n|[[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]]|| || style=\"text-align:center;\" | 1 ||\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 2 ||[[Tottenham Hotspur Stadium]]|| style=\"text-align:center;\" |62,303||[[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]]|| || style=\"text-align:center;\" | 4 || New Stadium\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |3||[[London Stadium]]|| style=\"text-align:center;\" |{{nts|60,000}}||[[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]]||66,000|| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 2 ||\n|-\n\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |4||[[Emirates Stadium]]|| style=\"text-align:center;\" |60,704\n|[[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]]||  || style=\"text-align:center;\" | 6 ||\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 5 ||[[City of Manchester Stadium|Etihad Stadium]]|| style=\"text-align:center;\" |55,017\n|[[Manchester City F.C.|Manches